            Chapter(
                id = "maths_4",
                title = "Quadratic Equations",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Quadratic Equation - Complete Definition:\n\nA quadratic equation is an equation of the form ax¬≤ + bx + c = 0 where:\n‚Ä¢ a, b, c are real numbers\n‚Ä¢ a ‚â† 0 (if a = 0, it becomes linear)\n‚Ä¢ The highest power of variable is 2\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ x¬≤ - 5x + 6 = 0 (a=1, b=-5, c=6)\n‚Ä¢ 2x¬≤ + 3x - 1 = 0 (a=2, b=3, c=-1)\n‚Ä¢ 3x¬≤ - 7 = 0 (a=3, b=0, c=-7)\n\nStandard form requires a ‚â† 0. The term 'quadratic' comes from 'quad' meaning square. This is the most common type of equation after linear equations. Quadratic equations appear in many real-world situations like projectile motion, area problems, and optimization.",
                    
                    "Roots of Quadratic Equation - Detailed Concept:\n\nRoots (or zeroes) are the solutions of ax¬≤ + bx + c = 0.\n\nKey Properties:\n‚Ä¢ A quadratic equation has at most 2 roots\n‚Ä¢ Roots can be real or complex numbers\n‚Ä¢ If Œ± and Œ≤ are roots, then (x - Œ±)(x - Œ≤) = 0\n‚Ä¢ Expanding: x¬≤ - (Œ±+Œ≤)x + Œ±Œ≤ = 0\n‚Ä¢ Comparing with ax¬≤ + bx + c = 0:\n  - Sum of roots: Œ± + Œ≤ = -b/a\n  - Product of roots: Œ±Œ≤ = c/a\n\nExample: For x¬≤ - 5x + 6 = 0:\n‚Ä¢ Roots are 2 and 3\n‚Ä¢ Sum = 2 + 3 = 5 = -(-5)/1 ‚úì\n‚Ä¢ Product = 2 √ó 3 = 6 = 6/1 ‚úì\n\nFinding roots means finding values of x that make the equation true. There are three methods: factorization, completing square, and quadratic formula.",
                    
                    "Discriminant (D) - Nature of Roots:\n\nThe discriminant D = b¬≤ - 4ac determines the nature of roots without solving.\n\nThree Cases:\n\n1. D > 0: Two distinct real roots\n   ‚Ä¢ Parabola cuts x-axis at two different points\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: x¬≤ - 5x + 6 = 0, D = 25-24 = 1 > 0\n   ‚Ä¢ Roots: 2 and 3 (distinct)\n\n2. D = 0: Two equal/coincident real roots\n   ‚Ä¢ Parabola touches x-axis at one point\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: x¬≤ - 4x + 4 = 0, D = 16-16 = 0\n   ‚Ä¢ Root: 2 (repeated)\n\n3. D < 0: No real roots, two complex conjugate roots\n   ‚Ä¢ Parabola doesn't intersect x-axis\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: x¬≤ + x + 1 = 0, D = 1-4 = -3 < 0\n   ‚Ä¢ Roots are complex numbers\n\nThe discriminant is a powerful tool to quickly determine solution type without calculation.",
                    
                    "Quadratic Formula - Universal Method:\n\nThe quadratic formula is: x = (-b ¬± ‚àöD) / 2a\nwhere D = b¬≤ - 4ac (discriminant)\n\nThis formula works for ALL quadratic equations.\n\nThe ¬± sign gives two roots:\n‚Ä¢ x‚ÇÅ = (-b + ‚àöD) / 2a\n‚Ä¢ x‚ÇÇ = (-b - ‚àöD) / 2a\n\nSpecial Case:\nWhen D = 0, both roots are equal: x = -b/2a\n\nDerivation:\nStarting from ax¬≤ + bx + c = 0:\n1. Divide by a: x¬≤ + (b/a)x + c/a = 0\n2. Complete the square: (x + b/2a)¬≤ = (b¬≤-4ac)/4a¬≤\n3. Take square root: x + b/2a = ¬±‚àö(b¬≤-4ac)/2a\n4. Solve: x = (-b ¬± ‚àö(b¬≤-4ac)) / 2a\n\nExample: Solve x¬≤ - 5x + 6 = 0\n‚Ä¢ a=1, b=-5, c=6\n‚Ä¢ D = 25 - 24 = 1\n‚Ä¢ x = (5 ¬± 1) / 2\n‚Ä¢ x‚ÇÅ = 3, x‚ÇÇ = 2\n\nThis is the most reliable method when factorization is difficult.",
                    
                    "Factorization Method - Step-by-Step:\n\nExpress quadratic as product of two linear factors.\n\nIf ax¬≤ + bx + c = a(x - Œ±)(x - Œ≤), then roots are Œ± and Œ≤.\n\nProcess:\n1. Write in standard form: ax¬≤ + bx + c = 0\n2. Find two numbers whose:\n   - Sum = b/a\n   - Product = c/a\n3. Split middle term using these numbers\n4. Factor by grouping\n5. Set each factor = 0 to find roots\n\nExample: x¬≤ - 5x + 6 = 0\n‚Ä¢ Need numbers with sum = 5, product = 6\n‚Ä¢ Numbers: 2 and 3 (since 2+3=5, 2√ó3=6)\n‚Ä¢ x¬≤ - 2x - 3x + 6 = 0\n‚Ä¢ x(x-2) - 3(x-2) = 0\n‚Ä¢ (x-2)(x-3) = 0\n‚Ä¢ Roots: x = 2 or x = 3\n\nWorks best when equation can be easily factorized. Check by expanding factors back.",
                    
                    "Completing the Square Method - Detailed Process:\n\nConvert equation to form (x + p)¬≤ = q\n\nSteps:\n1. Divide by a if a ‚â† 1\n2. Move constant term to right side\n3. Add (b/2a)¬≤ to both sides\n4. Write left side as perfect square\n5. Take square root of both sides\n6. Solve for x\n\nExample: x¬≤ + 6x + 5 = 0\n‚Ä¢ Step 1: Already a=1\n‚Ä¢ Step 2: x¬≤ + 6x = -5\n‚Ä¢ Step 3: Add (6/2)¬≤ = 9 to both sides\n‚Ä¢ x¬≤ + 6x + 9 = -5 + 9\n‚Ä¢ Step 4: (x + 3)¬≤ = 4\n‚Ä¢ Step 5: x + 3 = ¬±2\n‚Ä¢ Step 6: x = -3 ¬± 2\n‚Ä¢ Roots: x = -1 or x = -5\n\nThis method is useful for deriving quadratic formula and understanding the structure of quadratic equations.",
                    
                    "Relationship between Roots and Coefficients:\n\nFor ax¬≤ + bx + c = 0 with roots Œ± and Œ≤:\n\n‚Ä¢ Sum of roots: Œ± + Œ≤ = -b/a\n‚Ä¢ Product of roots: Œ±Œ≤ = c/a\n\nThese relationships are very useful:\n\n1. Forming equations when roots are given:\n   If roots are 2 and 3:\n   ‚Ä¢ Sum = 5, Product = 6\n   ‚Ä¢ Equation: x¬≤ - 5x + 6 = 0\n\n2. Finding expressions:\n   ‚Ä¢ Œ±¬≤ + Œ≤¬≤ = (Œ±+Œ≤)¬≤ - 2Œ±Œ≤\n   ‚Ä¢ Œ±¬≥ + Œ≤¬≥ = (Œ±+Œ≤)¬≥ - 3Œ±Œ≤(Œ±+Œ≤)\n   ‚Ä¢ Œ±/Œ≤ + Œ≤/Œ± = (Œ±¬≤+Œ≤¬≤)/(Œ±Œ≤)\n   ‚Ä¢ |Œ± - Œ≤| = ‚àö[(Œ±+Œ≤)¬≤ - 4Œ±Œ≤] = ‚àöD/a\n\nExample: For x¬≤ - 5x + 6 = 0:\n‚Ä¢ Œ± + Œ≤ = 5, Œ±Œ≤ = 6\n‚Ä¢ Œ±¬≤ + Œ≤¬≤ = 25 - 12 = 13\n‚Ä¢ Œ±¬≥ + Œ≤¬≥ = 125 - 90 = 35\n\nThese relationships help solve many problems without finding actual roots.",
                    
                    "Nature of Roots Based on Discriminant:\n\nD = b¬≤ - 4ac determines nature:\n\n1. D > 0 and D is perfect square:\n   ‚Ä¢ Roots are rational and distinct\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: x¬≤ - 5x + 6 = 0, D = 1 (perfect square)\n   ‚Ä¢ Roots: 2, 3 (rational)\n\n2. D > 0 but not perfect square:\n   ‚Ä¢ Roots are irrational and distinct\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: x¬≤ - 3x + 1 = 0, D = 5 (not perfect square)\n   ‚Ä¢ Roots: (3 ¬± ‚àö5)/2 (irrational)\n\n3. D = 0:\n   ‚Ä¢ Roots are rational and equal\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: x¬≤ - 4x + 4 = 0, D = 0\n   ‚Ä¢ Root: 2 (repeated)\n\n4. D < 0:\n   ‚Ä¢ Roots are complex (non-real)\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: x¬≤ + x + 1 = 0, D = -3\n   ‚Ä¢ Roots: (-1 ¬± i‚àö3)/2 (complex)\n\nThis classification helps understand solution types before solving.",
                    
                    "Word Problems - Systematic Approach:\n\nConvert real-world situations into quadratic equations.\n\nSteps:\n1. Read problem carefully\n2. Identify variable (usually x)\n3. Form equation based on conditions\n4. Solve using any method\n5. Verify answer makes sense\n6. Check all conditions are satisfied\n\nCommon Types:\n\n‚Ä¢ Age Problems:\n  'Product of ages is 12, sum is 7'\n  Let ages be x and (7-x)\n  x(7-x) = 12\n  x¬≤ - 7x + 12 = 0\n  Roots: 3 and 4\n\n‚Ä¢ Number Problems:\n  'Square of number exceeds number by 20'\n  x¬≤ = x + 20\n  x¬≤ - x - 20 = 0\n  Roots: 5 and -4 (reject negative)\n  Answer: 5\n\n‚Ä¢ Area/Perimeter Problems:\n  'Length is 3 more than width, area is 40'\n  Let width = x, length = x+3\n  x(x+3) = 40\n  x¬≤ + 3x - 40 = 0\n  Roots: 5 and -8 (reject negative)\n  Dimensions: 5 √ó 8\n\nPractice with various types builds problem-solving skills.",
                    
                    "Graphical Representation - Visual Understanding:\n\nThe graph of y = ax¬≤ + bx + c is a parabola.\n\nKey Features:\n\n‚Ä¢ Shape:\n  - If a > 0: Parabola opens upward (U-shaped)\n  - If a < 0: Parabola opens downward (‚à©-shaped)\n\n‚Ä¢ Vertex:\n  - Coordinates: (-b/2a, -D/4a)\n  - This is the turning point\n  - Maximum if a < 0, minimum if a > 0\n\n‚Ä¢ Roots:\n  - x-coordinates where parabola intersects x-axis (y = 0)\n  - Number of intersections = number of real roots\n  - If D > 0: Two intersections\n  - If D = 0: One intersection (touching)\n  - If D < 0: No intersection\n\n‚Ä¢ Y-intercept:\n  - Point where x = 0, so y = c\n  - Always at (0, c)\n\nExample: y = x¬≤ - 5x + 6\n‚Ä¢ Opens upward (a=1 > 0)\n‚Ä¢ Vertex at (2.5, -0.25)\n‚Ä¢ Intersects x-axis at x = 2 and x = 3\n‚Ä¢ Y-intercept at (0, 6)\n\nGraph helps visualize solutions and understand behavior."
                ),
                keyPoints = listOf(
                    "Standard Form: ax¬≤ + bx + c = 0 where a ‚â† 0. a, b, c are coefficients (a is leading coefficient). Examples: x¬≤-5x+6=0 (a=1, b=-5, c=6), 2x¬≤+3x-1=0 (a=2, b=3, c=-1). If equation is not in standard form, rearrange it first.",
