            Chapter(
                id = "maths_6",
                title = "Triangles",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Similarity of Triangles - Complete Concept:\n\nTwo triangles are similar if they have the same shape but may differ in size.\n\nDefinition:\nŒîABC ~ ŒîDEF (read as 'triangle ABC is similar to triangle DEF') if:\n\n1. Corresponding angles are equal:\n   ‚Ä¢ ‚à†A = ‚à†D\n   ‚Ä¢ ‚à†B = ‚à†E\n   ‚Ä¢ ‚à†C = ‚à†F\n\n2. Corresponding sides are proportional:\n   ‚Ä¢ AB/DE = BC/EF = AC/DF = k\n   ‚Ä¢ k is called the scale factor\n\nKey Points:\n‚Ä¢ Similar triangles have same shape\n‚Ä¢ Size may be different\n‚Ä¢ Symbol: ~\n‚Ä¢ All equilateral triangles are similar\n‚Ä¢ All congruent triangles are similar (k = 1)\n\nExample:\nIf ŒîABC ~ ŒîDEF with scale factor 2:\n‚Ä¢ AB = 2 √ó DE\n‚Ä¢ BC = 2 √ó EF\n‚Ä¢ AC = 2 √ó DF\n‚Ä¢ Angles are equal\n\nSimilarity is fundamental in geometry and has many practical applications.",
                    
                    "Basic Proportionality Theorem (BPT) - Thales Theorem:\n\nAlso known as Thales Theorem or BPT.\n\nStatement:\nIf a line is drawn parallel to one side of a triangle, it divides the other two sides in the same ratio.\n\nIn ŒîABC, if DE || BC, then:\nAD/DB = AE/EC\n\nProof:\n‚Ä¢ Uses area of triangles\n‚Ä¢ Parallel lines create similar triangles\n‚Ä¢ Areas are proportional\n‚Ä¢ Leads to side ratios\n\nConverse:\nIf a line divides two sides of a triangle in the same ratio, it is parallel to the third side.\n\nIf AD/DB = AE/EC, then DE || BC\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Prove similarity of triangles\n‚Ä¢ Find unknown lengths\n‚Ä¢ Divide line segments in given ratio\n‚Ä¢ Solve geometric problems\n\nExample:\nIn ŒîABC, if DE || BC, AD = 3, DB = 2, AE = 6:\n‚Ä¢ AD/DB = 3/2\n‚Ä¢ AE/EC = 6/EC = 3/2\n‚Ä¢ EC = 4\n\nThis theorem is very useful in solving triangle problems.",
                    
                    "Pythagoras Theorem - Right Triangle Property:\n\nOne of the most important theorems in geometry.\n\nStatement:\nIn a right triangle, the square of the hypotenuse equals the sum of squares of the other two sides.\n\nIf ŒîABC is right-angled at C:\nAB¬≤ = AC¬≤ + BC¬≤\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ AB = Hypotenuse (longest side, opposite right angle)\n‚Ä¢ AC, BC = Other two sides (legs)\n\nConverse:\nIf sides of a triangle satisfy: a¬≤ + b¬≤ = c¬≤, then the triangle is right-angled (with right angle opposite side c).\n\nPythagorean Triplets:\nSets of three positive integers that satisfy Pythagoras theorem:\n‚Ä¢ (3, 4, 5): 3¬≤ + 4¬≤ = 9 + 16 = 25 = 5¬≤\n‚Ä¢ (5, 12, 13): 5¬≤ + 12¬≤ = 25 + 144 = 169 = 13¬≤\n‚Ä¢ (8, 15, 17): 8¬≤ + 15¬≤ = 64 + 225 = 289 = 17¬≤\n‚Ä¢ (7, 24, 25): 7¬≤ + 24¬≤ = 49 + 576 = 625 = 25¬≤\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Find unknown side in right triangle\n‚Ä¢ Check if triangle is right-angled\n‚Ä¢ Solve distance problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in construction, navigation\n\nExample:\nIf two sides are 6 cm and 8 cm:\n‚Ä¢ Hypotenuse¬≤ = 6¬≤ + 8¬≤ = 36 + 64 = 100\n‚Ä¢ Hypotenuse = ‚àö100 = 10 cm\n\nThis theorem has countless applications in mathematics and real life.",
                    
                    "Criteria for Similarity - Three Methods:\n\nThree criteria to prove triangles are similar:\n\n1. AAA (Angle-Angle-Angle):\n   ‚Ä¢ If three angles of one triangle equal three angles of another\n   ‚Ä¢ Triangles are similar\n   ‚Ä¢ Actually, AA is sufficient (if two angles equal, third automatically equal)\n   ‚Ä¢ Most commonly used\n\n2. SSS (Side-Side-Side):\n   ‚Ä¢ If three sides of one triangle are proportional to three sides of another\n   ‚Ä¢ AB/DE = BC/EF = AC/DF\n   ‚Ä¢ Then triangles are similar\n\n3. SAS (Side-Angle-Side):\n   ‚Ä¢ If two sides are proportional and included angle is equal\n   ‚Ä¢ AB/DE = AC/DF and ‚à†A = ‚à†D\n   ‚Ä¢ Then triangles are similar\n\nNote:\n‚Ä¢ For similarity: Sides proportional\n‚Ä¢ For congruence: Sides equal\n‚Ä¢ Similarity is weaker condition than congruence\n\nExample:\nTo prove ŒîABC ~ ŒîDEF:\n‚Ä¢ Check if ‚à†A = ‚à†D, ‚à†B = ‚à†E (AAA)\n‚Ä¢ Or check if AB/DE = BC/EF = AC/DF (SSS)\n‚Ä¢ Or check if AB/DE = AC/DF and ‚à†A = ‚à†D (SAS)\n\nThese criteria help prove similarity in geometric problems.",
                    
                    "Areas of Similar Triangles - Important Relationship:\n\nIf two triangles are similar, their areas have a specific relationship.\n\nTheorem:\nIf two triangles are similar with ratio of corresponding sides = k, then:\n\nRatio of areas = k¬≤\n\nExample:\nIf sides are in ratio 2:3:\n‚Ä¢ Side ratio = 2:3 = k\n‚Ä¢ Area ratio = 2¬≤:3¬≤ = 4:9\n\nIf area ratio is given:\n‚Ä¢ Side ratio = ‚àö(area ratio)\n‚Ä¢ If areas in ratio 9:16, sides in ratio 3:4\n\nOther Ratios:\n‚Ä¢ Perimeter ratio = Side ratio = k\n‚Ä¢ Altitude ratio = Side ratio = k\n‚Ä¢ Median ratio = Side ratio = k\n‚Ä¢ Angle bisector ratio = Side ratio = k\n\nProof:\n‚Ä¢ Uses formula: Area = ¬Ω √ó base √ó height\n‚Ä¢ Heights are in ratio k\n‚Ä¢ Bases are in ratio k\n‚Ä¢ Area = ¬Ω √ó (k √ó base) √ó (k √ó height) = k¬≤ √ó original area\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Find area when similarity is known\n‚Ä¢ Compare areas of similar figures\n‚Ä¢ Solve scale problems\n\nExample:\nIf two similar triangles have sides 5 cm and 10 cm:\n‚Ä¢ Scale factor = 10/5 = 2\n‚Ä¢ If smaller area = 12 cm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Larger area = 12 √ó 2¬≤ = 12 √ó 4 = 48 cm¬≤\n\nThis relationship is crucial in geometry.",
                    
                    "Right Triangle Similarity - Altitude Property:\n\nSpecial property of right triangles with altitude.\n\nTheorem:\nIf altitude is drawn to the hypotenuse of a right triangle, it creates two smaller triangles that are:\n‚Ä¢ Similar to the original triangle\n‚Ä¢ Similar to each other\n\nIn right ŒîABC, right-angled at C:\nIf CD is altitude to hypotenuse AB:\n‚Ä¢ ŒîACD ~ ŒîABC\n‚Ä¢ ŒîBCD ~ ŒîABC\n‚Ä¢ ŒîACD ~ ŒîBCD\n\nImportant Relationships:\n\n1. (Altitude)¬≤ = Product of segments of hypotenuse:\n   CD¬≤ = AD √ó BD\n\n2. (Side)¬≤ = (Segment of hypotenuse) √ó (Entire hypotenuse):\n   AC¬≤ = AD √ó AB\n   BC¬≤ = BD √ó AB\n\nProof:\n‚Ä¢ Uses AAA similarity\n‚Ä¢ Right angles are equal\n‚Ä¢ Common angles\n‚Ä¢ Leads to similarity\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Geometric proofs\n‚Ä¢ Finding lengths\n‚Ä¢ Solving right triangle problems\n‚Ä¢ Construction problems\n\nExample:\nIn right triangle, if altitude divides hypotenuse into 4 cm and 9 cm:\n‚Ä¢ Altitude¬≤ = 4 √ó 9 = 36\n‚Ä¢ Altitude = 6 cm\n\nThis property is very useful in right triangle problems.",
                    
                    "Midpoint Theorem - Important Property:\n\nTheorem about line joining midpoints of triangle sides.\n\nStatement:\nThe line segment joining the midpoints of two sides of a triangle is:\n‚Ä¢ Parallel to the third side\n‚Ä¢ Half the length of the third side\n\nIn ŒîABC:\nIf D is midpoint of AB and E is midpoint of AC:\n‚Ä¢ DE || BC\n‚Ä¢ DE = ¬Ω BC\n\nConverse:\nIf a line through the midpoint of one side is parallel to another side, it bisects the third side.\n\nProof:\n‚Ä¢ Uses Basic Proportionality Theorem\n‚Ä¢ Shows DE divides sides in ratio 1:1\n‚Ä¢ Therefore parallel and half length\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Prove lines are parallel\n‚Ä¢ Find lengths in triangles\n‚Ä¢ Construction problems\n‚Ä¢ Geometric proofs\n\nExample:\nIn ŒîABC, if D and E are midpoints of AB and AC:\n‚Ä¢ If BC = 10 cm, then DE = 5 cm\n‚Ä¢ DE is parallel to BC\n\nExtension:\n‚Ä¢ Line joining midpoints of all three sides forms medial triangle\n‚Ä¢ Medial triangle is similar to original (scale factor ¬Ω)\n‚Ä¢ Area of medial triangle = ¬º area of original\n\nThis theorem is frequently used in geometry problems.",
                    
                    "Applications of Similarity - Real-World Uses:\n\nSimilarity has many practical applications:\n\n1. Scale Drawings and Maps:\n   ‚Ä¢ Maps use scale factors\n   ‚Ä¢ 1 cm on map = actual distance\n   ‚Ä¢ Similar figures with known scale\n\n2. Shadow Problems:\n   ‚Ä¢ Find height of objects using shadows\n   ‚Ä¢ Similar triangles formed\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Height of tree using shadow\n\n3. Mirror Problems:\n   ‚Ä¢ Reflection creates similar triangles\n   ‚Ä¢ Find distances or heights\n\n4. Finding Heights:\n   ‚Ä¢ Inaccessible heights\n   ‚Ä¢ Use similar triangles\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Height of building\n\n5. Geometric Proofs:\n   ‚Ä¢ Prove geometric relationships\n   ‚Ä¢ Use similarity criteria\n\n6. Calculating Unknown Lengths:\n   ‚Ä¢ When similarity is known\n   ‚Ä¢ Use proportions\n\n7. Architectural and Engineering:\n   ‚Ä¢ Scale models\n   ‚Ä¢ Blueprints\n   ‚Ä¢ Design applications\n\n8. Photography:\n   ‚Ä¢ Similar images\n   ‚Ä¢ Scaling and resizing\n\nExample - Shadow Problem:\nIf a 6 ft person casts 4 ft shadow, and tree casts 20 ft shadow:\n‚Ä¢ Height of tree = (6/4) √ó 20 = 30 ft\n‚Ä¢ Uses similarity of triangles\n\nSimilarity is fundamental in many fields.",
                    
                    "Properties of Similar Triangles - Complete List:\n\nIf two triangles are similar, many properties are proportional:\n\n1. Angles:\n   ‚Ä¢ Corresponding angles are equal\n   ‚Ä¢ Shape is identical\n\n2. Sides:\n   ‚Ä¢ Corresponding sides are proportional\n   ‚Ä¢ Ratio = scale factor k\n\n3. Perimeters:\n   ‚Ä¢ Perimeter ratio = Side ratio = k\n   ‚Ä¢ If sides in ratio 2:3, perimeters in ratio 2:3\n\n4. Areas:\n   ‚Ä¢ Area ratio = (Side ratio)¬≤ = k¬≤\n   ‚Ä¢ If sides in ratio 2:3, areas in ratio 4:9\n\n5. Altitudes:\n   ‚Ä¢ Altitude ratio = Side ratio = k\n   ‚Ä¢ Corresponding altitudes are proportional\n\n6. Medians:\n   ‚Ä¢ Median ratio = Side ratio = k\n   ‚Ä¢ Corresponding medians are proportional\n\n7. Angle Bisectors:\n   ‚Ä¢ Angle bisector ratio = Side ratio = k\n   ‚Ä¢ Corresponding bisectors are proportional\n\n8. Inradius and Circumradius:\n   ‚Ä¢ Also proportional\n   ‚Ä¢ Ratio = Side ratio = k\n\nImportant:\n‚Ä¢ All linear measurements: Ratio = k\n‚Ä¢ All area measurements: Ratio = k¬≤\n‚Ä¢ All volume measurements: Ratio = k¬≥ (for 3D)\n\nThese properties help solve many geometric problems efficiently.",
                    
                    "Solving Triangle Problems - Step-by-Step Method:\n\nSystematic approach to solve similarity problems:\n\nStep 1: Identify Similar Triangles\n‚Ä¢ Look for parallel lines\n‚Ä¢ Look for equal angles\n‚Ä¢ Check given conditions\n‚Ä¢ Use similarity criteria (AAA, SSS, SAS)\n\nStep 2: Set Up Proportions\n‚Ä¢ Write corresponding sides in proportion\n‚Ä¢ AB/DE = BC/EF = AC/DF\n‚Ä¢ Use given values\n\nStep 3: Cross-Multiply\n‚Ä¢ Solve for unknown\n‚Ä¢ Use algebraic manipulation\n‚Ä¢ Find the value\n\nStep 4: Verify Answer\n‚Ä¢ Check if ratios are equal\n‚Ä¢ Verify with given conditions\n‚Ä¢ Ensure answer makes sense\n\nStep 5: Use Area Relationships (if needed)\n‚Ä¢ If area given, use area ratio = k¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Find side ratio from area ratio\n‚Ä¢ Apply to find unknown\n\nStep 6: Apply Pythagoras (if right triangle)\n‚Ä¢ Use a¬≤ + b¬≤ = c¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Find missing side\n‚Ä¢ Combine with similarity\n\nExample:\nGiven: ŒîABC ~ ŒîDEF, AB = 6, DE = 4, BC = 9, find EF:\n‚Ä¢ AB/DE = BC/EF\n‚Ä¢ 6/4 = 9/EF\n‚Ä¢ EF = (4 √ó 9)/6 = 6\n\nPractice with various problems to master these techniques."
                ),
