            Chapter(
                id = "maths_7",
                title = "Coordinate Geometry",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Distance Formula - Finding Distance Between Points:\n\nThe distance formula finds the length between two points in coordinate plane.\n\nFormula:\nd = ‚àö[(x‚ÇÇ - x‚ÇÅ)¬≤ + (y‚ÇÇ - y‚ÇÅ)¬≤]\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ (x‚ÇÅ, y‚ÇÅ) = Coordinates of first point\n‚Ä¢ (x‚ÇÇ, y‚ÇÇ) = Coordinates of second point\n‚Ä¢ d = Distance between points\n\nDerivation:\n‚Ä¢ Uses Pythagoras theorem\n‚Ä¢ Forms right triangle\n‚Ä¢ Horizontal distance = |x‚ÇÇ - x‚ÇÅ|\n‚Ä¢ Vertical distance = |y‚ÇÇ - y‚ÇÅ|\n‚Ä¢ Distance = ‚àö[(horizontal)¬≤ + (vertical)¬≤]\n\nExample:\nDistance between (2, 3) and (5, 7):\n‚Ä¢ d = ‚àö[(5-2)¬≤ + (7-3)¬≤]\n‚Ä¢ d = ‚àö[3¬≤ + 4¬≤]\n‚Ä¢ d = ‚àö[9 + 16]\n‚Ä¢ d = ‚àö25 = 5 units\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Always positive\n‚Ä¢ Distance from A to B = Distance from B to A\n‚Ä¢ Distance from point to itself = 0\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Find length of line segment\n‚Ä¢ Check if points form right triangle\n‚Ä¢ Verify collinearity\n‚Ä¢ Solve geometric problems\n\nThis formula is fundamental in coordinate geometry.",
                    
                    "Section Formula (Internal Division) - Dividing Line Segment:\n\nThe section formula finds coordinates of a point dividing a line segment internally.\n\nFormula:\nP = ((mx‚ÇÇ + nx‚ÇÅ)/(m + n), (my‚ÇÇ + ny‚ÇÅ)/(m + n))\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ A(x‚ÇÅ, y‚ÇÅ) and B(x‚ÇÇ, y‚ÇÇ) are endpoints\n‚Ä¢ P divides AB internally in ratio m:n\n‚Ä¢ Point P lies between A and B\n\nSpecial Case - Midpoint:\nWhen m = n = 1:\n‚Ä¢ P = ((x‚ÇÅ + x‚ÇÇ)/2, (y‚ÇÅ + y‚ÇÇ)/2)\n‚Ä¢ This is the midpoint formula\n\nExample:\nPoint dividing (1, 2) and (4, 8) in ratio 1:2:\n‚Ä¢ x = (1√ó4 + 2√ó1)/(1 + 2) = (4 + 2)/3 = 6/3 = 2\n‚Ä¢ y = (1√ó8 + 2√ó2)/(1 + 2) = (8 + 4)/3 = 12/3 = 4\n‚Ä¢ Point is (2, 4)\n\nVerification:\n‚Ä¢ Distance AP : Distance PB = 1:2 ‚úì\n‚Ä¢ Point lies between A and B ‚úì\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Find point dividing segment in given ratio\n‚Ä¢ Locate specific points on line\n‚Ä¢ Solve geometric problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in construction and design",
                    
                    "Section Formula (External Division) - Point Outside Segment:\n\nThe section formula for external division finds coordinates when point lies outside the line segment.\n\nFormula:\nP = ((mx‚ÇÇ - nx‚ÇÅ)/(m - n), (my‚ÇÇ - ny‚ÇÅ)/(m - n))\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ A(x‚ÇÅ, y‚ÇÅ) and B(x‚ÇÇ, y‚ÇÇ) are endpoints\n‚Ä¢ P divides AB externally in ratio m:n\n‚Ä¢ Point P lies outside the line segment\n‚Ä¢ m ‚â† n (otherwise division by zero)\n\nKey Difference:\n‚Ä¢ Internal: Point between A and B\n‚Ä¢ External: Point outside A and B\n‚Ä¢ Internal: (m + n) in denominator\n‚Ä¢ External: (m - n) in denominator\n\nExample:\nPoint dividing (1, 2) and (4, 8) externally in ratio 3:1:\n‚Ä¢ x = (3√ó4 - 1√ó1)/(3 - 1) = (12 - 1)/2 = 11/2 = 5.5\n‚Ä¢ y = (3√ó8 - 1√ó2)/(3 - 1) = (24 - 2)/2 = 22/2 = 11\n‚Ä¢ Point is (5.5, 11)\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Find point outside segment\n‚Ä¢ Solve specific geometric problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in advanced coordinate geometry\n\nLess common than internal division but important for complete understanding.",
                    
                    "Midpoint Formula - Center Point of Segment:\n\nThe midpoint formula finds the center point of a line segment.\n\nFormula:\nM = ((x‚ÇÅ + x‚ÇÇ)/2, (y‚ÇÅ + y‚ÇÇ)/2)\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ (x‚ÇÅ, y‚ÇÅ) and (x‚ÇÇ, y‚ÇÇ) are endpoints\n‚Ä¢ M is the midpoint\n‚Ä¢ Divides segment into two equal parts\n\nDerivation:\n‚Ä¢ Special case of section formula\n‚Ä¢ When m:n = 1:1\n‚Ä¢ Point divides segment equally\n\nExample:\nMidpoint of (3, 4) and (7, 10):\n‚Ä¢ x = (3 + 7)/2 = 10/2 = 5\n‚Ä¢ y = (4 + 10)/2 = 14/2 = 7\n‚Ä¢ Midpoint is (5, 7)\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Equidistant from both endpoints\n‚Ä¢ Divides segment in ratio 1:1\n‚Ä¢ Always lies on the segment\n‚Ä¢ Used to find center of figures\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Find center of line segment\n‚Ä¢ Locate center of geometric figures\n‚Ä¢ Solve symmetry problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in construction\n\nThis is one of the most commonly used formulas in coordinate geometry.",
                    
                    "Area of Triangle - Using Coordinates:\n\nThe area formula finds area of triangle when vertices are known.\n\nFormula:\nA = ¬Ω |x‚ÇÅ(y‚ÇÇ - y‚ÇÉ) + x‚ÇÇ(y‚ÇÉ - y‚ÇÅ) + x‚ÇÉ(y‚ÇÅ - y‚ÇÇ)|\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ (x‚ÇÅ, y‚ÇÅ), (x‚ÇÇ, y‚ÇÇ), (x‚ÇÉ, y‚ÇÉ) are vertices\n‚Ä¢ A = Area of triangle\n‚Ä¢ | | = Absolute value (ensures positive)\n\nImportant:\n‚Ä¢ Absolute value ensures area is always positive\n‚Ä¢ Order of vertices matters (clockwise or anticlockwise)\n‚Ä¢ If area = 0, points are collinear\n\nExample:\nArea of triangle (0, 0), (4, 0), (0, 3):\n‚Ä¢ A = ¬Ω |0(0-3) + 4(3-0) + 0(0-0)|\n‚Ä¢ A = ¬Ω |0 + 12 + 0|\n‚Ä¢ A = ¬Ω √ó 12 = 6 sq units\n\nVerification:\n‚Ä¢ Base = 4, Height = 3\n‚Ä¢ Area = ¬Ω √ó 4 √ó 3 = 6 ‚úì\n\nSpecial Cases:\n‚Ä¢ If area = 0: Points are collinear\n‚Ä¢ Right triangle: Can use simpler method\n‚Ä¢ Equilateral: Special formulas\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Find area when coordinates known\n‚Ä¢ Check collinearity\n‚Ä¢ Solve geometric problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in surveying and mapping",
                    
                    "Collinearity of Points - Checking if Points Lie on Same Line:\n\nThree or more points are collinear if they lie on the same straight line.\n\nMethod 1: Using Area:\n‚Ä¢ If area of triangle = 0, points are collinear\n‚Ä¢ A = ¬Ω |x‚ÇÅ(y‚ÇÇ-y‚ÇÉ) + x‚ÇÇ(y‚ÇÉ-y‚ÇÅ) + x‚ÇÉ(y‚ÇÅ-y‚ÇÇ)| = 0\n\nMethod 2: Using Slope:\n‚Ä¢ If slope of AB = slope of BC, points are collinear\n‚Ä¢ m(AB) = (y‚ÇÇ-y‚ÇÅ)/(x‚ÇÇ-x‚ÇÅ)\n‚Ä¢ m(BC) = (y‚ÇÉ-y‚ÇÇ)/(x‚ÇÉ-x‚ÇÇ)\n‚Ä¢ If m(AB) = m(BC), then collinear\n\nExample:\nCheck if (1, 2), (2, 4), (3, 6) are collinear:\n\nUsing Area:\n‚Ä¢ A = ¬Ω |1(4-6) + 2(6-2) + 3(2-4)|\n‚Ä¢ A = ¬Ω |-2 + 8 - 6| = ¬Ω |0| = 0\n‚Ä¢ Points are collinear ‚úì\n\nUsing Slope:\n‚Ä¢ m(AB) = (4-2)/(2-1) = 2/1 = 2\n‚Ä¢ m(BC) = (6-4)/(3-2) = 2/1 = 2\n‚Ä¢ Slopes equal, so collinear ‚úì\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Verify geometric constructions\n‚Ä¢ Check alignment\n‚Ä¢ Solve coordinate problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in computer graphics",
                    
                    "Centroid of Triangle - Center of Mass:\n\nThe centroid is the point of intersection of medians of a triangle.\n\nFormula:\nG = ((x‚ÇÅ + x‚ÇÇ + x‚ÇÉ)/3, (y‚ÇÅ + y‚ÇÇ + y‚ÇÉ)/3)\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ (x‚ÇÅ, y‚ÇÅ), (x‚ÇÇ, y‚ÇÇ), (x‚ÇÉ, y‚ÇÉ) are vertices\n‚Ä¢ G is the centroid\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Divides each median in ratio 2:1\n‚Ä¢ Always lies inside the triangle\n‚Ä¢ Center of mass (balance point)\n‚Ä¢ Coordinates are average of vertices\n\nExample:\nCentroid of triangle (0, 0), (6, 0), (0, 9):\n‚Ä¢ x = (0 + 6 + 0)/3 = 6/3 = 2\n‚Ä¢ y = (0 + 0 + 9)/3 = 9/3 = 3\n‚Ä¢ Centroid is (2, 3)\n\nVerification:\n‚Ä¢ Median from (0, 0) to midpoint of (6,0) and (0,9)\n‚Ä¢ Midpoint = (3, 4.5)\n‚Ä¢ Centroid divides in ratio 2:1 ‚úì\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Find center of mass\n‚Ä¢ Solve geometric problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in physics and engineering\n‚Ä¢ Construction and design\n\nThe centroid is an important point in triangle geometry.",
                    
                    "Slope of Line - Steepness and Direction:\n\nThe slope measures the steepness and direction of a line.\n\nFormula:\nm = (y‚ÇÇ - y‚ÇÅ)/(x‚ÇÇ - x‚ÇÅ)\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ (x‚ÇÅ, y‚ÇÅ) and (x‚ÇÇ, y‚ÇÇ) are two points on line\n‚Ä¢ m = Slope\n\nInterpretation:\n‚Ä¢ m > 0: Line rises (left to right)\n‚Ä¢ m < 0: Line falls (left to right)\n‚Ä¢ m = 0: Horizontal line\n‚Ä¢ m = undefined: Vertical line (x‚ÇÇ = x‚ÇÅ)\n\nSpecial Cases:\n‚Ä¢ Horizontal line: m = 0\n‚Ä¢ Vertical line: m = undefined (division by zero)\n‚Ä¢ 45¬∞ line: m = 1 or -1\n\nParallel Lines:\n‚Ä¢ Have equal slopes\n‚Ä¢ m‚ÇÅ = m‚ÇÇ\n\nPerpendicular Lines:\n‚Ä¢ Product of slopes = -1\n‚Ä¢ m‚ÇÅ √ó m‚ÇÇ = -1\n‚Ä¢ If m‚ÇÅ = 2, then m‚ÇÇ = -¬Ω\n\nExample:\nSlope of line through (2, 3) and (5, 9):\n‚Ä¢ m = (9 - 3)/(5 - 2) = 6/3 = 2\n‚Ä¢ Line rises (positive slope)\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Describe line direction\n‚Ä¢ Find parallel/perpendicular lines\n‚Ä¢ Solve geometric problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in calculus and physics\n\nSlope is fundamental in understanding linear relationships.",
                    
                    "Applications of Coordinate Geometry - Real-World Uses:\n\nCoordinate geometry has many practical applications:\n\n1. Finding Distances and Areas:\n   ‚Ä¢ Calculate lengths\n   ‚Ä¢ Find areas of regions\n   ‚Ä¢ Measure distances on maps\n\n2. Locating Points:\n   ‚Ä¢ GPS coordinates\n   ‚Ä¢ Map reading\n   ‚Ä¢ Navigation systems\n\n3. Proving Geometric Properties:\n   ‚Ä¢ Verify theorems\n   ‚Ä¢ Prove relationships\n   ‚Ä¢ Solve geometric problems\n\n4. Solving Problems:\n   ‚Ä¢ Lines and curves\n   ‚Ä¢ Intersection points\n   ‚Ä¢ Optimization problems\n\n5. Navigation and GPS:\n   ‚Ä¢ Location tracking\n   ‚Ä¢ Route planning\n   ‚Ä¢ Distance calculations\n\n6. Computer Graphics:\n   ‚Ä¢ Drawing shapes\n   ‚Ä¢ Transformations\n   ‚Ä¢ Animation\n\n7. Architectural Planning:\n   ‚Ä¢ Building design\n   ‚Ä¢ Layout planning\n   ‚Ä¢ Measurements\n\n8. Map Reading:\n   ‚Ä¢ Coordinates on maps\n   ‚Ä¢ Distance calculations\n   ‚Ä¢ Location finding\n\n9. Engineering:\n   ‚Ä¢ Design calculations\n   ‚Ä¢ Structural analysis\n   ‚Ä¢ Surveying\n\n10. Science:\n    ‚Ä¢ Physics: Motion graphs\n    ‚Ä¢ Chemistry: Molecular structures\n    ‚Ä¢ Biology: Growth curves\n\nCoordinate geometry connects algebra and geometry, making it powerful for solving real-world problems.",
                    
                    "Important Formulas Summary - Quick Reference:\n\nAll essential coordinate geometry formulas:\n\n1. Distance Formula:\n   d = ‚àö[(x‚ÇÇ - x‚ÇÅ)¬≤ + (y‚ÇÇ - y‚ÇÅ)¬≤]\n\n2. Midpoint Formula:\n   M = ((x‚ÇÅ + x‚ÇÇ)/2, (y‚ÇÅ + y‚ÇÇ)/2)\n\n3. Section Formula (Internal):\n   P = ((mx‚ÇÇ + nx‚ÇÅ)/(m + n), (my‚ÇÇ + ny‚ÇÅ)/(m + n))\n\n4. Section Formula (External):\n   P = ((mx‚ÇÇ - nx‚ÇÅ)/(m - n), (my‚ÇÇ - ny‚ÇÅ)/(m - n))\n\n5. Area of Triangle:\n   A = ¬Ω |x‚ÇÅ(y‚ÇÇ - y‚ÇÉ) + x‚ÇÇ(y‚ÇÉ - y‚ÇÅ) + x‚ÇÉ(y‚ÇÅ - y‚ÇÇ)|\n\n6. Centroid of Triangle:\n   G = ((x‚ÇÅ + x‚ÇÇ + x‚ÇÉ)/3, (y‚ÇÅ + y‚ÇÇ + y‚ÇÉ)/3)\n\n7. Slope of Line:\n   m = (y‚ÇÇ - y‚ÇÅ)/(x‚ÇÇ - x‚ÇÅ)\n\n8. Collinearity:\n   ‚Ä¢ Area = 0, or\n   ‚Ä¢ Slope(AB) = Slope(BC)\n\n9. Parallel Lines:\n   m‚ÇÅ = m‚ÇÇ\n\n10. Perpendicular Lines:\n    m‚ÇÅ √ó m‚ÇÇ = -1\n\nMemorize these formulas for quick problem solving!"
