            Chapter(
                id = "maths_8",
                title = "Introduction to Trigonometry",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Trigonometric Ratios - Complete Definition:\n\nIn a right triangle, trigonometric ratios relate angles to sides.\n\nFor angle Œ∏ in right triangle:\n\n1. Sine (sin):\n   sin Œ∏ = Opposite side / Hypotenuse\n   ‚Ä¢ Ratio of opposite to hypotenuse\n\n2. Cosine (cos):\n   cos Œ∏ = Adjacent side / Hypotenuse\n   ‚Ä¢ Ratio of adjacent to hypotenuse\n\n3. Tangent (tan):\n   tan Œ∏ = Opposite side / Adjacent side\n   ‚Ä¢ Ratio of opposite to adjacent\n\nMnemonic: SOH CAH TOA\n‚Ä¢ SOH: Sine = Opposite/Hypotenuse\n‚Ä¢ CAH: Cosine = Adjacent/Hypotenuse\n‚Ä¢ TOA: Tangent = Opposite/Adjacent\n\nKey Properties:\n‚Ä¢ Ratios depend only on angle, not triangle size\n‚Ä¢ Same angle ‚Üí same ratios (regardless of triangle size)\n‚Ä¢ Ratios are dimensionless (pure numbers)\n\nExample:\nIn triangle with sides 3, 4, 5:\n‚Ä¢ If angle opposite to 3 is Œ∏:\n  - sin Œ∏ = 3/5\n  - cos Œ∏ = 4/5\n  - tan Œ∏ = 3/4\n\nThese ratios are fundamental in trigonometry.",
                    
                    "Reciprocal Trigonometric Ratios - Complete Set:\n\nThree more ratios are reciprocals of basic ratios:\n\n1. Cosecant (cosec):\n   cosec Œ∏ = 1/sin Œ∏ = Hypotenuse / Opposite\n   ‚Ä¢ Reciprocal of sine\n\n2. Secant (sec):\n   sec Œ∏ = 1/cos Œ∏ = Hypotenuse / Adjacent\n   ‚Ä¢ Reciprocal of cosine\n\n3. Cotangent (cot):\n   cot Œ∏ = 1/tan Œ∏ = Adjacent / Opposite\n   ‚Ä¢ Reciprocal of tangent\n\nRelationships:\n‚Ä¢ sin Œ∏ √ó cosec Œ∏ = 1\n‚Ä¢ cos Œ∏ √ó sec Œ∏ = 1\n‚Ä¢ tan Œ∏ √ó cot Œ∏ = 1\n\nExample:\nIf sin Œ∏ = 3/5:\n‚Ä¢ cosec Œ∏ = 1/(3/5) = 5/3\n‚Ä¢ If cos Œ∏ = 4/5:\n  sec Œ∏ = 1/(4/5) = 5/4\n‚Ä¢ If tan Œ∏ = 3/4:\n  cot Œ∏ = 1/(3/4) = 4/3\n\nImportant:\n‚Ä¢ Reciprocal of reciprocal gives original ratio\n‚Ä¢ Used in solving equations\n‚Ä¢ Helpful in simplifying expressions\n\nThese ratios complete the set of six trigonometric ratios.",
                    
                    "Fundamental Trigonometric Identities - Essential Formulas:\n\nThese identities are always true for any angle Œ∏:\n\n1. sin¬≤Œ∏ + cos¬≤Œ∏ = 1\n   ‚Ä¢ Most important identity\n   ‚Ä¢ Derived from Pythagoras theorem\n   ‚Ä¢ Always true\n\n2. 1 + tan¬≤Œ∏ = sec¬≤Œ∏\n   ‚Ä¢ Derived from first identity\n   ‚Ä¢ Divide sin¬≤Œ∏ + cos¬≤Œ∏ = 1 by cos¬≤Œ∏\n\n3. 1 + cot¬≤Œ∏ = cosec¬≤Œ∏\n   ‚Ä¢ Derived from first identity\n   ‚Ä¢ Divide sin¬≤Œ∏ + cos¬≤Œ∏ = 1 by sin¬≤Œ∏\n\nDerivation of First Identity:\n‚Ä¢ In right triangle: (Opposite)¬≤ + (Adjacent)¬≤ = (Hypotenuse)¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Divide by (Hypotenuse)¬≤:\n  (Opp/Hyp)¬≤ + (Adj/Hyp)¬≤ = 1\n  sin¬≤Œ∏ + cos¬≤Œ∏ = 1 ‚úì\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Simplify complex expressions\n‚Ä¢ Prove other identities\n‚Ä¢ Find one ratio when another is known\n‚Ä¢ Solve equations\n\nExample:\nIf sin Œ∏ = 4/5:\n‚Ä¢ sin¬≤Œ∏ = 16/25\n‚Ä¢ cos¬≤Œ∏ = 1 - 16/25 = 9/25\n‚Ä¢ cos Œ∏ = 3/5 (taking positive value for acute angle)\n\nThese identities are fundamental tools in trigonometry.",
                    
                    "Standard Trigonometric Values - Must Memorize:\n\nThese values must be memorized for common angles:\n\nFor 0¬∞:\n‚Ä¢ sin 0¬∞ = 0\n‚Ä¢ cos 0¬∞ = 1\n‚Ä¢ tan 0¬∞ = 0\n\nFor 30¬∞:\n‚Ä¢ sin 30¬∞ = 1/2\n‚Ä¢ cos 30¬∞ = ‚àö3/2\n‚Ä¢ tan 30¬∞ = 1/‚àö3\n\nFor 45¬∞:\n‚Ä¢ sin 45¬∞ = 1/‚àö2\n‚Ä¢ cos 45¬∞ = 1/‚àö2\n‚Ä¢ tan 45¬∞ = 1\n\nFor 60¬∞:\n‚Ä¢ sin 60¬∞ = ‚àö3/2\n‚Ä¢ cos 60¬∞ = 1/2\n‚Ä¢ tan 60¬∞ = ‚àö3\n\nFor 90¬∞:\n‚Ä¢ sin 90¬∞ = 1\n‚Ä¢ cos 90¬∞ = 0\n‚Ä¢ tan 90¬∞ = undefined (division by zero)\n\nPattern:\n‚Ä¢ Cos values are reverse of sin values\n‚Ä¢ sin 0¬∞ = 0, cos 0¬∞ = 1\n‚Ä¢ sin 30¬∞ = 1/2, cos 60¬∞ = 1/2\n‚Ä¢ sin 45¬∞ = cos 45¬∞ = 1/‚àö2\n‚Ä¢ sin 60¬∞ = ‚àö3/2, cos 30¬∞ = ‚àö3/2\n‚Ä¢ sin 90¬∞ = 1, cos 90¬∞ = 0\n\nTan Values:\n‚Ä¢ tan = sin/cos\n‚Ä¢ tan 0¬∞ = 0/1 = 0\n‚Ä¢ tan 30¬∞ = (1/2)/(‚àö3/2) = 1/‚àö3\n‚Ä¢ tan 45¬∞ = (1/‚àö2)/(1/‚àö2) = 1\n‚Ä¢ tan 60¬∞ = (‚àö3/2)/(1/2) = ‚àö3\n‚Ä¢ tan 90¬∞ = 1/0 = undefined\n\nThese values are essential for calculations without calculator.",
                    
                    "Complementary Angles - Special Relationships:\n\nTwo angles whose sum is 90¬∞ are complementary.\n\nIf A + B = 90¬∞, then:\n‚Ä¢ sin A = cos B\n‚Ä¢ cos A = sin B\n‚Ä¢ tan A = cot B\n‚Ä¢ cot A = tan B\n‚Ä¢ sec A = cosec B\n‚Ä¢ cosec A = sec B\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ sin 30¬∞ = cos 60¬∞ = 1/2\n‚Ä¢ sin 45¬∞ = cos 45¬∞ = 1/‚àö2\n‚Ä¢ sin 60¬∞ = cos 30¬∞ = ‚àö3/2\n‚Ä¢ tan 30¬∞ = cot 60¬∞ = 1/‚àö3\n‚Ä¢ tan 45¬∞ = cot 45¬∞ = 1\n\nWhy This Works:\n‚Ä¢ In right triangle, if one angle is A, other acute angle is (90¬∞ - A)\n‚Ä¢ Opposite to A = Adjacent to (90¬∞ - A)\n‚Ä¢ Adjacent to A = Opposite to (90¬∞ - A)\n‚Ä¢ Therefore: sin A = cos(90¬∞ - A)\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Find values of angles\n‚Ä¢ Simplify expressions\n‚Ä¢ Solve problems\n‚Ä¢ Very useful in calculations\n\nExample:\nTo find cos 60¬∞:\n‚Ä¢ Since 60¬∞ + 30¬∞ = 90¬∞\n‚Ä¢ cos 60¬∞ = sin 30¬∞ = 1/2\n\nThis relationship simplifies many trigonometric calculations.",
                    
                    "Trigonometric Ratios of Specific Angles - Complete Table:\n\nComplete values for standard angles:\n\nAngle | sin | cos | tan\n------|-----|-----|-----\n0¬∞    | 0   | 1   | 0\n30¬∞   | 1/2 | ‚àö3/2| 1/‚àö3\n45¬∞   | 1/‚àö2| 1/‚àö2| 1\n60¬∞   | ‚àö3/2| 1/2 | ‚àö3\n90¬∞   | 1   | 0   | undefined\n\nReciprocal Values:\n‚Ä¢ cosec 30¬∞ = 2, sec 30¬∞ = 2/‚àö3, cot 30¬∞ = ‚àö3\n‚Ä¢ cosec 45¬∞ = ‚àö2, sec 45¬∞ = ‚àö2, cot 45¬∞ = 1\n‚Ä¢ cosec 60¬∞ = 2/‚àö3, sec 60¬∞ = 2, cot 60¬∞ = 1/‚àö3\n\nMemorization Tips:\n‚Ä¢ sin values: 0, 1/2, 1/‚àö2, ‚àö3/2, 1\n‚Ä¢ cos values: Reverse of sin\n‚Ä¢ tan = sin/cos\n‚Ä¢ For 45¬∞: sin = cos = 1/‚àö2, tan = 1\n\nThese values form the foundation for:\n‚Ä¢ All trigonometric calculations\n‚Ä¢ Problem solving\n‚Ä¢ Applications\n‚Ä¢ Higher mathematics\n\nMaster these values - they are used constantly!",
                    
                    "Applications of Trigonometric Identities - Problem Solving:\n\nIdentities are powerful tools for solving problems:\n\nUses:\n\n1. Simplify Complex Expressions:\n   ‚Ä¢ Reduce to simpler form\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: sin‚Å¥Œ∏ + cos‚Å¥Œ∏\n     = (sin¬≤Œ∏ + cos¬≤Œ∏)¬≤ - 2sin¬≤Œ∏cos¬≤Œ∏\n     = 1 - 2sin¬≤Œ∏cos¬≤Œ∏\n\n2. Prove Other Identities:\n   ‚Ä¢ Use known identities\n   ‚Ä¢ Show equality\n   ‚Ä¢ Step-by-step proof\n\n3. Solve Equations:\n   ‚Ä¢ Find values of angles\n   ‚Ä¢ Use identities to simplify\n   ‚Ä¢ Solve for unknown\n\n4. Find Unknown Ratios:\n   ‚Ä¢ Given one ratio, find others\n   ‚Ä¢ Use identities\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: If sin Œ∏ = 4/5, find cos Œ∏\n     cos¬≤Œ∏ = 1 - sin¬≤Œ∏ = 1 - 16/25 = 9/25\n     cos Œ∏ = 3/5\n\n5. Convert Between Forms:\n   ‚Ä¢ Express in different ways\n   ‚Ä¢ Simplify expressions\n   ‚Ä¢ Make calculations easier\n\nExample:\nSimplify: (1 - sin¬≤Œ∏)/(1 - cos¬≤Œ∏)\n‚Ä¢ = cos¬≤Œ∏/sin¬≤Œ∏ (using sin¬≤Œ∏ + cos¬≤Œ∏ = 1)\n‚Ä¢ = cot¬≤Œ∏\n\nIdentities make complex problems manageable!",
                    
                    "Relationship between Ratios - Interconnections:\n\nAll trigonometric ratios are interconnected:\n\nBasic Relationships:\n‚Ä¢ tan Œ∏ = sin Œ∏ / cos Œ∏\n‚Ä¢ cot Œ∏ = cos Œ∏ / sin Œ∏\n‚Ä¢ cot Œ∏ = 1 / tan Œ∏\n\nReciprocal Relationships:\n‚Ä¢ sin Œ∏ √ó cosec Œ∏ = 1\n‚Ä¢ cos Œ∏ √ó sec Œ∏ = 1\n‚Ä¢ tan Œ∏ √ó cot Œ∏ = 1\n\nFinding All Ratios from One:\n\nIf tan Œ∏ = 3/4:\n‚Ä¢ We know: tan Œ∏ = sin Œ∏ / cos Œ∏ = 3/4\n‚Ä¢ Also: sin¬≤Œ∏ + cos¬≤Œ∏ = 1\n‚Ä¢ Let sin Œ∏ = 3k, cos Œ∏ = 4k\n‚Ä¢ Then: (3k)¬≤ + (4k)¬≤ = 1\n‚Ä¢ 9k¬≤ + 16k¬≤ = 1\n‚Ä¢ 25k¬≤ = 1\n‚Ä¢ k = 1/5\n‚Ä¢ sin Œ∏ = 3/5, cos Œ∏ = 4/5\n‚Ä¢ cosec Œ∏ = 5/3, sec Œ∏ = 5/4, cot Œ∏ = 4/3\n\nIf sin Œ∏ = 4/5:\n‚Ä¢ cos¬≤Œ∏ = 1 - 16/25 = 9/25\n‚Ä¢ cos Œ∏ = 3/5\n‚Ä¢ tan Œ∏ = (4/5)/(3/5) = 4/3\n‚Ä¢ All other ratios follow\n\nThese relationships allow finding all ratios from one known ratio.",
                    
                    "Trigonometric Ratios for Angles Greater than 90¬∞ - Extension:\n\nFor Class 10, focus is on acute angles (0¬∞ to 90¬∞).\n\nHowever, understanding extension is important:\n\n‚Ä¢ Ratios can be defined for all angles\n‚Ä¢ For obtuse angles (>90¬∞):\n  - Some ratios become negative\n  - sin remains positive (0¬∞ to 180¬∞)\n  - cos becomes negative (90¬∞ to 270¬∞)\n  - tan becomes negative (90¬∞ to 180¬∞)\n\n‚Ä¢ For angles > 180¬∞:\n  - All ratios repeat in cycles\n  - Periodicity: sin and cos repeat every 360¬∞\n  - tan repeats every 180¬∞\n\nClass 10 Focus:\n‚Ä¢ Mainly acute angles (0¬∞ to 90¬∞)\n‚Ä¢ All ratios are positive\n‚Ä¢ Easier calculations\n‚Ä¢ Foundation for higher classes\n\nHigher Classes:\n‚Ä¢ Extended to all angles\n‚Ä¢ Negative values\n‚Ä¢ Unit circle approach\n‚Ä¢ More complex applications\n\nFor now, master acute angles - they form the foundation!",
                    
