            Chapter(
                id = "maths_10",
                title = "Circles",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Tangent to a Circle - Complete Definition:\n\nA tangent is a line that touches a circle at exactly one point, called the point of tangency or point of contact.\n\nKey Properties:\n‚Ä¢ Touches circle at exactly one point\n‚Ä¢ Never enters the circle\n‚Ä¢ Lies outside the circle (except at point of contact)\n‚Ä¢ Has unique point of contact\n\nNumber of Tangents from a Point:\n\n1. From a point INSIDE the circle:\n   ‚Ä¢ Zero tangents can be drawn\n   ‚Ä¢ All lines through interior point intersect circle at two points (secants)\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Point P inside circle O - no tangent possible\n\n2. From a point ON the circle:\n   ‚Ä¢ Exactly ONE tangent can be drawn\n   ‚Ä¢ The point itself is the point of contact\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Point P on circle O - one tangent at P\n\n3. From a point OUTSIDE the circle:\n   ‚Ä¢ Exactly TWO tangents can be drawn\n   ‚Ä¢ Both tangents are equal in length\n   ‚Ä¢ Symmetric about the line joining point to center\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Point P outside circle O - two tangents PA and PB\n\nUnderstanding tangents is fundamental to circle geometry and helps solve many geometric problems.",
                    
                    "Tangent and Radius - Perpendicular Relationship:\n\nThe most important property of tangents: A tangent at any point is perpendicular to the radius through that point.\n\nTheorem:\nIf PT is a tangent at point P and OP is the radius through P, then:\n‚à†OPT = 90¬∞\n\nProof Concept:\n‚Ä¢ If tangent were not perpendicular, it would intersect circle at another point\n‚Ä¢ But tangent touches at only one point\n‚Ä¢ Therefore, it must be perpendicular\n\nConverse Theorem:\nIf a line through a point on a circle is perpendicular to the radius at that point, then the line is a tangent.\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Proving that a line is tangent\n‚Ä¢ Finding angles in circle problems\n‚Ä¢ Constructing tangents to circles\n‚Ä¢ Solving geometric proofs\n\nExample:\nIn circle with center O, if PT is tangent at P and OP = 5 cm:\n‚Ä¢ ‚à†OPT = 90¬∞\n‚Ä¢ If we know distance from O to any point on PT, we can find angles\n‚Ä¢ Used in many circle geometry problems\n\nThis property is used in almost every problem involving tangents and is fundamental to circle geometry.",
                    
                    "Length of Tangent from External Point - Equal Tangents:\n\nFrom an external point, the lengths of the two tangents to a circle are equal.\n\nTheorem:\nIf PA and PB are tangents from external point P to circle with center O, then:\nPA = PB\n\nProof:\n‚Ä¢ Join OP, OA, OB\n‚Ä¢ In triangles OAP and OBP:\n  - OA = OB (radii)\n  - OP = OP (common)\n  - ‚à†OAP = ‚à†OBP = 90¬∞ (tangent ‚ä• radius)\n‚Ä¢ Therefore, ŒîOAP ‚âÖ ŒîOBP (RHS congruence)\n‚Ä¢ Hence, PA = PB ‚úì\n\nAdditional Properties:\n‚Ä¢ Tangents subtend equal angles at center: ‚à†POA = ‚à†POB\n‚Ä¢ OP bisects the angle between tangents: ‚à†APO = ‚à†BPO\n‚Ä¢ OP bisects the chord joining points of contact (if drawn)\n‚Ä¢ Triangles OAP and OBP are congruent right triangles\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Finding unknown lengths when one tangent length is known\n‚Ä¢ Proving geometric relationships\n‚Ä¢ Solving problems involving external points and circles\n‚Ä¢ Used in construction problems\n\nExample:\nIf PA = 12 cm is a tangent from point P to circle O:\n‚Ä¢ Then PB (other tangent) = 12 cm\n‚Ä¢ Both tangents are equal\n‚Ä¢ Can use this to find distances and angles\n\nThis property is very useful in solving circle problems involving external points.",
                    
                    "Alternate Segment Theorem - Angle Relationships:\n\nThe Alternate Segment Theorem states that the angle between a tangent and a chord through the point of contact equals the angle in the alternate segment.\n\nStatement:\nIf a tangent touches a circle at point A and a chord AB is drawn, then:\nAngle between tangent and chord = Angle in alternate segment\n\nDiagram Understanding:\n‚Ä¢ Tangent touches circle at A\n‚Ä¢ Chord AB divides circle into two segments\n‚Ä¢ Angle between tangent and AB = Angle ACB (where C is on opposite arc)\n\nExample:\nIf tangent at A makes angle 50¬∞ with chord AB:\n‚Ä¢ Then angle ACB (in alternate segment) = 50¬∞\n‚Ä¢ Where C is any point on arc opposite to tangent\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Finding unknown angles in circle problems\n‚Ä¢ Proving angle relationships\n‚Ä¢ Solving complex geometric problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in many circle theorems\n\nWhy It Works:\n‚Ä¢ Based on angle properties of circles\n‚Ä¢ Uses the fact that angle in semicircle is 90¬∞\n‚Ä¢ Related to angle at center and angle at circumference\n\nThis theorem is powerful for solving angle problems in circles and is frequently used in geometric proofs.",
                    
                    "Angle in a Semicircle - Right Angle Property:\n\nThe angle subtended by a diameter in a semicircle is always a right angle (90¬∞).\n\nTheorem:\nIf AB is a diameter of a circle and C is any point on the circle (other than A and B), then:\n‚à†ACB = 90¬∞\n\nProof Concept:\n‚Ä¢ Angle at center O: ‚à†AOB = 180¬∞ (straight line)\n‚Ä¢ Angle at circumference: ‚à†ACB\n‚Ä¢ By angle property: Angle at center = 2 √ó Angle at circumference\n‚Ä¢ Therefore: ‚à†ACB = 180¬∞/2 = 90¬∞ ‚úì\n\nConverse Theorem:\nIf an angle in a circle is 90¬∞, then the side opposite to it is a diameter.\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Proving that a triangle is right-angled\n‚Ä¢ Finding right angles in geometric constructions\n‚Ä¢ Solving problems involving semicircles\n‚Ä¢ Used in many geometric proofs\n\nExample:\nIn circle with diameter AB = 10 cm:\n‚Ä¢ If C is any point on circle\n‚Ä¢ Then ‚à†ACB = 90¬∞\n‚Ä¢ Triangle ABC is right-angled at C\n‚Ä¢ Can use Pythagoras theorem: AC¬≤ + BC¬≤ = AB¬≤\n\nThis property is fundamental and appears in many circle geometry problems.",
                    
                    "Cyclic Quadrilateral - Opposite Angles Property:\n\nA cyclic quadrilateral is a quadrilateral with all four vertices lying on a circle.\n\nKey Theorem:\nIn a cyclic quadrilateral, opposite angles are supplementary (sum = 180¬∞).\n\nStatement:\nIf ABCD is a cyclic quadrilateral, then:\n‚à†A + ‚à†C = 180¬∞\n‚à†B + ‚à†D = 180¬∞\n\nProof Concept:\n‚Ä¢ Angle at center for arc AD = 2‚à†ABD\n‚Ä¢ Angle at center for arc BC = 2‚à†BCD\n‚Ä¢ Sum of arcs = 360¬∞\n‚Ä¢ Therefore, sum of opposite angles = 180¬∞\n\nAdditional Properties:\n‚Ä¢ Exterior angle = Interior opposite angle\n‚Ä¢ If sum of opposite angles is 180¬∞, quadrilateral is cyclic (converse)\n‚Ä¢ Used to prove that a quadrilateral is cyclic\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Finding unknown angles in cyclic quadrilaterals\n‚Ä¢ Proving that a quadrilateral is cyclic\n‚Ä¢ Solving angle problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in many geometric proofs\n\nExample:\nIn cyclic quadrilateral ABCD:\n‚Ä¢ If ‚à†A = 70¬∞, then ‚à†C = 180¬∞ - 70¬∞ = 110¬∞\n‚Ä¢ If ‚à†B = 80¬∞, then ‚à†D = 180¬∞ - 80¬∞ = 100¬∞\n‚Ä¢ Opposite angles always sum to 180¬∞\n\nThis property is essential for solving problems involving quadrilaterals inscribed in circles.",
                    
                    "Angle Properties in Circles - Complete Summary:\n\n1. Angle at Center:\n   ‚Ä¢ Angle subtended by an arc at center = 2 √ó Angle at circumference\n   ‚Ä¢ If arc AB subtends angle Œ∏ at center, it subtends Œ∏/2 at circumference\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: If ‚à†AOB = 100¬∞, then ‚à†ACB = 50¬∞\n\n2. Angles in Same Segment:\n   ‚Ä¢ Angles subtended by same arc at circumference are equal\n   ‚Ä¢ If C and D are on same arc AB, then ‚à†ACB = ‚à†ADB\n   ‚Ä¢ All angles in same segment are equal\n\n3. Angle in Semicircle:\n   ‚Ä¢ Angle in semicircle = 90¬∞\n   ‚Ä¢ If AB is diameter, then ‚à†ACB = 90¬∞\n   ‚Ä¢ Used to find right angles\n\n4. Opposite Angles in Cyclic Quadrilateral:\n   ‚Ä¢ Sum of opposite angles = 180¬∞\n   ‚Ä¢ ‚à†A + ‚à†C = 180¬∞, ‚à†B + ‚à†D = 180¬∞\n\n5. Exterior Angle:\n   ‚Ä¢ Exterior angle = Interior opposite angle\n   ‚Ä¢ In cyclic quadrilateral, exterior angle equals opposite interior angle\n\nThese properties are fundamental tools for solving circle geometry problems and are used extensively in proofs and calculations.",
                    
                    "Tangent from External Point - Complete Properties:\n\nWhen two tangents are drawn from an external point P to a circle with center O:\n\nProperties:\n\n1. Equal Lengths:\n   ‚Ä¢ PA = PB (both tangents have equal length)\n   ‚Ä¢ Proof: Triangles OAP and OBP are congruent (RHS)\n\n2. Equal Angles at Center:\n   ‚Ä¢ ‚à†POA = ‚à†POB\n   ‚Ä¢ Tangents subtend equal angles at center\n\n3. OP Bisects Angle Between Tangents:\n   ‚Ä¢ ‚à†APO = ‚à†BPO\n   ‚Ä¢ OP is angle bisector of ‚à†APB\n\n4. OP Bisects Chord (if drawn):\n   ‚Ä¢ If chord AB joins points of contact\n   ‚Ä¢ OP bisects AB perpendicularly\n   ‚Ä¢ OP is perpendicular bisector of AB\n\n5. Congruent Right Triangles:\n   ‚Ä¢ ŒîOAP ‚âÖ ŒîOBP\n   ‚Ä¢ Both are right triangles (tangent ‚ä• radius)\n   ‚Ä¢ Used in many proofs\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Finding lengths when one tangent is known\n‚Ä¢ Proving geometric relationships\n‚Ä¢ Solving construction problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in many circle geometry problems\n\nExample:\nIf PA = 8 cm from external point P:\n‚Ä¢ Then PB = 8 cm\n‚Ä¢ If OP = 10 cm and radius = 6 cm:\n‚Ä¢ Can find angles using right triangle properties\n‚Ä¢ ‚à†APO = ‚à†BPO (equal angles)\n\nThese properties are essential for solving problems involving tangents from external points.",
                    
                    "Circle Theorems - Applications and Uses:\n\nCircle theorems have wide applications in mathematics and real life:\n\n1. Geometric Constructions:\n   ‚Ä¢ Constructing tangents to circles\n   ‚Ä¢ Finding centers of circles\n   ‚Ä¢ Drawing perpendicular lines\n   ‚Ä¢ Creating geometric designs\n\n2. Proving Geometric Properties:\n   ‚Ä¢ Proving triangles are right-angled\n   ‚Ä¢ Proving quadrilaterals are cyclic\n   ‚Ä¢ Finding angle relationships\n   ‚Ä¢ Solving geometric proofs\n\n3. Solving Angle Problems:\n   ‚Ä¢ Finding unknown angles\n   ‚Ä¢ Using angle properties\n   ‚Ä¢ Combining multiple theorems\n   ‚Ä¢ Complex geometric calculations\n\n4. Finding Lengths and Areas:\n   ‚Ä¢ Using tangent properties\n   ‚Ä¢ Applying Pythagoras theorem\n   ‚Ä¢ Calculating distances\n   ‚Ä¢ Finding areas of segments\n\n5. Architectural Designs:\n   ‚Ä¢ Circular structures\n   ‚Ä¢ Arches and domes\n   ‚Ä¢ Geometric patterns\n   ‚Ä¢ Design calculations\n\n6. Engineering Problems:\n   ‚Ä¢ Mechanical designs\n   ‚Ä¢ Circular components\n   ‚Ä¢ Angle calculations\n   ‚Ä¢ Precision measurements\n\n7. Navigation:\n   ‚Ä¢ Circular paths\n   ‚Ä¢ Angle calculations\n   ‚Ä¢ Distance measurements\n\nUnderstanding circle theorems is essential for advanced geometry and has practical applications in many fields."
                ),
                keyPoints = listOf(
                    "Tangent to a Circle: Line that touches circle at exactly one point. Point of contact is where tangent touches circle. From external point, exactly two tangents can be drawn. Tangents from external point have equal lengths. Tangent is perpendicular to radius at point of contact (90¬∞ angle).",
