                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Division of Line Segment - Step by Step Method:\n\nTo divide a line segment AB in a given ratio m:n using Basic Proportionality Theorem.\n\nDetailed Steps:\n\nStep 1: Draw the Line Segment\n‚Ä¢ Draw line segment AB of given length\n‚Ä¢ Label endpoints A and B\n\nStep 2: Draw a Ray\n‚Ä¢ Draw ray AX making an acute angle with AB\n‚Ä¢ Angle should be convenient (30¬∞-60¬∞ works well)\n‚Ä¢ X is a point on the ray\n\nStep 3: Mark Equal Divisions\n‚Ä¢ Open compass to convenient width\n‚Ä¢ Starting from A, mark (m+n) equal divisions on ray AX\n‚Ä¢ Label points as A‚ÇÅ, A‚ÇÇ, A‚ÇÉ, ..., A‚Çò‚Çä‚Çô\n‚Ä¢ Each division should be equal\n\nStep 4: Join Last Point to B\n‚Ä¢ Join point A‚Çò‚Çä‚Çô to point B\n‚Ä¢ This creates a line through which we'll draw parallels\n\nStep 5: Draw Parallel Lines\n‚Ä¢ Through point A‚Çò, draw line parallel to A‚Çò‚Çä‚ÇôB\n‚Ä¢ This line intersects AB at point P\n‚Ä¢ Point P divides AB in ratio m:n\n\nVerification:\n‚Ä¢ AP:PB = m:n\n‚Ä¢ Can measure to verify\n\nExample:\nDividing 6 cm line in ratio 2:3:\n‚Ä¢ m = 2, n = 3, so m+n = 5\n‚Ä¢ Mark 5 equal divisions on ray\n‚Ä¢ Draw parallel through 2nd division point\n‚Ä¢ Result: AP = 2.4 cm, PB = 3.6 cm\n‚Ä¢ Ratio: 2.4:3.6 = 2:3 ‚úì\n\nThis construction is based on Basic Proportionality Theorem and is fundamental in geometry.",
                    
                    "Construction of Triangles - All Cases:\n\nTriangles can be constructed when given sufficient information. Minimum requirement: 3 independent measurements.\n\nCase 1: SSS (Side-Side-Side)\nGiven: Three sides (e.g., 5 cm, 6 cm, 7 cm)\nSteps:\n1. Draw base of one side (say 6 cm)\n2. With compass, draw arc from one endpoint with radius = second side (5 cm)\n3. From other endpoint, draw arc with radius = third side (7 cm)\n4. Arcs intersect at third vertex\n5. Join to complete triangle\n\nCase 2: SAS (Side-Angle-Side)\nGiven: Two sides and included angle (e.g., 5 cm, 6 cm, 60¬∞)\nSteps:\n1. Draw base of one side (say 5 cm)\n2. At one endpoint, construct given angle (60¬∞)\n3. Mark second side length on angle arm\n4. Join to complete triangle\n\nCase 3: ASA (Angle-Side-Angle)\nGiven: Two angles and included side (e.g., 50¬∞, 60¬∞, side 6 cm)\nSteps:\n1. Draw the given side (6 cm)\n2. At one endpoint, construct first angle (50¬∞)\n3. At other endpoint, construct second angle (60¬∞)\n4. Angle arms intersect at third vertex\n5. Complete triangle\n\nCase 4: RHS (Right angle-Hypotenuse-Side)\nGiven: Right angle, hypotenuse, one side\nSteps:\n1. Draw the given side\n2. Construct right angle at one endpoint\n3. With compass, mark hypotenuse length from vertex\n4. Complete right triangle\n\nImportant: Always check if triangle is possible (sum of two sides > third side).",
                    
                    "Construction of Tangents to Circle - Detailed Method:\n\nTo construct tangents from an external point P to a circle with center O.\n\nStep-by-Step Construction:\n\nStep 1: Identify Given Elements\n‚Ä¢ Circle with center O and radius r\n‚Ä¢ External point P (outside the circle)\n\nStep 2: Join Center to External Point\n‚Ä¢ Draw line segment OP\n‚Ä¢ This line will help locate tangent points\n\nStep 3: Find Midpoint of OP\n‚Ä¢ Find midpoint M of OP using perpendicular bisector\n‚Ä¢ Or measure and mark midpoint\n‚Ä¢ M is the center for auxiliary circle\n\nStep 4: Draw Auxiliary Circle\n‚Ä¢ With M as center and MO (or MP) as radius\n‚Ä¢ Draw a circle\n‚Ä¢ This circle passes through O and P\n\nStep 5: Find Intersection Points\n‚Ä¢ The auxiliary circle intersects the given circle at two points\n‚Ä¢ Label these points as A and B\n‚Ä¢ These are the points of tangency\n\nStep 6: Draw Tangents\n‚Ä¢ Join P to A - this is first tangent\n‚Ä¢ Join P to B - this is second tangent\n‚Ä¢ Both PA and PB are tangents\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ PA = PB (equal lengths)\n‚Ä¢ Tangents are symmetric about OP\n‚Ä¢ ‚à†OAP = ‚à†OBP = 90¬∞ (tangent ‚ä• radius)\n‚Ä¢ Used in many geometric problems\n\nThis construction is based on the property that angle in semicircle is 90¬∞.",
                    
                    "Tools for Geometric Constructions - Classical Method:\n\nClassical geometric constructions use only two tools:\n\n1. Compass:\n   ‚Ä¢ For drawing arcs and circles\n   ‚Ä¢ For transferring distances\n   ‚Ä¢ For marking equal lengths\n   ‚Ä¢ Can be adjusted to different radii\n   ‚Ä¢ Essential for all constructions\n\n2. Straightedge (Unmarked Ruler):\n   ‚Ä¢ For drawing straight lines\n   ‚Ä¢ For connecting points\n   ‚Ä¢ For extending lines\n   ‚Ä¢ Must be unmarked (no measurements)\n   ‚Ä¢ Cannot be used to measure\n\nTools NOT Allowed:\n‚Ä¢ Protractor (for measuring angles)\n‚Ä¢ Marked ruler (for measurements)\n‚Ä¢ Set squares (for right angles)\n‚Ä¢ Any measuring device\n\nWhy Only These Tools?\n‚Ä¢ Teaches fundamental geometric principles\n‚Ä¢ Ensures constructions are based on geometry, not measurement\n‚Ä¢ Develops understanding of geometric relationships\n‚Ä¢ Classical approach to geometry\n‚Ä¢ More accurate in theory\n\nModern Approach:\n‚Ä¢ May use protractor, set squares, etc. for practical work\n‚Ä¢ But understanding classical method is important\n‚Ä¢ Classical method proves geometric relationships\n\nMastering these two tools allows construction of:\n‚Ä¢ Perpendiculars, parallels, angle bisectors\n‚Ä¢ Triangles, circles, tangents\n‚Ä¢ Many geometric figures\n\nThis classical approach is the foundation of geometric constructions.",
                    
                    "Construction of Perpendicular Bisector - Complete Method:\n\nTo construct the perpendicular bisector of a line segment AB.\n\nDetailed Steps:\n\nStep 1: Draw the Line Segment\n‚Ä¢ Draw line segment AB\n‚Ä¢ Label endpoints A and B\n\nStep 2: Set Compass Width\n‚Ä¢ Open compass to more than half of AB\n‚Ä¢ This ensures arcs will intersect\n‚Ä¢ Example: If AB = 6 cm, use radius > 3 cm\n\nStep 3: Draw Arcs from A\n‚Ä¢ With A as center, draw arcs on both sides of AB\n‚Ä¢ Arcs should be above and below the line\n‚Ä¢ Keep same compass width\n\nStep 4: Draw Arcs from B\n‚Ä¢ With B as center, same radius\n‚Ä¢ Draw arcs on both sides of AB\n‚Ä¢ These arcs intersect the arcs from Step 3\n\nStep 5: Mark Intersection Points\n‚Ä¢ Arcs intersect at two points\n‚Ä¢ Label these as P and Q\n‚Ä¢ One point above AB, one below\n\nStep 6: Join Intersection Points\n‚Ä¢ Draw line joining P and Q\n‚Ä¢ This line is the perpendicular bisector\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Passes through midpoint of AB\n‚Ä¢ Perpendicular to AB (90¬∞ angle)\n‚Ä¢ Divides AB into two equal parts\n‚Ä¢ Every point on perpendicular bisector is equidistant from A and B\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Finding midpoint of segment\n‚Ä¢ Constructing perpendicular lines\n‚Ä¢ Finding center of circle through two points\n‚Ä¢ Used in many other constructions\n\nThis is one of the most fundamental constructions in geometry.",
                    
                    "Construction of Angle Bisector - Step by Step:\n\nTo bisect an angle ABC (divide it into two equal parts).\n\nDetailed Steps:\n\nStep 1: Draw the Angle\n‚Ä¢ Draw angle ABC with vertex B\n‚Ä¢ BA and BC are the two arms\n‚Ä¢ Angle can be any measure\n\nStep 2: Draw Arc from Vertex\n‚Ä¢ With B as center, draw an arc\n‚Ä¢ Arc cuts both arms BA and BC\n‚Ä¢ Label intersection points as D (on BA) and E (on BC)\n‚Ä¢ Use convenient radius\n\nStep 3: Draw Arcs from Intersection Points\n‚Ä¢ With D as center, draw an arc (inside the angle)\n‚Ä¢ With E as center, same radius, draw another arc\n‚Ä¢ These arcs intersect at point F\n\nStep 4: Join Vertex to Intersection\n‚Ä¢ Draw line from B through F\n‚Ä¢ This line BF is the angle bisector\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Divides angle into two equal parts\n‚Ä¢ ‚à†ABF = ‚à†FBC = (1/2)‚à†ABC\n‚Ä¢ Every point on bisector is equidistant from both arms\n‚Ä¢ Used in triangle constructions\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Constructing angles of specific measures (e.g., 45¬∞ = bisect 90¬∞)\n‚Ä¢ Finding incenter of triangle (intersection of angle bisectors)\n‚Ä¢ Solving angle problems\n‚Ä¢ Used in many geometric constructions\n\nExample:\nTo construct 45¬∞ angle:\n‚Ä¢ First construct 90¬∞ angle\n‚Ä¢ Then bisect it to get 45¬∞\n‚Ä¢ Can further bisect to get 22.5¬∞\n\nThis construction is fundamental and used frequently in geometry.",
                    
                    "Construction of Parallel Lines - Detailed Method:\n\nTo draw a line parallel to a given line through an external point.\n\nStep-by-Step Construction:\n\nStep 1: Identify Given Elements\n‚Ä¢ Given line l\n‚Ä¢ External point P (not on line l)\n\nStep 2: Draw Transversal\n‚Ä¢ Draw a line through P that intersects line l\n‚Ä¢ This line is called a transversal\n‚Ä¢ Label intersection point as Q\n\nStep 3: Copy the Angle\n‚Ä¢ At point P, construct an angle equal to angle at Q\n‚Ä¢ Use angle copying construction\n‚Ä¢ This creates corresponding angles\n\nMethod 1: Using Angle Copying\n‚Ä¢ Draw arc from Q cutting both lines\n‚Ä¢ With same radius, draw arc from P\n‚Ä¢ Measure arc length from Q, mark on arc from P\n‚Ä¢ Draw line through P making same angle\n\nMethod 2: Using Compass\n‚Ä¢ Mark equal distances on transversal from Q\n‚Ä¢ Use compass to transfer angle\n‚Ä¢ Construct equal angle at P\n\nStep 4: Draw Parallel Line\n‚Ä¢ The line through P making equal angle is parallel to l\n‚Ä¢ This uses property: If corresponding angles are equal, lines are parallel\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Never meets the given line\n‚Ä¢ Maintains constant distance from given line\n‚Ä¢ All points are equidistant from given line\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Constructing parallelograms\n‚Ä¢ Creating parallel structures\n‚Ä¢ Used in many geometric constructions\n‚Ä¢ Essential for advanced constructions\n\nThis construction is based on the property of parallel lines and corresponding angles.",
                    
                    "Construction of Similar Triangles - Scale Factor Method:\n\nTo construct a triangle similar to a given triangle with a given scale factor.\n\nGiven:\n‚Ä¢ Triangle ABC (original triangle)\n‚Ä¢ Scale factor k (e.g., 2:3 means new triangle is 2/3 size)\n\nMethod 1: Using Scale Factor on Base\n\nStep 1: Draw Scaled Base\n‚Ä¢ Draw base A'B' in required ratio\n‚Ä¢ If scale factor is 2:3, and AB = 6 cm:\n  New base = (2/3) √ó 6 = 4 cm\n\nStep 2: Construct Equal Angles\n‚Ä¢ At A', construct angle equal to ‚à†A\n‚Ä¢ At B', construct angle equal to ‚à†B\n‚Ä¢ Use angle copying construction\n\nStep 3: Complete Triangle\n‚Ä¢ Angle arms intersect at C'\n‚Ä¢ Triangle A'B'C' is similar to ABC\n\nMethod 2: Using Proportional Sides\n\nStep 1: Draw Base in Ratio\n‚Ä¢ Draw base in given ratio\n\nStep 2: Mark Proportional Points\n‚Ä¢ Divide base in same ratio as original\n‚Ä¢ Mark corresponding points\n\nStep 3: Construct Angles\n‚Ä¢ Construct corresponding angles\n‚Ä¢ Complete triangle\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ All angles are equal\n‚Ä¢ Sides are proportional\n‚Ä¢ Shape is same, size is different\n‚Ä¢ Area ratio = (scale factor)¬≤\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Scale drawings (maps, blueprints)\n‚Ä¢ Enlarging or reducing figures\n‚Ä¢ Creating similar geometric shapes\n‚Ä¢ Used in architecture and engineering\n\nExample:\nIf original triangle has sides 3, 4, 5 cm and scale factor is 2:\n‚Ä¢ New triangle has sides 6, 8, 10 cm\n‚Ä¢ All angles remain same\n‚Ä¢ Area becomes 4 times (2¬≤ = 4)\n\nThis construction is essential for understanding similarity and scale.",
                    
                    "Practical Applications of Constructions:\n\nGeometric constructions have wide applications:\n\n1. Architectural Drawings:\n   ‚Ä¢ Blueprints and plans\n   ‚Ä¢ Scale models of buildings\n   ‚Ä¢ Precise angle and length constructions\n   ‚Ä¢ Used by architects and engineers\n\n2. Engineering Designs:\n   ‚Ä¢ Mechanical parts design\n   ‚Ä¢ Circuit board layouts\n   ‚Ä¢ Structural designs\n   ‚Ä¢ Precision is critical\n\n3. Map Making:\n   ‚Ä¢ Scale drawings of areas\n   ‚Ä¢ Topographic maps\n   ‚Ä¢ Navigation charts\n   ‚Ä¢ Distance and angle measurements\n\n4. Scale Models:\n   ‚Ä¢ Miniature replicas\n   ‚Ä¢ Maintaining proportions\n   ‚Ä¢ Similar triangle constructions\n   ‚Ä¢ Used in design and presentation\n\n5. Geometric Proofs:\n   ‚Ä¢ Proving theorems\n   ‚Ä¢ Demonstrating properties\n   ‚Ä¢ Visual representation of concepts\n   ‚Ä¢ Educational purposes\n\n6. Art and Design:\n   ‚Ä¢ Geometric patterns\n   ‚Ä¢ Symmetrical designs\n   ‚Ä¢ Precise drawings\n   ‚Ä¢ Creative applications\n\n7. Surveying:\n   ‚Ä¢ Land measurement\n   ‚Ä¢ Boundary marking\n   ‚Ä¢ Angle and distance calculations\n   ‚Ä¢ Used in construction projects\n\nUnderstanding constructions helps visualize geometric concepts and solve practical problems in many fields.",
                    
                    "Important Tips for Accurate Constructions:\n\n1. Use Sharp Pencil:\n   ‚Ä¢ Fine point for accuracy\n   ‚Ä¢ Clear, visible lines\n   ‚Ä¢ Easy to erase if needed\n   ‚Ä¢ Professional appearance\n\n2. Construction Lines First:\n   ‚Ä¢ Draw light construction lines\n   ‚Ä¢ These are guide lines\n   ‚Ä¢ Can be erased later\n   ‚Ä¢ Final lines should be dark\n\n3. Label All Points:\n   ‚Ä¢ Use clear labels (A, B, C, etc.)\n   ‚Ä¢ Helps in explanation\n   ‚Ä¢ Avoids confusion\n   ‚Ä¢ Professional presentation\n\n4. Check Measurements:\n   ‚Ä¢ Verify lengths using compass\n   ‚Ä¢ Check angles\n   ‚Ä¢ Ensure accuracy\n   ‚Ä¢ Re-measure if needed\n\n5. Verify Construction:\n   ‚Ä¢ Check if it meets requirements\n   ‚Ä¢ Measure angles and lengths\n   ‚Ä¢ Ensure properties are satisfied\n   ‚Ä¢ Correct any errors\n\n6. Practice Regularly:\n   ‚Ä¢ Practice different constructions\n   ‚Ä¢ Master basic techniques\n   ‚Ä¢ Build confidence\n   ‚Ä¢ Improve accuracy\n\n7. Be Patient:\n   ‚Ä¢ Constructions require precision\n   ‚Ä¢ Take time for accuracy\n   ‚Ä¢ Don't rush\n   ‚Ä¢ Quality over speed\n\n8. Use Proper Tools:\n   ‚Ä¢ Good quality compass\n   ‚Ä¢ Straight, unmarked ruler\n   ‚Ä¢ Sharp pencil\n   ‚Ä¢ Clean workspace\n\nFollowing these tips ensures accurate and professional geometric constructions."
