                    "Cuboid - Complete Formulas and Properties:\n\nA cuboid is a rectangular solid with three dimensions: length (l), breadth (b), and height (h).\n\nVolume:\nV = l √ó b √ó h\n‚Ä¢ Volume is the space occupied by the cuboid\n‚Ä¢ Measured in cubic units (cm¬≥, m¬≥, etc.)\n‚Ä¢ Represents capacity\n\nTotal Surface Area (TSA):\nTSA = 2(lb + bh + hl)\n‚Ä¢ Sum of areas of all 6 faces\n‚Ä¢ Two faces of each type: front-back, left-right, top-bottom\n‚Ä¢ Measured in square units (cm¬≤, m¬≤, etc.)\n\nLateral Surface Area (LSA):\nLSA = 2h(l + b)\n‚Ä¢ Area of 4 side faces (excluding top and bottom)\n‚Ä¢ Only vertical faces\n‚Ä¢ Used when top and bottom are not included\n\nDiagonal:\nd = ‚àö(l¬≤ + b¬≤ + h¬≤)\n‚Ä¢ Space diagonal from one corner to opposite corner\n‚Ä¢ Longest distance inside cuboid\n\nExample:\nCuboid with l = 5 cm, b = 4 cm, h = 3 cm:\n‚Ä¢ Volume = 5 √ó 4 √ó 3 = 60 cm¬≥\n‚Ä¢ TSA = 2(5√ó4 + 4√ó3 + 3√ó5) = 2(20 + 12 + 15) = 94 cm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ LSA = 2√ó3(5 + 4) = 6√ó9 = 54 cm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Diagonal = ‚àö(5¬≤ + 4¬≤ + 3¬≤) = ‚àö(25 + 16 + 9) = ‚àö50 = 5‚àö2 cm\n\nApplications: Boxes, rooms, containers, storage units, packaging.",
                    
                    "Cube - Special Case of Cuboid:\n\nA cube is a special cuboid where all edges are equal (l = b = h = a).\n\nVolume:\nV = a¬≥\n‚Ä¢ Cube of the edge length\n‚Ä¢ All dimensions equal\n\nTotal Surface Area (TSA):\nTSA = 6a¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Six faces, each with area a¬≤\n‚Ä¢ All faces are identical squares\n\nLateral Surface Area (LSA):\nLSA = 4a¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Four side faces (excluding top and bottom)\n‚Ä¢ Each face has area a¬≤\n\nDiagonals:\n‚Ä¢ Face diagonal = a‚àö2 (diagonal of square face)\n‚Ä¢ Space diagonal = a‚àö3 (diagonal through cube)\n\nExample:\nCube with edge a = 4 cm:\n‚Ä¢ Volume = 4¬≥ = 64 cm¬≥\n‚Ä¢ TSA = 6 √ó 4¬≤ = 6 √ó 16 = 96 cm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ LSA = 4 √ó 4¬≤ = 4 √ó 16 = 64 cm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Face diagonal = 4‚àö2 cm\n‚Ä¢ Space diagonal = 4‚àö3 cm\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ If edge doubles, volume becomes 8 times (2¬≥ = 8)\n‚Ä¢ If edge triples, volume becomes 27 times (3¬≥ = 27)\n‚Ä¢ Surface area increases as square of edge\n\nApplications: Dice, cubic containers, storage cubes, building blocks, cubic objects.",
                    
                    "Cylinder - Circular Prism:\n\nA cylinder is a solid with circular base and uniform height.\n\nGiven: Radius r, Height h\n\nVolume:\nV = œÄr¬≤h\n‚Ä¢ Base area (œÄr¬≤) √ó height (h)\n‚Ä¢ Same as area of circle √ó height\n\nCurved Surface Area (CSA):\nCSA = 2œÄrh\n‚Ä¢ Circumference of base (2œÄr) √ó height (h)\n‚Ä¢ When unrolled, forms a rectangle\n‚Ä¢ Length = 2œÄr, Width = h\n\nTotal Surface Area (TSA):\nTSA = 2œÄr(r + h) = 2œÄr¬≤ + 2œÄrh\n‚Ä¢ Two circular bases (2 √ó œÄr¬≤) + Curved surface (2œÄrh)\n‚Ä¢ Complete surface area\n\nExample:\nCylinder with r = 3 cm, h = 5 cm:\n‚Ä¢ Volume = œÄ √ó 3¬≤ √ó 5 = 45œÄ cm¬≥\n‚Ä¢ Using œÄ = 22/7: V = 45 √ó (22/7) = 990/7 ‚âà 141.43 cm¬≥\n‚Ä¢ CSA = 2œÄ √ó 3 √ó 5 = 30œÄ cm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ TSA = 2œÄ √ó 3(3 + 5) = 6œÄ √ó 8 = 48œÄ cm¬≤\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ If height doubles, volume doubles, CSA doubles\n‚Ä¢ If radius doubles, volume becomes 4 times (r¬≤ effect), CSA doubles\n‚Ä¢ Volume ‚àù r¬≤h, CSA ‚àù rh\n\nApplications: Pipes, cans, pillars, cylindrical containers, tubes, drums.",
                    
                    "Cone - Tapered Solid:\n\nA cone is a solid with circular base tapering to a point (apex).\n\nGiven: Radius r, Height h, Slant height l\n\nSlant Height:\nl = ‚àö(r¬≤ + h¬≤)\n‚Ä¢ Distance from apex to any point on base circumference\n‚Ä¢ Found using Pythagoras theorem\n\nVolume:\nV = (1/3)œÄr¬≤h\n‚Ä¢ One-third of cylinder with same base and height\n‚Ä¢ Volume of cylinder = œÄr¬≤h\n‚Ä¢ Volume of cone = (1/3) √ó Volume of cylinder\n\nCurved Surface Area (CSA):\nCSA = œÄrl\n‚Ä¢ Area of curved (lateral) surface\n‚Ä¢ When unrolled, forms a sector of circle\n\nTotal Surface Area (TSA):\nTSA = œÄr(r + l) = œÄr¬≤ + œÄrl\n‚Ä¢ Circular base (œÄr¬≤) + Curved surface (œÄrl)\n‚Ä¢ Complete surface area\n\nExample:\nCone with r = 4 cm, h = 3 cm:\n‚Ä¢ Slant height l = ‚àö(4¬≤ + 3¬≤) = ‚àö(16 + 9) = ‚àö25 = 5 cm\n‚Ä¢ Volume = (1/3) √ó œÄ √ó 4¬≤ √ó 3 = (1/3) √ó 48œÄ = 16œÄ cm¬≥\n‚Ä¢ CSA = œÄ √ó 4 √ó 5 = 20œÄ cm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ TSA = œÄ √ó 4(4 + 5) = 4œÄ √ó 9 = 36œÄ cm¬≤\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Volume is always (1/3) of corresponding cylinder\n‚Ä¢ Slant height is always greater than height (l > h)\n‚Ä¢ If height doubles, volume doubles\n‚Ä¢ If radius doubles, volume becomes 4 times\n\nApplications: Ice cream cones, party hats, funnels, conical containers, traffic cones.",
                    
                    "Sphere - Perfect Round Solid:\n\nA sphere is a perfectly round solid, like a ball.\n\nGiven: Radius r\n\nVolume:\nV = (4/3)œÄr¬≥\n‚Ä¢ Four-thirds of œÄ times cube of radius\n‚Ä¢ Derived using calculus or geometric methods\n‚Ä¢ Volume of sphere = 2 √ó Volume of hemisphere\n\nSurface Area:\nSA = 4œÄr¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Area of curved surface (no flat faces)\n‚Ä¢ Same as area of 4 circles of radius r\n‚Ä¢ Only one surface (curved)\n\nExample:\nSphere with r = 5 cm:\n‚Ä¢ Volume = (4/3) √ó œÄ √ó 5¬≥ = (4/3) √ó 125œÄ = (500/3)œÄ cm¬≥\n‚Ä¢ Using œÄ = 22/7: V = (500/3) √ó (22/7) = 11000/21 ‚âà 523.81 cm¬≥\n‚Ä¢ Surface Area = 4œÄ √ó 5¬≤ = 4œÄ √ó 25 = 100œÄ cm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Using œÄ = 22/7: SA = 100 √ó (22/7) = 2200/7 ‚âà 314.29 cm¬≤\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ If radius doubles, volume becomes 8 times (r¬≥ effect)\n‚Ä¢ If radius doubles, surface area becomes 4 times (r¬≤ effect)\n‚Ä¢ Volume ‚àù r¬≥, Surface Area ‚àù r¬≤\n‚Ä¢ All points on surface are equidistant from center\n\nApplications: Balls, planets, spherical objects, bubbles, globes, bearings.",
                    
                    "Hemisphere - Half Sphere:\n\nA hemisphere is half of a sphere.\n\nGiven: Radius r\n\nVolume:\nV = (2/3)œÄr¬≥\n‚Ä¢ Half of sphere volume\n‚Ä¢ Sphere volume = (4/3)œÄr¬≥\n‚Ä¢ Hemisphere volume = (1/2) √ó (4/3)œÄr¬≥ = (2/3)œÄr¬≥\n\nCurved Surface Area (CSA):\nCSA = 2œÄr¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Half of sphere surface area\n‚Ä¢ Sphere SA = 4œÄr¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Hemisphere CSA = (1/2) √ó 4œÄr¬≤ = 2œÄr¬≤\n\nTotal Surface Area (TSA):\nTSA = 3œÄr¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Curved surface (2œÄr¬≤) + Circular base (œÄr¬≤)\n‚Ä¢ TSA = 2œÄr¬≤ + œÄr¬≤ = 3œÄr¬≤\n\nExample:\nHemisphere with r = 6 cm:\n‚Ä¢ Volume = (2/3) √ó œÄ √ó 6¬≥ = (2/3) √ó 216œÄ = 144œÄ cm¬≥\n‚Ä¢ CSA = 2œÄ √ó 6¬≤ = 2œÄ √ó 36 = 72œÄ cm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ TSA = 3œÄ √ó 6¬≤ = 3œÄ √ó 36 = 108œÄ cm¬≤\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Volume is (2/3) of full sphere\n‚Ä¢ Curved surface is half of sphere\n‚Ä¢ Has one flat circular face (base)\n‚Ä¢ Used in domes and bowls\n\nApplications: Domes, bowls, hemispherical containers, architectural structures, caps.",
                    
                    "Combination of Solids - Complex Objects:\n\nMany real objects are combinations of basic solids.\n\nGeneral Approach:\n1. Identify individual solids\n2. Find volume/area of each part\n3. Add volumes (for total volume)\n4. Add surface areas, subtract common areas (for total surface area)\n\nCommon Combinations:\n\n1. Cylinder with Hemisphere on Top:\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Tent, silo\n   ‚Ä¢ Volume = Volume of cylinder + Volume of hemisphere\n   ‚Ä¢ V = œÄr¬≤h + (2/3)œÄr¬≥\n   ‚Ä¢ TSA = CSA of cylinder + CSA of hemisphere + Area of base\n   ‚Ä¢ TSA = 2œÄrh + 2œÄr¬≤ + œÄr¬≤ = 2œÄrh + 3œÄr¬≤\n   ‚Ä¢ (Common base area is not included in TSA)\n\n2. Cone on Cylinder:\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Rocket, toy top\n   ‚Ä¢ Volume = Volume of cylinder + Volume of cone\n   ‚Ä¢ V = œÄr¬≤h‚ÇÅ + (1/3)œÄr¬≤h‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ TSA = CSA of cylinder + CSA of cone + Area of base\n\n3. Sphere in Cube:\n   ‚Ä¢ Volume of remaining space = Volume of cube - Volume of sphere\n   ‚Ä¢ V = a¬≥ - (4/3)œÄr¬≥\n\n4. Two Hemispheres on Cylinder:\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Pill, capsule\n   ‚Ä¢ Volume = Volume of cylinder + 2 √ó Volume of hemisphere\n   ‚Ä¢ V = œÄr¬≤h + 2 √ó (2/3)œÄr¬≥ = œÄr¬≤h + (4/3)œÄr¬≥\n\nProblem Solving:\n‚Ä¢ Break complex object into simple shapes\n‚Ä¢ Calculate each part separately\n‚Ä¢ Combine results carefully\n‚Ä¢ Watch for common surfaces that shouldn't be counted twice",
                    
                    "Conversion of Units - Important Equivalents:\n\nVolume Conversions:\n‚Ä¢ 1 m¬≥ = 1000 liters\n‚Ä¢ 1 liter = 1000 cm¬≥ = 1000 ml\n‚Ä¢ 1 cm¬≥ = 1 ml\n‚Ä¢ 1 m¬≥ = 1,000,000 cm¬≥\n‚Ä¢ 1 liter = 1 dm¬≥\n\nSurface Area Conversions:\n‚Ä¢ 1 m¬≤ = 10,000 cm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ 1 cm¬≤ = 100 mm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ 1 m¬≤ = 1,000,000 mm¬≤\n‚Ä¢ 1 km¬≤ = 1,000,000 m¬≤\n\nLength Conversions:\n‚Ä¢ 1 m = 100 cm = 1000 mm\n‚Ä¢ 1 km = 1000 m\n‚Ä¢ 1 cm = 10 mm\n\nImportant Notes:\n‚Ä¢ Always check units in problems\n‚Ä¢ Convert all measurements to same units before calculating\n‚Ä¢ Volume units are cubic (m¬≥, cm¬≥)\n‚Ä¢ Surface area units are square (m¬≤, cm¬≤)\n‚Ä¢ Length units are linear (m, cm)\n\nExample:\nCylinder with r = 2 m, h = 3 m:\n‚Ä¢ Volume = œÄ √ó 2¬≤ √ó 3 = 12œÄ m¬≥\n‚Ä¢ Convert to liters: 12œÄ √ó 1000 = 12,000œÄ liters\n‚Ä¢ CSA = 2œÄ √ó 2 √ó 3 = 12œÄ m¬≤\n‚Ä¢ Convert to cm¬≤: 12œÄ √ó 10,000 = 120,000œÄ cm¬≤\n\nAlways verify units match the context of the problem.",
                    
                    "Practical Applications - Real-World Uses:\n\nSurface areas and volumes have extensive practical applications:\n\n1. Construction:\n   ‚Ä¢ Calculating material needed (concrete, paint)\n   ‚Ä¢ Finding capacity of tanks and reservoirs\n   ‚Ä¢ Designing structures\n   ‚Ä¢ Cost estimation\n\n2. Manufacturing:\n   ‚Ä¢ Designing containers and packaging\n   ‚Ä¢ Material calculations\n   ‚Ä¢ Volume of products\n   ‚Ä¢ Surface area for coating/painting\n\n3. Engineering:\n   ‚Ä¢ Pipes and tubes (cylinders)\n   ‚Ä¢ Storage tanks\n   ‚Ä¢ Structural components\n   ‚Ä¢ Fluid capacity calculations\n\n4. Architecture:\n   ‚Ä¢ Building designs\n   ‚Ä¢ Dome constructions (hemispheres)\n   ‚Ä¢ Room volumes\n   ‚Ä¢ Surface area for materials\n\n5. Daily Life:\n   ‚Ä¢ Container capacities\n   ‚Ä¢ Paint needed for walls\n   ‚Ä¢ Water storage\n   ‚Ä¢ Packaging design\n\n6. Science:\n   ‚Ä¢ Volume of substances\n   ‚Ä¢ Surface area for reactions\n   ‚Ä¢ Capacity calculations\n   ‚Ä¢ Research applications\n\n7. Business:\n   ‚Ä¢ Packaging optimization\n   ‚Ä¢ Material cost calculation\n   ‚Ä¢ Storage capacity\n   ‚Ä¢ Shipping volume\n\nUnderstanding these applications connects mathematics to real-world problems and makes learning meaningful and practical.",
                    
                    "Problem Solving Strategy - Step-by-Step Approach:\n\n1. Identify the Shape:\n   ‚Ä¢ Determine if it's cuboid, cube, cylinder, cone, sphere, or combination\n   ‚Ä¢ Draw a rough diagram\n   ‚Ä¢ Label all given dimensions\n\n2. Note Given Dimensions:\n   ‚Ä¢ List all known values (radius, height, length, etc.)\n   ‚Ä¢ Check units\n   ‚Ä¢ Identify what needs to be found\n\n3. Choose Correct Formula:\n   ‚Ä¢ Select appropriate formula for volume or surface area\n   ‚Ä¢ For combinations, identify formulas for each part\n   ‚Ä¢ Ensure formula matches the shape\n\n4. Calculate Step by Step:\n   ‚Ä¢ Substitute values into formula\n   ‚Ä¢ Perform calculations carefully\n   ‚Ä¢ Show intermediate steps\n   ‚Ä¢ Use correct value of œÄ (22/7 or 3.14)\n\n5. Check Units:\n   ‚Ä¢ Ensure all measurements in same units\n   ‚Ä¢ Convert if necessary\n   ‚Ä¢ Verify final answer has correct units\n   ‚Ä¢ Volume: cubic units, Area: square units\n\n6. Verify Answer:\n   ‚Ä¢ Check if answer is reasonable\n   ‚Ä¢ Volume should be positive\n   ‚Ä¢ Compare with known values\n   ‚Ä¢ Re-check calculations if needed\n\n7. For Combination Problems:\n   ‚Ä¢ Break into individual shapes\n   ‚Ä¢ Calculate each part separately\n   ‚Ä¢ Add volumes\n   ‚Ä¢ Add areas, subtract common surfaces\n\n8. Practice Regularly:\n   ‚Ä¢ Solve various problems\n   ‚Ä¢ Master all formulas\n   ‚Ä¢ Build confidence\n   ‚Ä¢ Improve accuracy\n\nFollowing this strategy ensures accurate problem solving and better understanding of 3D geometry."
