            Chapter(
                id = "maths_14",
                title = "Statistics",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Mean (Average) - Complete Understanding:\n\nThe mean is the average of all observations, representing the central value of data.\n\nFormula:\nMean = (Œ£x)/n = (Sum of all values) / (Number of values)\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ Œ£x = Sum of all observations\n‚Ä¢ n = Total number of observations\n‚Ä¢ x = Individual values\n\nCalculation:\n1. Add all values\n2. Count total number of values\n3. Divide sum by count\n\nExample:\nData: 2, 4, 6, 8, 10\n‚Ä¢ Sum = 2 + 4 + 6 + 8 + 10 = 30\n‚Ä¢ Count = 5\n‚Ä¢ Mean = 30/5 = 6\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Uses all values in calculation\n‚Ä¢ Represents central tendency\n‚Ä¢ Affected by extreme values (outliers)\n‚Ä¢ Good for symmetric data\n‚Ä¢ Sensitive to changes in any value\n\nWhen to Use:\n‚Ä¢ When data is symmetric\n‚Ä¢ When all values are important\n‚Ä¢ For further calculations\n‚Ä¢ When outliers are not significant\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Average marks in exams\n‚Ä¢ Average temperature\n‚Ä¢ Average income\n‚Ä¢ Average speed\n‚Ä¢ Used in many real-world scenarios\n\nThe mean is the most commonly used measure of central tendency.",
                    
                    "Median - Middle Value:\n\nThe median is the middle value when data is arranged in order.\n\nFinding Median:\n\nStep 1: Arrange data in ascending or descending order\nStep 2: Find middle position\n\nFor Odd Number of Observations:\n‚Ä¢ Median = Middle value\n‚Ä¢ Position = (n + 1)/2\n‚Ä¢ Example: Data: 3, 5, 7, 9, 11 (n = 5)\n  Position = (5 + 1)/2 = 3rd value\n  Median = 7\n\nFor Even Number of Observations:\n‚Ä¢ Median = Average of two middle values\n‚Ä¢ Positions = n/2 and (n/2 + 1)\n‚Ä¢ Example: Data: 2, 4, 6, 8 (n = 4)\n  Positions = 2nd and 3rd values\n  Median = (4 + 6)/2 = 5\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Not affected by extreme values (outliers)\n‚Ä¢ Represents middle position\n‚Ä¢ Good for skewed data\n‚Ä¢ Divides data into two equal halves\n‚Ä¢ 50% values below, 50% above median\n\nWhen to Use:\n‚Ä¢ When data has outliers\n‚Ä¢ For skewed distributions\n‚Ä¢ When extreme values are not representative\n‚Ä¢ For ordinal data\n\nFor Grouped Data:\n‚Ä¢ Use cumulative frequency\n‚Ä¢ Find median class\n‚Ä¢ Apply formula: Median = L + [(n/2 - cf)/f] √ó h\n\nThe median is robust and not affected by outliers.",
                    
                    "Mode - Most Frequent Value:\n\nThe mode is the value that appears most frequently in the data.\n\nFinding Mode:\n1. Count frequency of each value\n2. Value with highest frequency is mode\n\nExample:\nData: 2, 3, 3, 4, 4, 4, 5\n‚Ä¢ Frequency: 2 appears 1 time, 3 appears 2 times, 4 appears 3 times, 5 appears 1 time\n‚Ä¢ Mode = 4 (appears most times)\n\nTypes:\n‚Ä¢ Unimodal: One mode\n‚Ä¢ Bimodal: Two modes (two values with same highest frequency)\n‚Ä¢ Multimodal: More than two modes\n‚Ä¢ No mode: All values appear equally (or all different)\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Represents most common value\n‚Ä¢ Not affected by outliers\n‚Ä¢ Can have multiple modes\n‚Ä¢ May not exist (if all values different)\n‚Ä¢ Useful for categorical data\n\nWhen to Use:\n‚Ä¢ For categorical data\n‚Ä¢ Finding most popular item\n‚Ä¢ Most common size\n‚Ä¢ When frequency matters\n\nFor Grouped Data:\n‚Ä¢ Modal class = Class with highest frequency\n‚Ä¢ Use formula: Mode = L + [(f‚ÇÅ - f‚ÇÄ)/(2f‚ÇÅ - f‚ÇÄ - f‚ÇÇ)] √ó h\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Most popular color\n‚Ä¢ Most common shoe size\n‚Ä¢ Most frequent score\n‚Ä¢ Used in surveys and polls\n\nThe mode identifies the most typical or common value.",
                    
                    "Mean of Grouped Data - Three Methods:\n\nWhen data is grouped into classes, we use special methods to find mean.\n\nMethod 1: Direct Method\nFormula: Mean = Œ£(fx)/Œ£f\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ f = Frequency of class\n‚Ä¢ x = Class mark (midpoint of class)\n‚Ä¢ fx = f √ó x (frequency √ó class mark)\n‚Ä¢ Œ£f = Sum of all frequencies\n‚Ä¢ Œ£fx = Sum of (frequency √ó class mark)\n\nSteps:\n1. Find class marks (midpoints)\n2. Multiply frequency by class mark (fx)\n3. Sum all fx values\n4. Sum all frequencies\n5. Divide Œ£fx by Œ£f\n\nMethod 2: Assumed Mean Method\nFormula: Mean = A + (Œ£fd)/Œ£f\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ A = Assumed mean (convenient value, usually middle class mark)\n‚Ä¢ d = x - A (deviation from assumed mean)\n‚Ä¢ fd = f √ó d\n‚Ä¢ Œ£fd = Sum of (frequency √ó deviation)\n\nSteps:\n1. Choose assumed mean A\n2. Find deviations d = x - A\n3. Multiply frequency by deviation (fd)\n4. Sum all fd values\n5. Apply formula\n\nMethod 3: Step Deviation Method\nFormula: Mean = A + h(Œ£fu)/Œ£f\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ A = Assumed mean\n‚Ä¢ h = Class width (common difference)\n‚Ä¢ u = (x - A)/h (step deviation)\n‚Ä¢ fu = f √ó u\n‚Ä¢ Œ£fu = Sum of (frequency √ó step deviation)\n\nSteps:\n1. Choose assumed mean A\n2. Find step deviations u = (x - A)/h\n3. Multiply frequency by step deviation (fu)\n4. Sum all fu values\n5. Apply formula\n\nChoose method based on convenience and class width.",
                    
                    "Cumulative Frequency - Running Total:\n\nCumulative frequency is the running total of frequencies up to a certain point.\n\nTypes:\n\n1. Less Than Type:\n   ‚Ä¢ Cumulative frequency up to upper limit of class\n   ‚Ä¢ Shows how many values are less than upper limit\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: If class is 0-10, cf shows values < 10\n\n2. More Than Type:\n   ‚Ä¢ Cumulative frequency from lower limit of class\n   ‚Ä¢ Shows how many values are greater than or equal to lower limit\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: If class is 0-10, cf shows values ‚â• 0\n\nCalculation:\n‚Ä¢ Start with first class frequency\n‚Ä¢ Add subsequent frequencies\n‚Ä¢ Running total accumulates\n\nExample:\nFrequencies: 5, 8, 12, 10\nLess than type cumulative:\n‚Ä¢ 5 (first class)\n‚Ä¢ 5 + 8 = 13 (up to second class)\n‚Ä¢ 13 + 12 = 25 (up to third class)\n‚Ä¢ 25 + 10 = 35 (up to fourth class)\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Finding median (where n/2 lies)\n‚Ä¢ Finding quartiles and percentiles\n‚Ä¢ Drawing ogives (cumulative frequency curves)\n‚Ä¢ Analyzing data distribution\n\nOgive (Cumulative Frequency Curve):\n‚Ä¢ Graph of cumulative frequency\n‚Ä¢ Less than ogive: Upper limits vs cumulative frequency\n‚Ä¢ More than ogive: Lower limits vs cumulative frequency\n‚Ä¢ Intersection of two ogives gives median\n\nCumulative frequency helps understand data distribution and find percentiles.",
                    
                    "Median of Grouped Data - Formula Method:\n\nTo find median when data is grouped into classes.\n\nFormula:\nMedian = L + [(n/2 - cf)/f] √ó h\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ L = Lower limit of median class\n‚Ä¢ n = Total number of observations (Œ£f)\n‚Ä¢ cf = Cumulative frequency of class before median class\n‚Ä¢ f = Frequency of median class\n‚Ä¢ h = Class width\n\nSteps:\n\nStep 1: Find Cumulative Frequencies\n‚Ä¢ Calculate less than type cumulative frequencies\n‚Ä¢ Running total of frequencies\n\nStep 2: Determine Median Class\n‚Ä¢ Find n/2 (half of total observations)\n‚Ä¢ Locate class where cumulative frequency ‚â• n/2\n‚Ä¢ This is the median class\n\nStep 3: Apply Formula\n‚Ä¢ Identify L (lower limit of median class)\n‚Ä¢ Find cf (cumulative frequency of previous class)\n‚Ä¢ Note f (frequency of median class)\n‚Ä¢ Note h (class width)\n‚Ä¢ Substitute in formula\n\nExample:\nIf n = 50, median class is 20-30 with:\n‚Ä¢ L = 20\n‚Ä¢ cf = 15 (cumulative frequency before median class)\n‚Ä¢ f = 12 (frequency of median class)\n‚Ä¢ h = 10 (class width)\n\nMedian = 20 + [(50/2 - 15)/12] √ó 10\n       = 20 + [(25 - 15)/12] √ó 10\n       = 20 + [10/12] √ó 10\n       = 20 + 8.33\n       = 28.33\n\nThis gives the median value for grouped data.",
                    
                    "Mode of Grouped Data - Modal Class Method:\n\nTo find mode when data is grouped into classes.\n\nFormula:\nMode = L + [(f‚ÇÅ - f‚ÇÄ)/(2f‚ÇÅ - f‚ÇÄ - f‚ÇÇ)] √ó h\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ L = Lower limit of modal class\n‚Ä¢ f‚ÇÅ = Frequency of modal class (highest frequency)\n‚Ä¢ f‚ÇÄ = Frequency of class before modal class\n‚Ä¢ f‚ÇÇ = Frequency of class after modal class\n‚Ä¢ h = Class width\n\nSteps:\n\nStep 1: Identify Modal Class\n‚Ä¢ Find class with highest frequency\n‚Ä¢ This is the modal class\n\nStep 2: Note Required Values\n‚Ä¢ L = Lower limit of modal class\n‚Ä¢ f‚ÇÅ = Frequency of modal class\n‚Ä¢ f‚ÇÄ = Frequency of previous class\n‚Ä¢ f‚ÇÇ = Frequency of next class\n‚Ä¢ h = Class width\n\nStep 3: Apply Formula\n‚Ä¢ Substitute values in formula\n‚Ä¢ Calculate mode\n\nExample:\nModal class: 20-30 with frequency 15\nPrevious class (10-20): frequency 8\nNext class (30-40): frequency 10\nClass width h = 10\n\nMode = 20 + [(15 - 8)/(2√ó15 - 8 - 10)] √ó 10\n     = 20 + [7/(30 - 18)] √ó 10\n     = 20 + [7/12] √ó 10\n     = 20 + 5.83\n     = 25.83\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Mode lies within modal class\n‚Ä¢ Depends on frequencies of adjacent classes\n‚Ä¢ Gives approximate value for grouped data\n\nThis formula provides the mode for grouped frequency distributions.",
                    
                    "Graphical Representation - Visualizing Data:\n\nDifferent graphs for different types of data:\n\n1. Histogram:\n   ‚Ä¢ For continuous data\n   ‚Ä¢ Bars have no gaps (unlike bar graph)\n   ‚Ä¢ Width represents class intervals\n   ‚Ä¢ Height represents frequency\n   ‚Ä¢ Area is proportional to frequency\n   ‚Ä¢ Used to show distribution\n\n2. Frequency Polygon:\n   ‚Ä¢ Line graph joining midpoints of histogram bars\n   ‚Ä¢ Shows trend in data\n   ‚Ä¢ Can compare multiple distributions\n   ‚Ä¢ Smooth curve representation\n\n3. Ogive (Cumulative Frequency Curve):\n   ‚Ä¢ Graph of cumulative frequency\n   ‚Ä¢ Less than ogive: Upper limits vs cumulative frequency\n   ‚Ä¢ More than ogive: Lower limits vs cumulative frequency\n   ‚Ä¢ Intersection gives median\n   ‚Ä¢ Used to find percentiles\n\n4. Bar Graph:\n   ‚Ä¢ For discrete data\n   ‚Ä¢ Bars have gaps between them\n   ‚Ä¢ Each bar represents a category\n   ‚Ä¢ Height shows frequency\n\n5. Pie Chart:\n   ‚Ä¢ Circular graph\n   ‚Ä¢ Shows proportions\n   ‚Ä¢ Angle = (Frequency/Total) √ó 360¬∞\n   ‚Ä¢ Used for categorical data\n\nChoosing Right Graph:\n‚Ä¢ Continuous data ‚Üí Histogram\n‚Ä¢ Discrete data ‚Üí Bar graph\n‚Ä¢ Proportions ‚Üí Pie chart\n‚Ä¢ Trends ‚Üí Frequency polygon\n‚Ä¢ Percentiles ‚Üí Ogive\n\nGraphs help visualize patterns and understand data distribution.",
                    
                    "Measures of Central Tendency - Comparison:\n\nUnderstanding when to use each measure:\n\nMean:\n‚Ä¢ Uses: All values in calculation\n‚Ä¢ Affected by: Outliers (extreme values)\n‚Ä¢ Best for: Symmetric data\n‚Ä¢ Advantage: Uses all information\n‚Ä¢ Disadvantage: Sensitive to outliers\n‚Ä¢ Example: Average marks when all students present\n\nMedian:\n‚Ä¢ Uses: Only middle value(s)\n‚Ä¢ Affected by: Not affected by outliers\n‚Ä¢ Best for: Skewed data\n‚Ä¢ Advantage: Robust, not influenced by extremes\n‚Ä¢ Disadvantage: Ignores other values\n‚Ä¢ Example: Median income (not affected by very high incomes)\n\nMode:\n‚Ä¢ Uses: Most frequent value\n‚Ä¢ Affected by: Not affected by outliers\n‚Ä¢ Best for: Categorical data\n‚Ä¢ Advantage: Shows most typical value\n‚Ä¢ Disadvantage: May not exist or be unique\n‚Ä¢ Example: Most popular color, most common size\n\nChoosing Measure:\n‚Ä¢ Symmetric data ‚Üí Use mean\n‚Ä¢ Skewed data ‚Üí Use median\n‚Ä¢ Categorical data ‚Üí Use mode\n‚Ä¢ For complete picture ‚Üí Use all three\n\nAll three together provide comprehensive understanding of data central tendency.",
                    
                    "Applications of Statistics - Real-World Uses:\n\nStatistics is used extensively in various fields:\n\n1. Education:\n   ‚Ä¢ Analyzing exam results\n   ‚Ä¢ Average scores\n   ‚Ä¢ Performance trends\n   ‚Ä¢ Grade distributions\n\n2. Business:\n   ‚Ä¢ Market research\n   ‚Ä¢ Sales analysis\n   ‚Ä¢ Customer surveys\n   ‚Ä¢ Quality control\n\n3. Science:\n   ‚Ä¢ Experimental data analysis\n   ‚Ä¢ Research findings\n   ‚Ä¢ Scientific measurements\n   ‚Ä¢ Data interpretation\n\n4. Medicine:\n   ‚Ä¢ Medical research\n   ‚Ä¢ Treatment effectiveness\n   ‚Ä¢ Patient data analysis\n   ‚Ä¢ Clinical trials\n\n5. Economics:\n   ‚Ä¢ Economic indicators\n   ‚Ä¢ Income distribution\n   ‚Ä¢ Market analysis\n   ‚Ä¢ GDP calculations\n\n6. Sports:\n   ‚Ä¢ Player statistics\n   ‚Ä¢ Performance analysis\n   ‚Ä¢ Team comparisons\n   ‚Ä¢ Records and averages\n\n7. Weather:\n   ‚Ä¢ Temperature averages\n   ‚Ä¢ Rainfall data\n   ‚Ä¢ Climate analysis\n   ‚Ä¢ Forecasting\n\n8. Social Sciences:\n   ‚Ä¢ Opinion polls\n   ‚Ä¢ Survey analysis\n   ‚Ä¢ Population studies\n   ‚Ä¢ Social trends\n\nUnderstanding statistics helps in:\n‚Ä¢ Making informed decisions\n‚Ä¢ Interpreting data correctly\n‚Ä¢ Identifying patterns\n‚Ä¢ Predicting trends\n‚Ä¢ Solving real-world problems\n\nStatistics is essential for data-driven decision making in all fields."
