            Chapter(
                id = "maths_15",
                title = "Probability",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Probability - Complete Definition:\n\nProbability is a measure of the likelihood or chance that an event will occur.\n\nExpression:\n‚Ä¢ As a fraction: 0 to 1\n‚Ä¢ As a decimal: 0.0 to 1.0\n‚Ä¢ As a percentage: 0% to 100%\n\nBasic Formula:\nProbability = Number of favorable outcomes / Total number of possible outcomes\n\nP(E) = n(E) / n(S)\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ P(E) = Probability of event E\n‚Ä¢ n(E) = Number of favorable outcomes\n‚Ä¢ n(S) = Total number of possible outcomes\n\nExample:\nProbability of getting head in coin toss:\n‚Ä¢ Favorable outcomes: 1 (Head)\n‚Ä¢ Total outcomes: 2 (Head, Tail)\n‚Ä¢ P(Head) = 1/2 = 0.5 = 50%\n\nKey Requirements:\n‚Ä¢ All outcomes must be equally likely\n‚Ä¢ Sample space must be well-defined\n‚Ä¢ Events must be clearly specified\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Predicting outcomes\n‚Ä¢ Making decisions\n‚Ä¢ Risk assessment\n‚Ä¢ Games and sports\n‚Ä¢ Weather forecasting\n‚Ä¢ Quality control\n‚Ä¢ Insurance\n\nProbability helps quantify uncertainty and make informed predictions.",
                    
                    "Basic Probability Formula - Detailed Understanding:\n\nThe fundamental formula for probability:\n\nP(E) = Number of favorable outcomes / Total number of outcomes\n\nConditions:\n‚Ä¢ All outcomes must be equally likely\n‚Ä¢ Sample space must be complete\n‚Ä¢ Events must be well-defined\n\nExample 1: Single Die\nProbability of getting 6:\n‚Ä¢ Favorable outcomes: 1 (getting 6)\n‚Ä¢ Total outcomes: 6 (1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6)\n‚Ä¢ P(6) = 1/6\n\nExample 2: Even Number on Die\nProbability of getting even number:\n‚Ä¢ Favorable outcomes: 3 (2, 4, 6)\n‚Ä¢ Total outcomes: 6\n‚Ä¢ P(Even) = 3/6 = 1/2\n\nExample 3: Prime Number on Die\nProbability of getting prime number:\n‚Ä¢ Prime numbers on die: 2, 3, 5\n‚Ä¢ Favorable outcomes: 3\n‚Ä¢ Total outcomes: 6\n‚Ä¢ P(Prime) = 3/6 = 1/2\n\nCalculation Steps:\n1. Identify all possible outcomes (sample space)\n2. Count total number of outcomes\n3. Identify favorable outcomes for the event\n4. Count number of favorable outcomes\n5. Divide favorable by total\n\nThis formula is the foundation of all probability calculations.",
                    
                    "Range of Probability - Limits and Interpretation:\n\nProbability always lies between 0 and 1, inclusive.\n\nRange: 0 ‚â§ P(E) ‚â§ 1\n\nSpecial Cases:\n\n1. P(E) = 0 (Impossible Event):\n   ‚Ä¢ Event will never occur\n   ‚Ä¢ No favorable outcomes\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Getting 7 on a single die\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Sun not rising tomorrow\n\n2. P(E) = 1 (Certain Event):\n   ‚Ä¢ Event will always occur\n   ‚Ä¢ All outcomes are favorable\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Sun rising tomorrow\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Getting a number ‚â§ 6 on a die\n\n3. P(E) = 0.5 (Equally Likely):\n   ‚Ä¢ 50% chance\n   ‚Ä¢ Equal probability of occurrence and non-occurrence\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Getting head in fair coin toss\n\n4. 0 < P(E) < 1 (Possible Event):\n   ‚Ä¢ Event may or may not occur\n   ‚Ä¢ Some chance, but not certain\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Getting 3 on die (P = 1/6)\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Rain tomorrow (P = 0.3)\n\nInterpretation:\n‚Ä¢ Closer to 0: Less likely\n‚Ä¢ Closer to 1: More likely\n‚Ä¢ 0.5: Equally likely\n\nUnderstanding the range helps interpret probability values correctly.",
                    
                    "Complementary Events - Opposite Events:\n\nTwo events are complementary if one occurs exactly when the other doesn't.\n\nDefinition:\n‚Ä¢ Event E and event 'not E' are complementary\n‚Ä¢ If E occurs, 'not E' does not occur\n‚Ä¢ If E does not occur, 'not E' occurs\n‚Ä¢ Together, they cover all possibilities\n\nKey Relationship:\nP(E) + P(not E) = 1\n\nTherefore:\nP(not E) = 1 - P(E)\n\nExample 1: Coin Toss\n‚Ä¢ E = Getting head, P(E) = 1/2\n‚Ä¢ not E = Getting tail, P(not E) = 1/2\n‚Ä¢ P(E) + P(not E) = 1/2 + 1/2 = 1 ‚úì\n\nExample 2: Rain\n‚Ä¢ If P(rain) = 0.3\n‚Ä¢ Then P(no rain) = 1 - 0.3 = 0.7\n‚Ä¢ P(rain) + P(no rain) = 0.3 + 0.7 = 1 ‚úì\n\nExample 3: Exam\n‚Ä¢ If P(passing) = 0.8\n‚Ä¢ Then P(failing) = 1 - 0.8 = 0.2\n‚Ä¢ P(passing) + P(failing) = 0.8 + 0.2 = 1 ‚úì\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Finding probability of opposite event\n‚Ä¢ When P(not E) is easier to calculate\n‚Ä¢ Verifying probability calculations\n‚Ä¢ Solving probability problems\n\nComplementary events are very useful in probability calculations.",
                    
                    "Sample Space - All Possible Outcomes:\n\nThe sample space is the set of all possible outcomes of an experiment.\n\nNotation: S\n\nExamples:\n\n1. Coin Toss:\n   ‚Ä¢ S = {H, T}\n   ‚Ä¢ Two possible outcomes\n   ‚Ä¢ n(S) = 2\n\n2. Single Die:\n   ‚Ä¢ S = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}\n   ‚Ä¢ Six possible outcomes\n   ‚Ä¢ n(S) = 6\n\n3. Two Coins:\n   ‚Ä¢ S = {HH, HT, TH, TT}\n   ‚Ä¢ Four possible outcomes\n   ‚Ä¢ n(S) = 4\n\n4. Two Dice:\n   ‚Ä¢ 36 possible outcomes\n   ‚Ä¢ S = {(1,1), (1,2), ..., (6,6)}\n   ‚Ä¢ n(S) = 36\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Contains all possible outcomes\n‚Ä¢ No outcome is left out\n‚Ä¢ Outcomes are mutually exclusive\n‚Ä¢ Together, outcomes cover all possibilities\n\nFinding Sample Space:\n‚Ä¢ List all possible outcomes\n‚Ä¢ Ensure completeness\n‚Ä¢ Check for duplicates\n‚Ä¢ Count total outcomes\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Calculating total outcomes\n‚Ä¢ Finding probability\n‚Ä¢ Listing all possibilities\n‚Ä¢ Understanding experiment\n\nSample space is fundamental to all probability calculations.",
                    
                    "Event - Subset of Sample Space:\n\nAn event is a subset of the sample space, representing favorable outcomes.\n\nDefinition:\n‚Ä¢ Event E is a collection of outcomes\n‚Ä¢ E ‚äÜ S (event is subset of sample space)\n‚Ä¢ Contains outcomes favorable to the event\n\nExamples:\n\n1. Event: Getting Even Number on Die\n   ‚Ä¢ Sample space: S = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}\n   ‚Ä¢ Event E = {2, 4, 6}\n   ‚Ä¢ n(E) = 3\n   ‚Ä¢ P(E) = 3/6 = 1/2\n\n2. Event: Getting Head on Coin\n   ‚Ä¢ Sample space: S = {H, T}\n   ‚Ä¢ Event E = {H}\n   ‚Ä¢ n(E) = 1\n   ‚Ä¢ P(E) = 1/2\n\n3. Event: Getting Prime Number on Die\n   ‚Ä¢ Sample space: S = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}\n   ‚Ä¢ Event E = {2, 3, 5}\n   ‚Ä¢ n(E) = 3\n   ‚Ä¢ P(E) = 3/6 = 1/2\n\nTypes of Events:\n‚Ä¢ Simple event: Single outcome\n‚Ä¢ Compound event: Multiple outcomes\n‚Ä¢ Impossible event: Empty set (no outcomes)\n‚Ä¢ Certain event: Entire sample space (all outcomes)\n\nProbability of Event:\nP(E) = n(E) / n(S)\n\nUnderstanding events helps define what we want to find probability of.",
                    
                    "Probability of Multiple Events - Combined Probabilities:\n\nWhen dealing with multiple events, different rules apply:\n\n1. Independent Events:\n   ‚Ä¢ Events that don't affect each other\n   ‚Ä¢ P(A and B) = P(A) √ó P(B)\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Tossing two coins\n     P(Head on first) = 1/2\n     P(Head on second) = 1/2\n     P(Both heads) = (1/2) √ó (1/2) = 1/4\n\n2. Mutually Exclusive Events:\n   ‚Ä¢ Events that cannot occur together\n   ‚Ä¢ P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B)\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Getting 2 or 3 on die\n     P(2) = 1/6, P(3) = 1/6\n     P(2 or 3) = 1/6 + 1/6 = 2/6 = 1/3\n\n3. Non-Mutually Exclusive Events:\n   ‚Ä¢ Events that can occur together\n   ‚Ä¢ P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A and B)\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Getting even number or prime number on die\n     P(Even) = 3/6, P(Prime) = 3/6\n     P(Even and Prime) = 1/6 (only 2)\n     P(Even or Prime) = 3/6 + 3/6 - 1/6 = 5/6\n\nUnderstanding these rules helps solve complex probability problems.",
                    
                    "Experimental Probability - Based on Actual Data:\n\nExperimental probability is calculated from actual experiments or observations.\n\nFormula:\nExperimental P(E) = Number of times event occurred / Total number of trials\n\nKey Points:\n‚Ä¢ Based on real data\n‚Ä¢ Calculated after performing experiment\n‚Ä¢ May differ from theoretical probability\n‚Ä¢ Becomes more accurate with more trials\n\nExample:\nTossing a coin 100 times:\n‚Ä¢ Heads occurred: 52 times\n‚Ä¢ Tails occurred: 48 times\n‚Ä¢ Experimental P(Head) = 52/100 = 0.52\n‚Ä¢ Theoretical P(Head) = 1/2 = 0.50\n\nLaw of Large Numbers:\n‚Ä¢ As number of trials increases\n‚Ä¢ Experimental probability approaches theoretical probability\n‚Ä¢ More trials ‚Üí more accurate\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ When theoretical probability is unknown\n‚Ä¢ Real-world data analysis\n‚Ä¢ Quality control\n‚Ä¢ Sports statistics\n‚Ä¢ Medical research\n\nAdvantages:\n‚Ä¢ Based on actual observations\n‚Ä¢ Reflects real-world conditions\n‚Ä¢ Useful when theory is complex\n\nLimitations:\n‚Ä¢ Requires many trials for accuracy\n‚Ä¢ May vary with different trials\n‚Ä¢ Time-consuming\n\nExperimental probability is valuable for real-world applications.",
                    
                    "Theoretical Probability - Mathematical Calculation:\n\nTheoretical probability is calculated using mathematical reasoning and logic.\n\nCharacteristics:\n‚Ä¢ Based on mathematical formulas\n‚Ä¢ Assumes all outcomes are equally likely\n‚Ä¢ Calculated before experiment\n‚Ä¢ More precise when assumptions hold\n\nExample:\nTheoretical probability of head in coin toss:\n‚Ä¢ Sample space: {H, T}\n‚Ä¢ Favorable outcomes: {H}\n‚Ä¢ P(Head) = 1/2 = 0.5\n\nAdvantages:\n‚Ä¢ Precise and exact\n‚Ä¢ No need for experiments\n‚Ä¢ Based on logic\n‚Ä¢ Consistent results\n\nWhen to Use:\n‚Ä¢ When all outcomes are known\n‚Ä¢ When outcomes are equally likely\n‚Ä¢ For mathematical problems\n‚Ä¢ When assumptions are valid\n\nComparison with Experimental:\n‚Ä¢ Theoretical: Calculated from theory\n‚Ä¢ Experimental: Calculated from data\n‚Ä¢ As trials increase, experimental ‚Üí theoretical\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Games of chance\n‚Ä¢ Mathematical problems\n‚Ä¢ When theory is well-established\n‚Ä¢ Educational purposes\n\nTheoretical probability provides the expected value based on mathematical principles.",
                    
                    "Applications of Probability - Real-World Uses:\n\nProbability is used extensively in various fields:\n\n1. Weather Forecasting:\n   ‚Ä¢ Probability of rain\n   ‚Ä¢ Temperature predictions\n   ‚Ä¢ Storm likelihood\n   ‚Ä¢ Climate analysis\n\n2. Insurance:\n   ‚Ä¢ Risk assessment\n   ‚Ä¢ Premium calculation\n   ‚Ä¢ Claim probability\n   ‚Ä¢ Actuarial science\n\n3. Quality Control:\n   ‚Ä¢ Defect probability\n   ‚Ä¢ Product reliability\n   ‚Ä¢ Testing strategies\n   ‚Ä¢ Manufacturing\n\n4. Medical Diagnosis:\n   ‚Ä¢ Disease probability\n   ‚Ä¢ Treatment effectiveness\n   ‚Ä¢ Test accuracy\n   ‚Ä¢ Risk assessment\n\n5. Games and Sports:\n   ‚Ä¢ Winning chances\n   ‚Ä¢ Player statistics\n   ‚Ä¢ Betting odds\n   ‚Ä¢ Strategy decisions\n\n6. Business:\n   ‚Ä¢ Market predictions\n   ‚Ä¢ Investment risk\n   ‚Ä¢ Sales forecasting\n   ‚Ä¢ Decision making\n\n7. Science:\n   ‚Ä¢ Experimental outcomes\n   ‚Ä¢ Research findings\n   ‚Ä¢ Statistical analysis\n   ‚Ä¢ Hypothesis testing\n\n8. Daily Life:\n   ‚Ä¢ Decision making\n   ‚Ä¢ Risk assessment\n   ‚Ä¢ Planning\n   ‚Ä¢ Understanding uncertainty\n\nUnderstanding probability helps:\n‚Ä¢ Make informed decisions\n‚Ä¢ Assess risks\n‚Ä¢ Predict outcomes\n‚Ä¢ Understand chance events\n‚Ä¢ Solve real-world problems\n\nProbability is essential for understanding and dealing with uncertainty in all aspects of life."
                ),
                keyPoints = listOf(
                    "Basic Concepts: Probability measures likelihood of event. Range: 0 (impossible) to 1 (certain). Probability = Number of favorable outcomes / Total number of outcomes. Sample space is set of all possible outcomes. Event is subset of sample space. Example: Probability of head in coin toss = 1/2 (one favorable out of two possible).",
                    "Probability of Events: For equally likely outcomes, P(E) = Number of outcomes favorable to E / Total number of outcomes. Sum of probabilities of all possible outcomes = 1. Probability of sure event = 1, impossible event = 0. Example: Probability of getting prime number on die = 3/6 = 1/2 (primes: 2,3,5).",
