            Chapter(
                id = "science_1",
                title = "Chemical Reactions and Equations",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Chemical Reaction - Complete Definition:\n\nA chemical reaction is a process in which one or more substances (reactants) are converted into new substances (products) with different physical and chemical properties.\n\nKey Characteristics:\n‚Ä¢ Reactants: Starting substances\n‚Ä¢ Products: New substances formed\n‚Ä¢ Chemical bonds break and form\n‚Ä¢ Properties change (color, state, energy, etc.)\n‚Ä¢ Mass is conserved (Law of Conservation of Mass)\n\nExample:\n2H‚ÇÇ + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2H‚ÇÇO\n‚Ä¢ Reactants: Hydrogen (H‚ÇÇ) and Oxygen (O‚ÇÇ)\n‚Ä¢ Products: Water (H‚ÇÇO)\n‚Ä¢ Properties change: Gases combine to form liquid\n\nIndicators of Chemical Reaction:\n‚Ä¢ Change in color\n‚Ä¢ Formation of precipitate\n‚Ä¢ Evolution of gas\n‚Ä¢ Change in temperature\n‚Ä¢ Change in smell\n\nChemical reactions are fundamental to all life processes and industrial processes.",
                    
                    "Chemical Equation - Symbolic Representation:\n\nA chemical equation is a symbolic representation of a chemical reaction using chemical formulas.\n\nStructure:\nReactants ‚Üí Products\n\nComponents:\n‚Ä¢ Reactants: On left side of arrow\n‚Ä¢ Products: On right side of arrow\n‚Ä¢ Arrow (‚Üí): Shows direction of reaction\n‚Ä¢ Coefficients: Numbers before formulas (show quantity)\n‚Ä¢ Subscripts: Numbers in formulas (show atoms in molecule)\n\nExample:\n2H‚ÇÇ + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2H‚ÇÇO\n‚Ä¢ 2H‚ÇÇ: 2 molecules of hydrogen\n‚Ä¢ O‚ÇÇ: 1 molecule of oxygen\n‚Ä¢ 2H‚ÇÇO: 2 molecules of water\n\nPhysical States:\n‚Ä¢ (s) = solid\n‚Ä¢ (l) = liquid\n‚Ä¢ (g) = gas\n‚Ä¢ (aq) = aqueous (dissolved in water)\n\nExample with states:\n2H‚ÇÇ(g) + O‚ÇÇ(g) ‚Üí 2H‚ÇÇO(l)\n\nEquations must be balanced to follow Law of Conservation of Mass.",
                    
                    "Balanced Equation - Law of Conservation of Mass:\n\nA balanced equation has equal number of atoms of each element on both sides.\n\nLaw of Conservation of Mass:\n‚Ä¢ Atoms are neither created nor destroyed\n‚Ä¢ Mass of reactants = Mass of products\n‚Ä¢ Number of each type of atom must be equal on both sides\n\nExample - Unbalanced:\nH‚ÇÇ + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí H‚ÇÇO\n‚Ä¢ Left: 2H, 2O\n‚Ä¢ Right: 2H, 1O\n‚Ä¢ Not balanced (oxygen atoms don't match)\n\nExample - Balanced:\n2H‚ÇÇ + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2H‚ÇÇO\n‚Ä¢ Left: 4H, 2O\n‚Ä¢ Right: 4H, 2O\n‚Ä¢ Balanced ‚úì\n\nWhy Balance?\n‚Ä¢ Follows scientific law\n‚Ä¢ Shows correct ratios\n‚Ä¢ Allows calculations (stoichiometry)\n‚Ä¢ Represents actual reaction\n\nBalancing is essential for:\n‚Ä¢ Understanding reaction\n‚Ä¢ Calculating quantities\n‚Ä¢ Predicting products\n‚Ä¢ Chemical analysis",
                    
                    "Steps to Balance Equations - Detailed Method:\n\nStep-by-step process:\n\nStep 1: Write Correct Formulas\n‚Ä¢ Use proper chemical formulas\n‚Ä¢ Don't change subscripts (they show actual molecules)\n‚Ä¢ Example: H‚ÇÇO (not H‚ÇÇO‚ÇÇ)\n\nStep 2: Count Atoms on Each Side\n‚Ä¢ List all elements\n‚Ä¢ Count atoms in each element\n‚Ä¢ Compare left and right\n\nStep 3: Use Coefficients to Balance\n‚Ä¢ Add coefficients (numbers before formulas)\n‚Ä¢ Start with elements that appear once\n‚Ä¢ Balance atoms one by one\n‚Ä¢ Use smallest whole numbers\n\nStep 4: Check All Atoms\n‚Ä¢ Verify each element is balanced\n‚Ä¢ Recheck if needed\n‚Ä¢ Ensure coefficients are in lowest terms\n\nExample:\nBalance: Fe + H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí Fe‚ÇÉO‚ÇÑ + H‚ÇÇ\n\nStep 1: Formulas are correct\nStep 2: Count:\n‚Ä¢ Left: Fe=1, H=2, O=1\n‚Ä¢ Right: Fe=3, H=2, O=4\n\nStep 3: Balance:\n‚Ä¢ Start with Fe: 3Fe + H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí Fe‚ÇÉO‚ÇÑ + H‚ÇÇ\n‚Ä¢ Balance O: 3Fe + 4H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí Fe‚ÇÉO‚ÇÑ + H‚ÇÇ\n‚Ä¢ Balance H: 3Fe + 4H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí Fe‚ÇÉO‚ÇÑ + 4H‚ÇÇ\n\nStep 4: Check:\n‚Ä¢ Left: Fe=3, H=8, O=4\n‚Ä¢ Right: Fe=3, H=8, O=4 ‚úì\n\nBalanced: 3Fe + 4H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí Fe‚ÇÉO‚ÇÑ + 4H‚ÇÇ",
                    
                    "Types of Chemical Reactions - Complete Classification:\n\n1. Combination Reaction:\n   ‚Ä¢ Two or more substances combine to form one product\n   ‚Ä¢ General: A + B ‚Üí AB\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: 2H‚ÇÇ + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2H‚ÇÇO\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: CaO + H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí Ca(OH)‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Also called synthesis reaction\n\n2. Decomposition Reaction:\n   ‚Ä¢ One substance breaks into two or more products\n   ‚Ä¢ General: AB ‚Üí A + B\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: 2H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí 2H‚ÇÇ + O‚ÇÇ (electrolysis)\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: CaCO‚ÇÉ ‚Üí CaO + CO‚ÇÇ (heating)\n   ‚Ä¢ Requires energy (heat, light, electricity)\n\n3. Displacement Reaction:\n   ‚Ä¢ More reactive element displaces less reactive element\n   ‚Ä¢ General: A + BC ‚Üí AC + B\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Zn + H‚ÇÇSO‚ÇÑ ‚Üí ZnSO‚ÇÑ + H‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Fe + CuSO‚ÇÑ ‚Üí FeSO‚ÇÑ + Cu\n   ‚Ä¢ Based on reactivity series\n\n4. Double Displacement Reaction:\n   ‚Ä¢ Ions exchange partners\n   ‚Ä¢ General: AB + CD ‚Üí AD + CB\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: AgNO‚ÇÉ + NaCl ‚Üí AgCl + NaNO‚ÇÉ\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: BaCl‚ÇÇ + Na‚ÇÇSO‚ÇÑ ‚Üí BaSO‚ÇÑ + 2NaCl\n   ‚Ä¢ Often forms precipitate\n\n5. Oxidation-Reduction (Redox):\n   ‚Ä¢ Involves transfer of electrons\n   ‚Ä¢ Oxidation and reduction occur together\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Fe‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ + 2Al ‚Üí Al‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ + 2Fe",
                    
                    "Oxidation - Loss of Electrons:\n\nOxidation is the process of:\n‚Ä¢ Loss of electrons\n‚Ä¢ Gain of oxygen\n‚Ä¢ Loss of hydrogen\n‚Ä¢ Increase in oxidation number\n\nDefinition:\nA substance is oxidized when it loses electrons.\n\nExample 1:\n2Mg + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2MgO\n‚Ä¢ Mg loses electrons ‚Üí Mg¬≤‚Å∫\n‚Ä¢ Mg is oxidized\n‚Ä¢ O‚ÇÇ gains electrons ‚Üí O¬≤‚Åª\n\nExample 2:\nZn + CuSO‚ÇÑ ‚Üí ZnSO‚ÇÑ + Cu\n‚Ä¢ Zn loses electrons: Zn ‚Üí Zn¬≤‚Å∫ + 2e‚Åª\n‚Ä¢ Zn is oxidized\n‚Ä¢ Cu¬≤‚Å∫ gains electrons: Cu¬≤‚Å∫ + 2e‚Åª ‚Üí Cu\n\nOxidizing Agent:\n‚Ä¢ Substance that causes oxidation\n‚Ä¢ Accepts electrons\n‚Ä¢ Gets reduced itself\n‚Ä¢ Example: O‚ÇÇ, Cu¬≤‚Å∫, Fe¬≥‚Å∫\n\nIdentifying Oxidation:\n‚Ä¢ Element becomes positive ion\n‚Ä¢ Gains oxygen\n‚Ä¢ Loses hydrogen\n‚Ä¢ Oxidation number increases\n\nOxidation is always accompanied by reduction (redox reaction).",
                    
                    "Reduction - Gain of Electrons:\n\nReduction is the process of:\n‚Ä¢ Gain of electrons\n‚Ä¢ Loss of oxygen\n‚Ä¢ Gain of hydrogen\n‚Ä¢ Decrease in oxidation number\n\nDefinition:\nA substance is reduced when it gains electrons.\n\nExample 1:\nCuO + H‚ÇÇ ‚Üí Cu + H‚ÇÇO\n‚Ä¢ Cu¬≤‚Å∫ gains electrons ‚Üí Cu\n‚Ä¢ CuO is reduced\n‚Ä¢ H‚ÇÇ loses electrons ‚Üí 2H‚Å∫\n\nExample 2:\nFe‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ + 2Al ‚Üí Al‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ + 2Fe\n‚Ä¢ Fe¬≥‚Å∫ gains electrons ‚Üí Fe\n‚Ä¢ Fe‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ is reduced\n‚Ä¢ Al loses electrons ‚Üí Al¬≥‚Å∫\n\nReducing Agent:\n‚Ä¢ Substance that causes reduction\n‚Ä¢ Donates electrons\n‚Ä¢ Gets oxidized itself\n‚Ä¢ Example: H‚ÇÇ, C, Zn, Al\n\nIdentifying Reduction:\n‚Ä¢ Positive ion becomes element\n‚Ä¢ Loses oxygen\n‚Ä¢ Gains hydrogen\n‚Ä¢ Oxidation number decreases\n\nMnemonic:\n‚Ä¢ OIL RIG: Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain (of electrons)\n\nReduction always occurs with oxidation (redox reaction).",
                    
                    "Redox Reaction - Complete Understanding:\n\nA redox reaction involves both oxidation and reduction occurring simultaneously.\n\nKey Points:\n‚Ä¢ One substance is oxidized\n‚Ä¢ Another substance is reduced\n‚Ä¢ Electrons are transferred\n‚Ä¢ Cannot have one without the other\n\nExample:\nFe‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ + 2Al ‚Üí Al‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ + 2Fe\n\nOxidation:\n‚Ä¢ Al ‚Üí Al¬≥‚Å∫ + 3e‚Åª\n‚Ä¢ Al loses electrons (oxidized)\n‚Ä¢ Al is reducing agent\n\nReduction:\n‚Ä¢ Fe¬≥‚Å∫ + 3e‚Åª ‚Üí Fe\n‚Ä¢ Fe gains electrons (reduced)\n‚Ä¢ Fe‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ is oxidizing agent\n\nIdentifying Redox:\n‚Ä¢ Check if oxidation numbers change\n‚Ä¢ Look for electron transfer\n‚Ä¢ Check for gain/loss of oxygen or hydrogen\n\nTypes:\n‚Ä¢ Direct combination: 2Mg + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2MgO\n‚Ä¢ Displacement: Zn + CuSO‚ÇÑ ‚Üí ZnSO‚ÇÑ + Cu\n‚Ä¢ Decomposition: 2H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí 2H‚ÇÇ + O‚ÇÇ\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Extraction of metals\n‚Ä¢ Batteries and cells\n‚Ä¢ Corrosion and rusting\n‚Ä¢ Combustion reactions\n\nRedox reactions are fundamental in chemistry and biology.",
                    
                    "Corrosion - Metal Deterioration:\n\nCorrosion is the slow process of deterioration of metals due to reaction with environment (air, water, acids).\n\nRusting of Iron:\n‚Ä¢ Most common example\n‚Ä¢ Chemical equation: 4Fe + 3O‚ÇÇ + 6H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí 4Fe(OH)‚ÇÉ\n‚Ä¢ Requires: Iron, Oxygen, Water (moisture)\n‚Ä¢ Forms: Hydrated ferric oxide (rust)\n‚Ä¢ Rust is reddish-brown, flaky\n‚Ä¢ Weakens the metal\n\nFactors Affecting Corrosion:\n‚Ä¢ Presence of moisture (water)\n‚Ä¢ Presence of oxygen\n‚Ä¢ Presence of acids/salts (accelerates)\n‚Ä¢ Temperature (higher = faster)\n‚Ä¢ Impurities in metal\n\nPrevention Methods:\n\n1. Painting:\n   ‚Ä¢ Forms protective layer\n   ‚Ä¢ Prevents contact with air/water\n   ‚Ä¢ Common for iron objects\n\n2. Galvanization:\n   ‚Ä¢ Coating with zinc\n   ‚Ä¢ Zinc protects iron (sacrificial protection)\n   ‚Ä¢ Used for pipes, buckets\n\n3. Alloying:\n   ‚Ä¢ Mixing with other metals\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Stainless steel (iron + chromium + nickel)\n   ‚Ä¢ More resistant to corrosion\n\n4. Electroplating:\n   ‚Ä¢ Coating with another metal\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Chromium plating\n\n5. Oiling/Greasing:\n   ‚Ä¢ Temporary protection\n   ‚Ä¢ For machinery parts\n\nOther Examples:\n‚Ä¢ Copper: Green layer (basic copper carbonate)\n‚Ä¢ Silver: Black tarnish (silver sulfide)\n‚Ä¢ Aluminum: Protective oxide layer (prevents further corrosion)",
                    
                    "Rancidity - Food Spoilage:\n\nRancidity is the oxidation of fats and oils in food, causing bad smell and taste.\n\nProcess:\n‚Ä¢ Fats and oils react with oxygen\n‚Ä¢ Forms compounds with unpleasant odor and taste\n‚Ä¢ Makes food unfit for consumption\n‚Ä¢ Occurs over time\n\nTypes:\n\n1. Oxidative Rancidity:\n   ‚Ä¢ Reaction with oxygen\n   ‚Ä¢ Forms peroxides\n   ‚Ä¢ Common in unsaturated fats\n\n2. Hydrolytic Rancidity:\n   ‚Ä¢ Breakdown by water\n   ‚Ä¢ Forms free fatty acids\n   ‚Ä¢ Common in presence of enzymes\n\nFactors Affecting:\n‚Ä¢ Exposure to air (oxygen)\n‚Ä¢ Light (UV rays accelerate)\n‚Ä¢ Temperature (heat speeds up)\n‚Ä¢ Presence of metals (catalysts)\n‚Ä¢ Moisture\n\nPrevention Methods:\n\n1. Adding Antioxidants:\n   ‚Ä¢ BHA (Butylated Hydroxyanisole)\n   ‚Ä¢ BHT (Butylated Hydroxytoluene)\n   ‚Ä¢ Vitamin E\n   ‚Ä¢ Prevents oxidation\n\n2. Storing in Airtight Containers:\n   ‚Ä¢ Prevents contact with oxygen\n   ‚Ä¢ Reduces oxidation\n\n3. Refrigeration:\n   ‚Ä¢ Low temperature slows reaction\n   ‚Ä¢ Preserves food longer\n\n4. Packaging with Nitrogen:\n   ‚Ä¢ Replaces oxygen\n   ‚Ä¢ Prevents oxidation\n\n5. Adding Preservatives:\n   ‚Ä¢ Chemical preservatives\n   ‚Ä¢ Extends shelf life\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Prevents food spoilage\n‚Ä¢ Maintains food quality\n‚Ä¢ Ensures food safety\n‚Ä¢ Reduces waste"
                ),
