            Chapter(
                id = "science_2",
                title = "Life Processes",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Life Processes - Complete Overview:\n\nThe basic functions performed by living organisms to maintain life are called life processes.\n\nSeven Essential Processes:\n1. Nutrition - Obtaining and utilizing food\n2. Respiration - Releasing energy from food\n3. Transportation - Moving materials within body\n4. Excretion - Removing waste products\n5. Control and Coordination - Responding to environment\n6. Reproduction - Producing offspring\n7. Growth - Increasing in size\n\nAll living organisms perform these processes:\n‚Ä¢ Plants: Autotrophic nutrition, simple transport systems\n‚Ä¢ Animals: Heterotrophic nutrition, complex organ systems\n‚Ä¢ Both need energy, materials, and waste removal\n\nThese processes are interconnected - one cannot function without others. Understanding these processes helps understand how living things survive and function.",
                    
                    "Nutrition - Detailed Types and Processes:\n\nNutrition is the process of obtaining and utilizing food for growth, maintenance, and energy.\n\nTwo Main Types:\n\n1. Autotrophic Nutrition:\n   ‚Ä¢ Organisms make their own food\n   ‚Ä¢ Plants use photosynthesis\n   ‚Ä¢ Equation: 6CO‚ÇÇ + 6H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí C‚ÇÜH‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇO‚ÇÜ + 6O‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Requires: CO‚ÇÇ, H‚ÇÇO, sunlight, chlorophyll\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples: Green plants, some bacteria\n\n2. Heterotrophic Nutrition:\n   ‚Ä¢ Organisms depend on others for food\n   ‚Ä¢ Cannot make their own food\n   ‚Ä¢ Types:\n     - Holozoic (ingestion): Animals\n     - Saprophytic (decomposition): Fungi\n     - Parasitic (host): Some plants, animals\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples: All animals, fungi, some plants\n\nProcess in Animals:\nIngestion ‚Üí Digestion ‚Üí Absorption ‚Üí Assimilation ‚Üí Egestion\n\nNutrition provides:\n‚Ä¢ Energy for metabolic activities\n‚Ä¢ Materials for growth and repair\n‚Ä¢ Essential nutrients (proteins, carbohydrates, fats, vitamins, minerals)",
                    
                    "Photosynthesis - Complete Process:\n\nPhotosynthesis is the process by which green plants make food using carbon dioxide, water, and sunlight.\n\nChemical Equation:\n6CO‚ÇÇ + 6H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí C‚ÇÜH‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇO‚ÇÜ + 6O‚ÇÇ\n\nRequirements:\n‚Ä¢ Carbon dioxide (from air)\n‚Ä¢ Water (from roots)\n‚Ä¢ Sunlight (energy source)\n‚Ä¢ Chlorophyll (green pigment in leaves)\n\nSite:\n‚Ä¢ Occurs in chloroplasts (cell organelles)\n‚Ä¢ Mainly in leaves (green parts)\n\nProcess:\n1. Light Reaction:\n   ‚Ä¢ Occurs in presence of light\n   ‚Ä¢ Chlorophyll absorbs light energy\n   ‚Ä¢ Water splits: H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí H‚Å∫ + OH‚Åª\n   ‚Ä¢ Oxygen released: 2OH‚Åª ‚Üí H‚ÇÇO + ¬ΩO‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Energy stored as ATP and NADPH\n\n2. Dark Reaction (Calvin Cycle):\n   ‚Ä¢ Can occur in light or dark\n   ‚Ä¢ Uses ATP and NADPH from light reaction\n   ‚Ä¢ CO‚ÇÇ combines with hydrogen to form glucose\n   ‚Ä¢ Glucose is stored as starch\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Produces food for all living organisms\n‚Ä¢ Releases oxygen (essential for respiration)\n‚Ä¢ Removes CO‚ÇÇ from atmosphere\n‚Ä¢ Maintains oxygen-carbon dioxide balance",
                    
                    "Human Digestive System - Complete Journey:\n\nThe human digestive system processes food through various organs:\n\nPathway:\n\n1. Mouth:\n   ‚Ä¢ Teeth: Mechanical digestion (chewing)\n   ‚Ä¢ Saliva: Contains amylase enzyme\n   ‚Ä¢ Amylase breaks down starch ‚Üí maltose\n   ‚Ä¢ Food mixed with saliva forms bolus\n\n2. Esophagus:\n   ‚Ä¢ Muscular tube\n   ‚Ä¢ Peristalsis (wave-like contractions) pushes food down\n   ‚Ä¢ No digestion occurs here\n\n3. Stomach:\n   ‚Ä¢ J-shaped muscular bag\n   ‚Ä¢ Secretes gastric juice:\n     - HCl: Kills bacteria, activates pepsin\n     - Pepsin: Digests proteins ‚Üí peptides\n   ‚Ä¢ Churning action mixes food\n   ‚Ä¢ Food becomes chyme\n\n4. Small Intestine:\n   ‚Ä¢ Longest part (6-7 meters)\n   ‚Ä¢ Receives:\n     - Pancreatic juice (trypsin, lipase, amylase)\n     - Bile (from liver, emulsifies fats)\n     - Intestinal juice (complete digestion)\n   ‚Ä¢ Complete digestion occurs here\n   ‚Ä¢ Absorption of nutrients through villi\n   ‚Ä¢ Villi increase surface area for absorption\n\n5. Large Intestine:\n   ‚Ä¢ Absorbs water and minerals\n   ‚Ä¢ Forms feces from undigested food\n   ‚Ä¢ Stores feces temporarily\n\n6. Anus:\n   ‚Ä¢ Egestion of feces\n\nEnzymes:\n‚Ä¢ Amylase: Starch ‚Üí Sugar\n‚Ä¢ Pepsin/Trypsin: Proteins ‚Üí Amino acids\n‚Ä¢ Lipase: Fats ‚Üí Fatty acids + Glycerol",
                    
                    "Respiration - Energy Release Process:\n\nRespiration is the process of releasing energy from food.\n\nTwo Types:\n\n1. Aerobic Respiration:\n   ‚Ä¢ Requires oxygen\n   ‚Ä¢ Complete breakdown of glucose\n   ‚Ä¢ Equation: C‚ÇÜH‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇO‚ÇÜ + 6O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 6CO‚ÇÇ + 6H‚ÇÇO + Energy (38 ATP)\n   ‚Ä¢ Produces: CO‚ÇÇ, H‚ÇÇO, and large amount of energy\n   ‚Ä¢ Occurs in: Mitochondria\n   ‚Ä¢ More efficient (38 ATP per glucose)\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples: Most organisms, including humans\n\n2. Anaerobic Respiration:\n   ‚Ä¢ No oxygen required\n   ‚Ä¢ Incomplete breakdown of glucose\n   ‚Ä¢ Produces less energy (2 ATP per glucose)\n   ‚Ä¢ Types:\n     - Alcoholic: C‚ÇÜH‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇO‚ÇÜ ‚Üí 2C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÖOH + 2CO‚ÇÇ + Energy\n       (Yeast, some bacteria)\n     - Lactic Acid: C‚ÇÜH‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇO‚ÇÜ ‚Üí 2C‚ÇÉH‚ÇÜO‚ÇÉ + Energy\n       (Muscle cells during exercise)\n   ‚Ä¢ Less efficient but faster\n\nProcess:\n1. Glycolysis: Glucose ‚Üí Pyruvate (in cytoplasm)\n2. If oxygen present: Pyruvate ‚Üí CO‚ÇÇ + H‚ÇÇO (in mitochondria)\n3. If no oxygen: Pyruvate ‚Üí Alcohol/Lactic acid\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Provides energy for all life processes\n‚Ä¢ Essential for survival\n‚Ä¢ Energy used for: Movement, growth, reproduction, etc.",
                    
                    "Human Respiratory System - Complete Structure:\n\nThe respiratory system takes in oxygen and removes carbon dioxide.\n\nPathway:\n\n1. Nostrils:\n   ‚Ä¢ Entry point for air\n   ‚Ä¢ Hairs filter dust particles\n\n2. Nasal Cavity:\n   ‚Ä¢ Warms and moistens air\n   ‚Ä¢ Mucus traps particles\n   ‚Ä¢ Cilia move mucus out\n\n3. Pharynx:\n   ‚Ä¢ Common passage for air and food\n   ‚Ä¢ Epiglottis prevents food entering windpipe\n\n4. Larynx (Voice Box):\n   ‚Ä¢ Contains vocal cords\n   ‚Ä¢ Produces sound\n\n5. Trachea (Windpipe):\n   ‚Ä¢ Tube with C-shaped cartilage rings\n   ‚Ä¢ Keeps airway open\n   ‚Ä¢ Divides into two bronchi\n\n6. Bronchi:\n   ‚Ä¢ Two branches (one to each lung)\n   ‚Ä¢ Further divide into bronchioles\n\n7. Bronchioles:\n   ‚Ä¢ Smaller branches\n   ‚Ä¢ End in air sacs (alveoli)\n\n8. Alveoli:\n   ‚Ä¢ Tiny air sacs (millions in each lung)\n   ‚Ä¢ Site of gas exchange\n   ‚Ä¢ Surrounded by blood capillaries\n   ‚Ä¢ Thin walls for easy diffusion\n   ‚Ä¢ Large surface area\n\nGas Exchange:\n‚Ä¢ O‚ÇÇ diffuses from alveoli ‚Üí blood\n‚Ä¢ CO‚ÇÇ diffuses from blood ‚Üí alveoli\n\nBreathing:\n‚Ä¢ Inhalation: Diaphragm contracts, chest expands, air enters\n‚Ä¢ Exhalation: Diaphragm relaxes, chest contracts, air exits\n‚Ä¢ Rate: 15-18 times per minute (at rest)",
                    
                    "Transportation in Plants - Xylem and Phloem:\n\nPlants have two transport systems:\n\n1. Xylem:\n   ‚Ä¢ Transports water and minerals\n   ‚Ä¢ Direction: Upward (roots ‚Üí leaves)\n   ‚Ä¢ Made of: Dead cells (vessels and tracheids)\n   ‚Ä¢ Function:\n     - Absorbs water from soil (root hairs)\n     - Transports to all parts\n     - Provides raw materials for photosynthesis\n\n2. Phloem:\n   ‚Ä¢ Transports food (sugars, amino acids)\n   ‚Ä¢ Direction: Bidirectional (leaves ‚Üî other parts)\n   ‚Ä¢ Made of: Living cells (sieve tubes and companion cells)\n   ‚Ä¢ Function:\n     - Transports food from leaves (source) to other parts (sink)\n     - Storage organs can also be sources\n\nMechanisms:\n\n‚Ä¢ Root Pressure:\n  - Water pushed up from roots\n  - Active process\n\n‚Ä¢ Transpiration Pull:\n  - Main force for upward movement\n  - Water evaporates from leaves\n  - Creates suction force\n  - Pulls water up through xylem\n  - Cohesion-tension theory\n\n‚Ä¢ Translocation:\n  - Movement of food through phloem\n  - Active transport\n  - Requires energy\n\nFactors Affecting:\n‚Ä¢ Temperature, humidity, wind speed (transpiration)\n‚Ä¢ Light intensity (photosynthesis affects food transport)",
                    
                    "Human Circulatory System - Heart and Blood Vessels:\n\nThe circulatory system transports materials throughout the body.\n\nComponents:\n\n1. Heart:\n   ‚Ä¢ Four-chambered pump\n   ‚Ä¢ Chambers:\n     - Right Atrium: Receives deoxygenated blood\n     - Right Ventricle: Pumps to lungs\n     - Left Atrium: Receives oxygenated blood\n     - Left Ventricle: Pumps to body (thickest wall)\n   ‚Ä¢ Valves: Prevent backflow\n   ‚Ä¢ Heartbeat: 60-100 times per minute\n\n2. Blood Vessels:\n\n   Arteries:\n   ‚Ä¢ Carry blood away from heart\n   ‚Ä¢ Thick, elastic walls\n   ‚Ä¢ Carry oxygenated blood (except pulmonary artery)\n   ‚Ä¢ High pressure\n   ‚Ä¢ No valves (except at base)\n\n   Veins:\n   ‚Ä¢ Carry blood to heart\n   ‚Ä¢ Thin walls, less elastic\n   ‚Ä¢ Carry deoxygenated blood (except pulmonary vein)\n   ‚Ä¢ Low pressure\n   ‚Ä¢ Have valves to prevent backflow\n\n   Capillaries:\n   ‚Ä¢ Smallest blood vessels\n   ‚Ä¢ Connect arteries and veins\n   ‚Ä¢ Thin walls (one cell thick)\n   ‚Ä¢ Site of material exchange\n   ‚Ä¢ Large surface area\n\nCirculation:\n‚Ä¢ Pulmonary: Heart ‚Üí Lungs ‚Üí Heart\n‚Ä¢ Systemic: Heart ‚Üí Body ‚Üí Heart\n‚Ä¢ Double circulation (mammals and birds)",
                    
                    "Blood Components - Detailed Structure:\n\nBlood is a fluid connective tissue with four main components:\n\n1. Plasma (55%):\n   ‚Ä¢ Liquid part of blood\n   ‚Ä¢ Yellowish color\n   ‚Ä¢ Composition:\n     - Water (90%)\n     - Proteins (albumin, globulin, fibrinogen)\n     - Nutrients (glucose, amino acids, fats)\n     - Waste products (urea, CO‚ÇÇ)\n     - Hormones, enzymes\n   ‚Ä¢ Functions:\n     - Transports nutrients, hormones, waste\n     - Maintains body temperature\n     - Clotting (fibrinogen)\n\n2. Red Blood Cells (RBCs) (45%):\n   ‚Ä¢ Most numerous cells\n   ‚Ä¢ Biconcave disc shape\n   ‚Ä¢ No nucleus (mature)\n   ‚Ä¢ Contains hemoglobin (red pigment)\n   ‚Ä¢ Function: Carry oxygen\n   ‚Ä¢ Life span: 120 days\n   ‚Ä¢ Produced in: Bone marrow\n\n3. White Blood Cells (WBCs):\n   ‚Ä¢ Larger than RBCs\n   ‚Ä¢ Have nucleus\n   ‚Ä¢ Types: Neutrophils, lymphocytes, monocytes, etc.\n   ‚Ä¢ Function: Fight infections, immunity\n   ‚Ä¢ Life span: Few days to weeks\n   ‚Ä¢ Produced in: Bone marrow, lymph nodes\n\n4. Platelets:\n   ‚Ä¢ Small cell fragments\n   ‚Ä¢ No nucleus\n   ‚Ä¢ Function: Blood clotting\n   ‚Ä¢ Life span: 7-10 days\n   ‚Ä¢ Produced in: Bone marrow\n\nBlood Functions:\n‚Ä¢ Transport: O‚ÇÇ, CO‚ÇÇ, nutrients, waste, hormones\n‚Ä¢ Defense: WBCs fight pathogens\n‚Ä¢ Clotting: Prevents blood loss\n‚Ä¢ Temperature regulation",
                    
                    "Excretion - Waste Removal Systems:\n\nExcretion is the removal of waste products from the body.\n\nPlants:\n‚Ä¢ Through Stomata:\n  - Water vapor (transpiration)\n  - Oxygen (photosynthesis byproduct)\n‚Ä¢ Through Leaves:\n  - Falling leaves remove waste\n  - Some waste stored in leaves\n‚Ä¢ Through Roots:\n  - Some waste released into soil\n‚Ä¢ Storage:\n  - Resins, gums, latex\n\nHumans:\n\n1. Kidneys (Main Excretory Organs):\n   ‚Ä¢ Two bean-shaped organs\n   ‚Ä¢ Filter blood\n   ‚Ä¢ Remove: Urea, excess water, salts\n   ‚Ä¢ Produce: Urine\n   ‚Ä¢ Process:\n     - Filtration: Blood filtered in nephrons\n     - Reabsorption: Useful substances reabsorbed\n     - Secretion: Additional wastes added\n     - Urine formation: Final waste product\n\n2. Lungs:\n   ‚Ä¢ Remove: Carbon dioxide (CO‚ÇÇ)\n   ‚Ä¢ Remove: Water vapor\n   ‚Ä¢ During exhalation\n\n3. Skin:\n   ‚Ä¢ Sweat glands\n   ‚Ä¢ Remove: Water, salts, urea (in sweat)\n   ‚Ä¢ Cooling effect\n\n4. Liver:\n   ‚Ä¢ Converts ammonia ‚Üí urea\n   ‚Ä¢ Produces bile (contains waste)\n   ‚Ä¢ Detoxification\n\nExcretory Products:\n‚Ä¢ CO‚ÇÇ, H‚ÇÇO, Urea, Uric acid, Salts\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Prevents accumulation of toxic wastes\n‚Ä¢ Maintains internal environment\n‚Ä¢ Essential for survival"
                ),
                keyPoints = listOf(
                    "Nutrition in Plants and Animals: Plants are autotrophic (photosynthesis: 6CO‚ÇÇ+6H‚ÇÇO‚ÜíC‚ÇÜH‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇO‚ÇÜ+6O‚ÇÇ). Animals are heterotrophic. Human nutrition: Ingestion ‚Üí Digestion (mouth, stomach, small intestine) ‚Üí Absorption (small intestine) ‚Üí Assimilation. Digestive enzymes: Amylase (starch), Pepsin (proteins), Lipase (fats), Trypsin (proteins).",
                    "Respiration: Process to release energy from food. Aerobic: C‚ÇÜH‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇO‚ÇÜ+6O‚ÇÇ‚Üí6CO‚ÇÇ+6H‚ÇÇO+Energy (38 ATP). Anaerobic: C‚ÇÜH‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇO‚ÇÜ‚Üí2C‚ÇÉH‚ÇÜO‚ÇÉ+Energy (2 ATP) in muscles, or C‚ÇÜH‚ÇÅ‚ÇÇO‚ÇÜ‚Üí2C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÖOH+2CO‚ÇÇ+Energy in yeast. Human respiratory system: Nose ‚Üí Pharynx ‚Üí Larynx ‚Üí Trachea ‚Üí Bronchi ‚Üí Alveoli (gas exchange).",
                    "Transportation in Plants and Animals: Plants: Xylem (water/minerals up from roots, transpiration pull), Phloem (food from leaves to all parts, translocation). Animals: Blood (plasma 55%, RBCs carry O‚ÇÇ, WBCs fight infection, platelets clot), Heart (4 chambers, double circulation), Blood vessels (arteries away, veins to heart, capillaries exchange).",
                    "Excretion: Removal of metabolic wastes. Plants: Through stomata (CO‚ÇÇ, O‚ÇÇ, water vapor), falling leaves, bark. Humans: Kidneys filter blood, produce urine (urea, water, salts). Other organs: Lungs (CO‚ÇÇ), Skin (sweat: water, salts, urea), Liver (bile, converts ammonia to urea). Kidney structure: Nephrons filter blood, form urine.",
                    "Control and Coordination: Nervous system (brain, spinal cord, nerves) for quick responses. Endocrine system (hormones) for slow, long-term control. Plant hormones: Auxins (growth), Gibberellins (stem elongation), Cytokinins (cell division), Abscisic acid (dormancy). Human hormones: Insulin (blood sugar), Adrenaline (fight/flight), Growth hormone, Thyroxine (metabolism)."
