            Chapter(
                id = "science_3",
                title = "Light - Reflection and Refraction",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Reflection of Light - Complete Concept:\n\nReflection is the bouncing back of light when it strikes a surface.\n\nTwo Types:\n\n1. Regular Reflection:\n   ‚Ä¢ Occurs on smooth, polished surfaces\n   ‚Ä¢ Parallel rays remain parallel after reflection\n   ‚Ä¢ Forms clear images\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Mirror, still water\n\n2. Diffuse Reflection:\n   ‚Ä¢ Occurs on rough, uneven surfaces\n   ‚Ä¢ Parallel rays scatter in different directions\n   ‚Ä¢ No clear image formed\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Paper, wall, most objects\n\nKey Terms:\n‚Ä¢ Incident Ray: Light ray striking the surface\n‚Ä¢ Reflected Ray: Light ray bouncing back\n‚Ä¢ Normal: Perpendicular line to surface at point of incidence\n‚Ä¢ Angle of Incidence (i): Angle between incident ray and normal\n‚Ä¢ Angle of Reflection (r): Angle between reflected ray and normal\n\nReflection allows us to see non-luminous objects. All objects reflect light, which enters our eyes.",
                    
                    "Laws of Reflection - Fundamental Principles:\n\nThere are two laws of reflection:\n\nLaw 1: Angle of Incidence = Angle of Reflection\n‚Ä¢ ‚à†i = ‚à†r\n‚Ä¢ Both angles measured from normal\n‚Ä¢ Always equal, regardless of angle\n‚Ä¢ Example: If i = 30¬∞, then r = 30¬∞\n\nLaw 2: Incident Ray, Reflected Ray, and Normal Lie in Same Plane\n‚Ä¢ All three are in one plane\n‚Ä¢ Normal is perpendicular to surface\n‚Ä¢ Plane contains all three lines\n\nVerification:\n‚Ä¢ Can be verified using plane mirror and pins\n‚Ä¢ Light ray experiment confirms both laws\n‚Ä¢ Works for all surfaces (smooth and rough)\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Designing mirrors\n‚Ä¢ Understanding image formation\n‚Ä¢ Periscopes, kaleidoscopes\n‚Ä¢ Optical instruments\n\nThese laws are universal and apply to all types of reflection.",
                    
                    "Plane Mirror - Image Characteristics:\n\nA plane mirror is a flat, smooth reflecting surface.\n\nImage Properties:\n\n1. Virtual Image:\n   ‚Ä¢ Cannot be obtained on screen\n   ‚Ä¢ Formed behind mirror\n   ‚Ä¢ Light rays appear to come from behind\n\n2. Erect Image:\n   ‚Ä¢ Same orientation as object\n   ‚Ä¢ Not inverted\n\n3. Same Size:\n   ‚Ä¢ Image size = Object size\n   ‚Ä¢ No magnification\n\n4. Same Distance:\n   ‚Ä¢ Image distance = Object distance\n   ‚Ä¢ If object is 5m from mirror, image is 5m behind mirror\n\n5. Laterally Inverted:\n   ‚Ä¢ Left appears as right\n   ‚Ä¢ Right appears as left\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: 'AMBULANCE' written backwards on vehicles\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Dressing mirrors\n‚Ä¢ Periscopes\n‚Ä¢ Kaleidoscopes\n‚Ä¢ Security applications\n\nFormation:\n‚Ä¢ Light from object reflects from mirror\n‚Ä¢ Reflected rays appear to come from behind mirror\n‚Ä¢ Brain interprets as image behind mirror",
                    
                    "Spherical Mirrors - Types and Structure:\n\nSpherical mirrors have curved reflecting surfaces, part of a sphere.\n\nTwo Types:\n\n1. Concave Mirror:\n   ‚Ä¢ Inner surface is reflecting\n   ‚Ä¢ Curves inward (like a cave)\n   ‚Ä¢ Also called converging mirror\n   ‚Ä¢ Center of curvature (C) is in front\n   ‚Ä¢ Principal axis passes through C and pole (P)\n   ‚Ä¢ Focal length (f) = R/2 (R is radius)\n\n2. Convex Mirror:\n   ‚Ä¢ Outer surface is reflecting\n   ‚Ä¢ Curves outward (bulges out)\n   ‚Ä¢ Also called diverging mirror\n   ‚Ä¢ Center of curvature (C) is behind mirror\n   ‚Ä¢ Principal axis passes through C and pole (P)\n   ‚Ä¢ Focal length (f) = R/2\n\nKey Terms:\n‚Ä¢ Pole (P): Center point of mirror\n‚Ä¢ Center of Curvature (C): Center of sphere\n‚Ä¢ Radius of Curvature (R): Distance PC\n‚Ä¢ Principal Focus (F): Point where parallel rays meet/diverged from\n‚Ä¢ Focal Length (f): Distance PF = R/2\n‚Ä¢ Principal Axis: Line through P and C\n\nRay Diagrams:\n‚Ä¢ Help locate images\n‚Ä¢ Use specific rules for drawing rays\n‚Ä¢ Show image position, nature, size",
                    
                    "Concave Mirror - Image Formation:\n\nConcave mirror can form different types of images depending on object position.\n\nCases:\n\n1. Object at Infinity:\n   ‚Ä¢ Image: At focus (F)\n   ‚Ä¢ Real, inverted, highly diminished\n   ‚Ä¢ Use: Solar cookers, searchlights\n\n2. Object Beyond C:\n   ‚Ä¢ Image: Between F and C\n   ‚Ä¢ Real, inverted, diminished\n\n3. Object at C:\n   ‚Ä¢ Image: At C\n   ‚Ä¢ Real, inverted, same size\n\n4. Object Between C and F:\n   ‚Ä¢ Image: Beyond C\n   ‚Ä¢ Real, inverted, enlarged\n   ‚Ä¢ Use: Shaving mirrors (when close)\n\n5. Object at F:\n   ‚Ä¢ Image: At infinity\n   ‚Ä¢ Real, inverted, highly enlarged\n\n6. Object Between F and P:\n   ‚Ä¢ Image: Behind mirror\n   ‚Ä¢ Virtual, erect, enlarged\n   ‚Ä¢ Use: Makeup mirrors, shaving mirrors\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Shaving mirrors (enlarged image)\n‚Ä¢ Searchlights (parallel beam)\n‚Ä¢ Solar cookers (concentrate sunlight)\n‚Ä¢ Astronomical telescopes\n‚Ä¢ Headlights of vehicles\n\nMirror Formula:\n1/f = 1/v + 1/u\n‚Ä¢ f = focal length\n‚Ä¢ v = image distance\n‚Ä¢ u = object distance\n\nMagnification:\nm = -v/u = h'/h\n‚Ä¢ Negative sign indicates inverted image",
                    
                    "Convex Mirror - Always Virtual Image:\n\nConvex mirror always forms virtual, erect, diminished image regardless of object position.\n\nImage Characteristics:\n‚Ä¢ Always virtual (cannot be obtained on screen)\n‚Ä¢ Always erect (same orientation)\n‚Ä¢ Always diminished (smaller than object)\n‚Ä¢ Always behind mirror\n\nWhy Always Virtual?\n‚Ä¢ Reflected rays diverge\n‚Ä¢ Never actually meet\n‚Ä¢ Appear to come from behind mirror\n‚Ä¢ Formed by extending reflected rays backward\n\nUses:\n\n1. Rear-view Mirrors in Vehicles:\n   ‚Ä¢ Wide field of view\n   ‚Ä¢ Shows larger area\n   ‚Ä¢ Diminished but covers more\n\n2. Security Mirrors:\n   ‚Ä¢ In shops, parking lots\n   ‚Ä¢ Wide viewing angle\n   ‚Ä¢ Monitor large areas\n\n3. Street Corner Mirrors:\n   ‚Ä¢ At intersections\n   ‚Ä¢ See around corners\n   ‚Ä¢ Safety applications\n\nAdvantages:\n‚Ä¢ Wide field of view\n‚Ä¢ Always shows erect image\n‚Ä¢ Useful for safety\n\nLimitations:\n‚Ä¢ Image is always smaller\n‚Ä¢ Cannot form real images\n‚Ä¢ Less detail (diminished)\n\nMirror Formula:\n1/f = 1/v + 1/u\n‚Ä¢ f is negative (behind mirror)\n‚Ä¢ v is negative (virtual image)\n‚Ä¢ u is negative (object in front)",
                    
                    "Refraction of Light - Bending of Light:\n\nRefraction is the bending of light when it passes from one transparent medium to another.\n\nCause:\n‚Ä¢ Light changes speed in different media\n‚Ä¢ Speed in vacuum/air > Speed in water/glass\n‚Ä¢ Bending occurs due to speed change\n\nDirection of Bending:\n\n1. Entering Denser Medium:\n   ‚Ä¢ Light bends towards normal\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Air ‚Üí Water, Air ‚Üí Glass\n   ‚Ä¢ Speed decreases\n\n2. Entering Rarer Medium:\n   ‚Ä¢ Light bends away from normal\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Water ‚Üí Air, Glass ‚Üí Air\n   ‚Ä¢ Speed increases\n\nKey Terms:\n‚Ä¢ Incident Ray: Ray entering new medium\n‚Ä¢ Refracted Ray: Ray in new medium\n‚Ä¢ Normal: Perpendicular to surface\n‚Ä¢ Angle of Incidence (i): In first medium\n‚Ä¢ Angle of Refraction (r): In second medium\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ Pencil appears bent in water\n‚Ä¢ Pool appears shallower than actual\n‚Ä¢ Stars twinkle (atmospheric refraction)\n‚Ä¢ Mirage formation\n\nRefraction explains many optical phenomena we observe daily.",
                    
                    "Refractive Index - Complete Concept:\n\nRefractive index (n) measures how much light slows down in a medium.\n\nDefinition:\nn = Speed of light in vacuum / Speed of light in medium\nn = c / v\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ c = Speed of light in vacuum (3 √ó 10‚Å∏ m/s)\n‚Ä¢ v = Speed of light in medium\n‚Ä¢ n = Refractive index (dimensionless)\n\nValues:\n‚Ä¢ Vacuum: n = 1 (fastest)\n‚Ä¢ Air: n ‚âà 1.0003 (almost 1)\n‚Ä¢ Water: n ‚âà 1.33\n‚Ä¢ Glass: n ‚âà 1.5 (varies with type)\n‚Ä¢ Diamond: n ‚âà 2.42 (very high)\n\nPhysical Meaning:\n‚Ä¢ Higher n = Slower light = More bending\n‚Ä¢ Lower n = Faster light = Less bending\n\nRelative Refractive Index:\n‚Ä¢ n‚ÇÇ‚ÇÅ = n‚ÇÇ/n‚ÇÅ = v‚ÇÅ/v‚ÇÇ\n‚Ä¢ Refractive index of medium 2 w.r.t. medium 1\n\nFactors Affecting:\n‚Ä¢ Wavelength of light (dispersion)\n‚Ä¢ Temperature\n‚Ä¢ Density of medium\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Lens design\n‚Ä¢ Optical fibers\n‚Ä¢ Prisms\n‚Ä¢ Understanding refraction",
                    
                    "Snell's Law - Refraction Formula:\n\nSnell's law relates angles and refractive indices in refraction.\n\nFormula:\nn‚ÇÅsin(i) = n‚ÇÇsin(r)\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ n‚ÇÅ = Refractive index of first medium\n‚Ä¢ n‚ÇÇ = Refractive index of second medium\n‚Ä¢ i = Angle of incidence\n‚Ä¢ r = Angle of refraction\n\nDerivation:\n‚Ä¢ Based on experimental observations\n‚Ä¢ Relates angles to speed of light\n‚Ä¢ Works for all transparent media\n\nExample:\nLight enters water from air:\n‚Ä¢ n‚ÇÅ (air) = 1, n‚ÇÇ (water) = 1.33\n‚Ä¢ If i = 30¬∞:\n  1 √ó sin(30¬∞) = 1.33 √ó sin(r)\n  0.5 = 1.33 √ó sin(r)\n  sin(r) = 0.5/1.33 = 0.376\n  r = 22.1¬∞\n‚Ä¢ Light bends towards normal ‚úì\n\nTotal Internal Reflection:\n‚Ä¢ When light goes from denser to rarer medium\n‚Ä¢ If angle of incidence > critical angle\n‚Ä¢ All light reflects back (no refraction)\n‚Ä¢ Critical angle: sin(c) = n‚ÇÇ/n‚ÇÅ\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Optical fibers (communication)\n‚Ä¢ Prisms (periscopes)\n‚Ä¢ Diamond cutting (brilliance)\n‚Ä¢ Understanding mirage",
                    
                    "Lenses - Types and Properties:\n\nLenses are transparent materials (usually glass) with curved surfaces that refract light.\n\nTwo Types:\n\n1. Convex Lens (Converging):\n   ‚Ä¢ Thicker at center, thinner at edges\n   ‚Ä¢ Converges parallel rays to focus\n   ‚Ä¢ Also called converging lens\n   ‚Ä¢ Focal length is positive\n   ‚Ä¢ Can form real or virtual images\n\n2. Concave Lens (Diverging):\n   ‚Ä¢ Thinner at center, thicker at edges\n   ‚Ä¢ Diverges parallel rays\n   ‚Ä¢ Also called diverging lens\n   ‚Ä¢ Focal length is negative\n   ‚Ä¢ Always forms virtual, erect, diminished image\n\nConvex Lens Image Formation:\n‚Ä¢ Object at infinity: Real, inverted, at F\n‚Ä¢ Object beyond 2F: Real, inverted, between F and 2F\n‚Ä¢ Object at 2F: Real, inverted, at 2F (same size)\n‚Ä¢ Object between F and 2F: Real, inverted, beyond 2F (enlarged)\n‚Ä¢ Object at F: Image at infinity\n‚Ä¢ Object between F and lens: Virtual, erect, enlarged\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Convex: Camera, projector, eye, magnifying glass\n‚Ä¢ Concave: Spectacles (myopia), telescopes\n\nLens Formula:\n1/f = 1/v - 1/u\n‚Ä¢ f = focal length\n‚Ä¢ v = image distance\n‚Ä¢ u = object distance",
                    
                    "Power of Lens - Measuring Lens Strength:\n\nThe power of a lens measures its ability to converge or diverge light.\n\nFormula:\nP = 1/f\n\nWhere:\n‚Ä¢ P = Power (in Dioptres, D)\n‚Ä¢ f = Focal length (in meters)\n\nUnit:\n‚Ä¢ Dioptre (D)\n‚Ä¢ 1 D = 1/m\n\nSign Convention:\n‚Ä¢ Convex lens: Positive power (converging)\n‚Ä¢ Concave lens: Negative power (diverging)\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ f = +0.5 m: P = 1/0.5 = +2 D (convex)\n‚Ä¢ f = -0.25 m: P = 1/(-0.25) = -4 D (concave)\n‚Ä¢ f = +2 m: P = 1/2 = +0.5 D (weak convex)\n\nCombination of Lenses:\n‚Ä¢ Powers add: P = P‚ÇÅ + P‚ÇÇ\n‚Ä¢ Example: +2D and -1D: P = 2 + (-1) = +1D\n\nApplications:\n‚Ä¢ Prescribing spectacles\n‚Ä¢ Camera lenses\n‚Ä¢ Telescope design\n‚Ä¢ Understanding vision correction\n\nHigher Power:\n‚Ä¢ Shorter focal length\n‚Ä¢ More bending of light\n‚Ä¢ Stronger lens effect\n\nPower helps opticians prescribe correct lenses for vision correction."
                ),
