            Chapter(
                id = "science_4",
                title = "Acids, Bases and Salts",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Acids - Complete Definition and Properties:\n\nAcids are substances that release H‚Å∫ (hydrogen) ions in aqueous solution.\n\nArrhenius Definition:\n‚Ä¢ Acid ‚Üí H‚Å∫ + Anion\n‚Ä¢ Example: HCl ‚Üí H‚Å∫ + Cl‚Åª\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ pH < 7 (acidic)\n‚Ä¢ Turn blue litmus red\n‚Ä¢ Taste sour (lemon, vinegar, tamarind)\n‚Ä¢ Conduct electricity (due to ions)\n‚Ä¢ Corrosive in nature\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ Strong Acids (completely ionize):\n  - HCl (Hydrochloric acid)\n  - H‚ÇÇSO‚ÇÑ (Sulphuric acid)\n  - HNO‚ÇÉ (Nitric acid)\n\n‚Ä¢ Weak Acids (partially ionize):\n  - CH‚ÇÉCOOH (Acetic acid - vinegar)\n  - H‚ÇÇCO‚ÇÉ (Carbonic acid)\n  - Citric acid (in citrus fruits)\n\nChemical Reactions:\n‚Ä¢ With metals: Acid + Metal ‚Üí Salt + H‚ÇÇ\n  Example: Zn + 2HCl ‚Üí ZnCl‚ÇÇ + H‚ÇÇ\n\n‚Ä¢ With carbonates: Acid + Carbonate ‚Üí Salt + H‚ÇÇO + CO‚ÇÇ\n  Example: CaCO‚ÇÉ + 2HCl ‚Üí CaCl‚ÇÇ + H‚ÇÇO + CO‚ÇÇ\n\n‚Ä¢ With bases: Acid + Base ‚Üí Salt + H‚ÇÇO\n  Example: HCl + NaOH ‚Üí NaCl + H‚ÇÇO\n\nAcids are essential in many chemical processes and industries.",
                    
                    "Bases - Complete Definition and Properties:\n\nBases are substances that release OH‚Åª (hydroxide) ions in aqueous solution.\n\nArrhenius Definition:\n‚Ä¢ Base ‚Üí OH‚Åª + Cation\n‚Ä¢ Example: NaOH ‚Üí Na‚Å∫ + OH‚Åª\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ pH > 7 (basic/alkaline)\n‚Ä¢ Turn red litmus blue\n‚Ä¢ Taste bitter\n‚Ä¢ Feel soapy/slippery (saponification with skin oils)\n‚Ä¢ Conduct electricity (due to ions)\n‚Ä¢ Some are caustic (can cause burns)\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ Strong Bases (completely dissociate):\n  - NaOH (Sodium hydroxide - caustic soda)\n  - KOH (Potassium hydroxide)\n  - Ca(OH)‚ÇÇ (Calcium hydroxide - slaked lime)\n\n‚Ä¢ Weak Bases (partially dissociate):\n  - NH‚ÇÑOH (Ammonium hydroxide)\n  - Mg(OH)‚ÇÇ (Magnesium hydroxide)\n\nChemical Reactions:\n‚Ä¢ With acids: Base + Acid ‚Üí Salt + H‚ÇÇO\n  Example: NaOH + HCl ‚Üí NaCl + H‚ÇÇO\n\n‚Ä¢ With ammonium salts: Base + NH‚ÇÑ‚Å∫ ‚Üí Salt + H‚ÇÇO + NH‚ÇÉ\n  Example: NH‚ÇÑCl + NaOH ‚Üí NaCl + H‚ÇÇO + NH‚ÇÉ\n\n‚Ä¢ Turn turmeric paper red-brown\n\nBases neutralize acids and are used in many applications.",
                    
                    "Salts - Formation and Types:\n\nSalts are ionic compounds formed by neutralization reaction between acid and base.\n\nGeneral Reaction:\nAcid + Base ‚Üí Salt + Water\n\nExample:\nHCl + NaOH ‚Üí NaCl + H‚ÇÇO\n‚Ä¢ HCl (acid) + NaOH (base) ‚Üí NaCl (salt) + H‚ÇÇO\n\nTypes of Salts:\n\n1. Normal Salts:\n   ‚Ä¢ Complete neutralization\n   ‚Ä¢ No replaceable H‚Å∫ or OH‚Åª\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples: NaCl, Na‚ÇÇSO‚ÇÑ, KNO‚ÇÉ\n\n2. Acidic Salts:\n   ‚Ä¢ From partial neutralization of polybasic acid\n   ‚Ä¢ Contains replaceable H‚Å∫\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: NaHSO‚ÇÑ (sodium hydrogen sulphate)\n   ‚Ä¢ Formed: H‚ÇÇSO‚ÇÑ + NaOH ‚Üí NaHSO‚ÇÑ + H‚ÇÇO\n\n3. Basic Salts:\n   ‚Ä¢ From partial neutralization of polyacidic base\n   ‚Ä¢ Contains replaceable OH‚Åª\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Ca(OH)Cl (basic calcium chloride)\n\nCommon Salts and Uses:\n‚Ä¢ NaCl (Table salt): Food seasoning, preservation\n‚Ä¢ NaHCO‚ÇÉ (Baking soda): Cooking, antacid, fire extinguisher\n‚Ä¢ Na‚ÇÇCO‚ÇÉ (Washing soda): Cleaning, water softening\n‚Ä¢ CaSO‚ÇÑ (Plaster of Paris): Construction, medical casts\n‚Ä¢ CaOCl‚ÇÇ (Bleaching powder): Bleaching, disinfection\n\nSalts are essential in daily life and industries.",
                    
                    "pH Scale - Measuring Acidity and Basicity:\n\nThe pH scale measures acidity or basicity from 0 to 14.\n\nScale:\n‚Ä¢ pH = 7: Neutral (pure water)\n‚Ä¢ pH < 7: Acidic (lower = more acidic)\n‚Ä¢ pH > 7: Basic/Alkaline (higher = more basic)\n\nFormula:\npH = -log‚ÇÅ‚ÇÄ[H‚Å∫]\n\nWhere [H‚Å∫] is hydrogen ion concentration in mol/L.\n\nKey Points:\n‚Ä¢ Each unit change = 10√ó change in H‚Å∫ concentration\n‚Ä¢ pH 6 has 10√ó more H‚Å∫ than pH 7\n‚Ä¢ pH 5 has 100√ó more H‚Å∫ than pH 7\n‚Ä¢ pH 4 has 1000√ó more H‚Å∫ than pH 7\n\nUniversal Indicator Colors:\n‚Ä¢ Red (pH 1-3): Strong acid\n‚Ä¢ Orange (pH 4-5): Weak acid\n‚Ä¢ Yellow (pH 6): Very weak acid\n‚Ä¢ Green (pH 7): Neutral\n‚Ä¢ Blue (pH 8-10): Weak base\n‚Ä¢ Purple (pH 11-14): Strong base\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ Stomach acid: pH 1-2\n‚Ä¢ Lemon juice: pH 2-3\n‚Ä¢ Coffee: pH 5\n‚Ä¢ Pure water: pH 7\n‚Ä¢ Baking soda: pH 8-9\n‚Ä¢ Soap: pH 9-10\n‚Ä¢ Bleach: pH 12-13\n\npH is crucial in:\n‚Ä¢ Biology (enzyme function)\n‚Ä¢ Agriculture (soil pH)\n‚Ä¢ Medicine (blood pH)\n‚Ä¢ Industry (process control)",
                    
                    "Indicators - Detecting Acids and Bases:\n\nIndicators are substances that change color to indicate acidic or basic nature.\n\nCommon Indicators:\n\n1. Litmus:\n   ‚Ä¢ Red in acid\n   ‚Ä¢ Blue in base\n   ‚Ä¢ Most common indicator\n   ‚Ä¢ Available as solution or paper\n\n2. Phenolphthalein:\n   ‚Ä¢ Colorless in acid\n   ‚Ä¢ Pink in base\n   ‚Ä¢ Used in titrations\n   ‚Ä¢ Clear color change\n\n3. Methyl Orange:\n   ‚Ä¢ Red in acid\n   ‚Ä¢ Yellow in base\n   ‚Ä¢ Used in acid-base titrations\n   ‚Ä¢ Good for weak bases\n\n4. Universal Indicator:\n   ‚Ä¢ Shows full pH range\n   ‚Ä¢ Different colors for different pH\n   ‚Ä¢ Red ‚Üí Orange ‚Üí Yellow ‚Üí Green ‚Üí Blue ‚Üí Purple\n   ‚Ä¢ Most comprehensive\n\nNatural Indicators:\n‚Ä¢ Turmeric:\n  - Yellow in acid\n  - Red-brown in base\n  - Used in cooking\n\n‚Ä¢ Red Cabbage:\n  - Red/pink in acid\n  - Green/blue in base\n  - Natural pH indicator\n\n‚Ä¢ China Rose:\n  - Pink in acid\n  - Green in base\n\nHow They Work:\n‚Ä¢ Indicators are weak acids/bases\n‚Ä¢ Different colors in acid and base forms\n‚Ä¢ Color change at specific pH\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Quick identification of acid/base\n‚Ä¢ Titrations (finding concentration)\n‚Ä¢ Educational demonstrations\n‚Ä¢ Testing unknown solutions",
                    
                    "Neutralization Reaction - Acid-Base Reaction:\n\nNeutralization is the reaction between acid and base to form salt and water.\n\nGeneral Form:\nAcid + Base ‚Üí Salt + Water\n\nExample:\nHCl + NaOH ‚Üí NaCl + H‚ÇÇO\n‚Ä¢ Hydrochloric acid + Sodium hydroxide\n‚Ä¢ ‚Üí Sodium chloride + Water\n\nCharacteristics:\n‚Ä¢ Heat is usually evolved (exothermic)\n‚Ä¢ pH moves towards 7\n‚Ä¢ Complete when moles of H‚Å∫ = moles of OH‚Åª\n‚Ä¢ Forms neutral solution (pH = 7)\n\nIonic Equation:\nH‚Å∫ + OH‚Åª ‚Üí H‚ÇÇO\n\nApplications:\n\n1. Antacid Tablets:\n   ‚Ä¢ Neutralize excess stomach acid\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Mg(OH)‚ÇÇ + 2HCl ‚Üí MgCl‚ÇÇ + 2H‚ÇÇO\n   ‚Ä¢ Relieves acidity\n\n2. Soil Treatment:\n   ‚Ä¢ Add lime (CaO/Ca(OH)‚ÇÇ) to acidic soil\n   ‚Ä¢ Raises pH for better crop growth\n   ‚Ä¢ Ca(OH)‚ÇÇ + H‚ÇÇSO‚ÇÑ ‚Üí CaSO‚ÇÑ + 2H‚ÇÇO\n\n3. Industrial Processes:\n   ‚Ä¢ Wastewater treatment\n   ‚Ä¢ Chemical manufacturing\n   ‚Ä¢ pH control in reactions\n\n4. Bee Sting Treatment:\n   ‚Ä¢ Bee sting is acidic\n   ‚Ä¢ Apply baking soda (base) to neutralize\n\n5. Wasp Sting Treatment:\n   ‚Ä¢ Wasp sting is basic\n   ‚Ä¢ Apply vinegar (acid) to neutralize\n\nNeutralization is fundamental in chemistry and daily life.",
                    
                    "Properties of Acids - Chemical Behavior:\n\nAcids have characteristic chemical properties:\n\n1. Reaction with Active Metals:\n   ‚Ä¢ Produce hydrogen gas\n   ‚Ä¢ General: Acid + Metal ‚Üí Salt + H‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Zn + 2HCl ‚Üí ZnCl‚ÇÇ + H‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Mg + H‚ÇÇSO‚ÇÑ ‚Üí MgSO‚ÇÑ + H‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Not all metals react (depends on reactivity)\n   ‚Ä¢ Metals above H in reactivity series react\n\n2. Reaction with Metal Carbonates/Bicarbonates:\n   ‚Ä¢ Produce carbon dioxide\n   ‚Ä¢ General: Acid + Carbonate ‚Üí Salt + H‚ÇÇO + CO‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: CaCO‚ÇÉ + 2HCl ‚Üí CaCl‚ÇÇ + H‚ÇÇO + CO‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: NaHCO‚ÇÉ + HCl ‚Üí NaCl + H‚ÇÇO + CO‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Used to test for carbonates\n\n3. Reaction with Bases:\n   ‚Ä¢ Form salts and water\n   ‚Ä¢ Neutralization reaction\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: HCl + NaOH ‚Üí NaCl + H‚ÇÇO\n\n4. Electrical Conductivity:\n   ‚Ä¢ Conduct electricity in aqueous solution\n   ‚Ä¢ Due to presence of ions (H‚Å∫ and anions)\n   ‚Ä¢ Stronger acid = better conductor\n\n5. Corrosive Nature:\n   ‚Ä¢ Can damage materials\n   ‚Ä¢ Strong acids are dangerous\n   ‚Ä¢ Can cause burns on skin\n   ‚Ä¢ Handle with care\n\n6. pH < 7:\n   ‚Ä¢ Acidic nature\n   ‚Ä¢ Lower pH = stronger acid\n\nThese properties help identify and use acids safely.",
                    
                    "Properties of Bases - Chemical Behavior:\n\nBases have characteristic chemical properties:\n\n1. Reaction with Acids:\n   ‚Ä¢ Form salts and water\n   ‚Ä¢ Neutralization reaction\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: NaOH + HCl ‚Üí NaCl + H‚ÇÇO\n   ‚Ä¢ Heat is evolved\n\n2. Soapy/Slippery Feel:\n   ‚Ä¢ Due to saponification reaction\n   ‚Ä¢ Reacts with skin oils\n   ‚Ä¢ Forms soap-like substance\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: NaOH with skin\n\n3. Electrical Conductivity:\n   ‚Ä¢ Conduct electricity in aqueous solution\n   ‚Ä¢ Due to presence of ions (OH‚Åª and cations)\n   ‚Ä¢ Stronger base = better conductor\n\n4. Caustic Nature:\n   ‚Ä¢ Some bases are very corrosive\n   ‚Ä¢ NaOH, KOH can cause severe burns\n   ‚Ä¢ Handle with extreme care\n   ‚Ä¢ Can damage organic materials\n\n5. Reaction with Ammonium Salts:\n   ‚Ä¢ Produce ammonia gas\n   ‚Ä¢ General: Base + NH‚ÇÑ‚Å∫ ‚Üí Salt + H‚ÇÇO + NH‚ÇÉ\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: NH‚ÇÑCl + NaOH ‚Üí NaCl + H‚ÇÇO + NH‚ÇÉ\n   ‚Ä¢ Used to test for ammonium salts\n\n6. Effect on Turmeric:\n   ‚Ä¢ Turn turmeric paper red-brown\n   ‚Ä¢ Natural indicator test\n   ‚Ä¢ Yellow turmeric ‚Üí Red-brown in base\n\n7. pH > 7:\n   ‚Ä¢ Basic/alkaline nature\n   ‚Ä¢ Higher pH = stronger base\n\nUnderstanding these properties helps use bases safely and effectively.",
                    
                    "Uses of Acids - Applications:\n\nAcids have numerous important uses:\n\n1. Hydrochloric Acid (HCl):\n   ‚Ä¢ Cleaning: Remove rust, scale\n   ‚Ä¢ Pickling steel: Clean metal surfaces\n   ‚Ä¢ Food processing: pH control\n   ‚Ä¢ Laboratory: Common reagent\n\n2. Sulphuric Acid (H‚ÇÇSO‚ÇÑ):\n   ‚Ä¢ Battery acid: Lead-acid batteries\n   ‚Ä¢ Fertilizers: Superphosphate, ammonium sulphate\n   ‚Ä¢ Detergents: Manufacturing\n   ‚Ä¢ Chemical industry: Many processes\n   ‚Ä¢ Drying agent: Removes water\n   ‚Ä¢ Most widely used acid\n\n3. Nitric Acid (HNO‚ÇÉ):\n   ‚Ä¢ Fertilizers: Ammonium nitrate\n   ‚Ä¢ Explosives: TNT, dynamite\n   ‚Ä¢ Dyes: Manufacturing\n   ‚Ä¢ Etching: Metal processing\n\n4. Acetic Acid (CH‚ÇÉCOOH):\n   ‚Ä¢ Vinegar: Food (5-8% solution)\n   ‚Ä¢ Food preservative\n   ‚Ä¢ Pickling: Preserve vegetables\n   ‚Ä¢ Chemical synthesis\n\n5. Citric Acid:\n   ‚Ä¢ Food and beverages: Flavoring\n   ‚Ä¢ Preservative: Extend shelf life\n   ‚Ä¢ Cleaning: Remove stains\n\n6. Ascorbic Acid:\n   ‚Ä¢ Vitamin C: Health supplement\n   ‚Ä¢ Antioxidant: Food preservation\n\nAcids are essential in modern industry and daily life.",
                    
