            Chapter(
                id = "science_5",
                title = "Metals and Non-metals",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Physical Properties of Metals - Complete List:\n\nMetals have characteristic physical properties:\n\n1. Shiny Luster:\n   ‚Ä¢ Metallic shine\n   ‚Ä¢ Reflect light\n   ‚Ä¢ Polished surface\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Gold, silver\n\n2. Malleable:\n   ‚Ä¢ Can be hammered into thin sheets\n   ‚Ä¢ Without breaking\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Gold (most malleable)\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Aluminum foil\n\n3. Ductile:\n   ‚Ä¢ Can be drawn into wires\n   ‚Ä¢ Stretched without breaking\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Copper, silver\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Electrical wires\n\n4. Good Conductors:\n   ‚Ä¢ Heat: Transfer heat easily\n   ‚Ä¢ Electricity: Allow current flow\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Silver (best conductor)\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Electrical wiring, cooking utensils\n\n5. High Melting and Boiling Points:\n   ‚Ä¢ Most are solid at room temperature\n   ‚Ä¢ Exception: Mercury (liquid)\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Iron (1538¬∞C), Copper (1085¬∞C)\n\n6. Sonorous:\n   ‚Ä¢ Make ringing sound when struck\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Bells, musical instruments\n\n7. Hard and Strong:\n   ‚Ä¢ Most are hard (except Na, K)\n   ‚Ä¢ High tensile strength\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Construction\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ Iron, Copper, Aluminum, Gold, Silver, Zinc\n\nThese properties make metals essential for:\n‚Ä¢ Construction\n‚Ä¢ Electrical applications\n‚Ä¢ Manufacturing\n‚Ä¢ Jewelry\n‚Ä¢ Transportation",
                    
                    "Physical Properties of Non-metals - Complete List:\n\nNon-metals have different physical properties:\n\n1. Dull Appearance:\n   ‚Ä¢ No metallic luster\n   ‚Ä¢ Not shiny\n   ‚Ä¢ Exception: Diamond, iodine\n\n2. Brittle:\n   ‚Ä¢ Break easily when hammered\n   ‚Ä¢ Cannot be hammered into sheets\n   ‚Ä¢ Cannot be drawn into wires\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Sulfur, phosphorus\n\n3. Poor Conductors:\n   ‚Ä¢ Heat: Do not transfer heat well\n   ‚Ä¢ Electricity: Do not conduct (insulators)\n   ‚Ä¢ Exception: Graphite (conducts electricity)\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Insulation materials\n\n4. Low Melting and Boiling Points:\n   ‚Ä¢ Many are gases at room temperature\n   ‚Ä¢ Some are liquids\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Bromine (liquid)\n\n5. Non-sonorous:\n   ‚Ä¢ Do not make ringing sound\n   ‚Ä¢ Break when struck\n\n6. Exist in All Three States:\n   ‚Ä¢ Solid: Carbon, sulfur, phosphorus\n   ‚Ä¢ Liquid: Bromine\n   ‚Ä¢ Gas: Oxygen, nitrogen, hydrogen, chlorine\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ Carbon, Sulfur, Oxygen, Nitrogen, Chlorine, Phosphorus\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Based on their specific properties\n‚Ä¢ Essential for life (oxygen, nitrogen)\n‚Ä¢ Industrial applications\n‚Ä¢ Chemical processes",
                    
                    "Chemical Properties of Metals - Reactions:\n\nMetals have characteristic chemical behavior:\n\n1. Lose Electrons:\n   ‚Ä¢ Form positive ions (cations)\n   ‚Ä¢ M ‚Üí M‚Åø‚Å∫ + ne‚Åª\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Na ‚Üí Na‚Å∫ + e‚Åª\n   ‚Ä¢ Tendency decreases down reactivity series\n\n2. React with Oxygen:\n   ‚Ä¢ Form basic oxides\n   ‚Ä¢ 4Na + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2Na‚ÇÇO (sodium oxide)\n   ‚Ä¢ 2Mg + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2MgO (magnesium oxide)\n   ‚Ä¢ Basic oxides react with water to form bases\n\n3. React with Acids:\n   ‚Ä¢ Produce hydrogen gas\n   ‚Ä¢ Metal + Acid ‚Üí Salt + H‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Zn + 2HCl ‚Üí ZnCl‚ÇÇ + H‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Only metals above H in reactivity series\n   ‚Ä¢ Metals below H don't react\n\n4. Displacement Reactions:\n   ‚Ä¢ More reactive metal displaces less reactive\n   ‚Ä¢ Zn + CuSO‚ÇÑ ‚Üí ZnSO‚ÇÑ + Cu\n   ‚Ä¢ Fe + CuSO‚ÇÑ ‚Üí FeSO‚ÇÑ + Cu\n   ‚Ä¢ Based on reactivity series\n\n5. React with Water:\n   ‚Ä¢ Highly reactive: Na, K (vigorous)\n   ‚Ä¢ Moderately reactive: Ca, Mg (with steam)\n   ‚Ä¢ Less reactive: Fe (with steam only)\n   ‚Ä¢ 2Na + 2H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí 2NaOH + H‚ÇÇ\n\nReactivity decreases: K > Na > Ca > Mg > Al > Zn > Fe > Pb > H > Cu > Ag > Au",
                    
                    "Chemical Properties of Non-metals - Reactions:\n\nNon-metals have different chemical behavior:\n\n1. Gain Electrons:\n   ‚Ä¢ Form negative ions (anions)\n   ‚Ä¢ Non-metal + e‚Åª ‚Üí Non-metal ion\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Cl + e‚Åª ‚Üí Cl‚Åª\n   ‚Ä¢ Tendency increases with electronegativity\n\n2. React with Oxygen:\n   ‚Ä¢ Form acidic or neutral oxides\n   ‚Ä¢ C + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí CO‚ÇÇ (acidic - carbonic acid)\n   ‚Ä¢ S + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí SO‚ÇÇ (acidic - sulfurous acid)\n   ‚Ä¢ H‚ÇÇ + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2H‚ÇÇO (neutral)\n   ‚Ä¢ Acidic oxides react with water to form acids\n\n3. Generally Don't React with Acids:\n   ‚Ä¢ Most non-metals don't react\n   ‚Ä¢ Exception: Carbon with concentrated acids\n   ‚Ä¢ C + 4HNO‚ÇÉ ‚Üí CO‚ÇÇ + 4NO‚ÇÇ + 2H‚ÇÇO\n\n4. Oxidizing Agents:\n   ‚Ä¢ Accept electrons\n   ‚Ä¢ Get reduced themselves\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: O‚ÇÇ, Cl‚ÇÇ, F‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Strong oxidizing agents\n\n5. React with Metals:\n   ‚Ä¢ Form ionic compounds\n   ‚Ä¢ 2Na + Cl‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2NaCl\n   ‚Ä¢ Mg + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2MgO\n\n6. React with Each Other:\n   ‚Ä¢ Form covalent compounds\n   ‚Ä¢ H‚ÇÇ + Cl‚ÇÇ ‚Üí 2HCl\n   ‚Ä¢ C + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí CO‚ÇÇ\n\nHighly Reactive Non-metals:\n‚Ä¢ Chlorine, Oxygen, Fluorine\n‚Ä¢ Form compounds easily",
                    
                    "Reactivity Series - Complete Order:\n\nThe reactivity series orders metals from most to least reactive.\n\nOrder:\nK > Na > Ca > Mg > Al > Zn > Fe > Pb > H > Cu > Ag > Au\n\n(Most reactive) ‚Üí (Least reactive)\n\nKey Points:\n\n1. Displacement:\n   ‚Ä¢ More reactive metal displaces less reactive\n   ‚Ä¢ Zn + CuSO‚ÇÑ ‚Üí ZnSO‚ÇÑ + Cu (Zn more reactive)\n   ‚Ä¢ Cu + ZnSO‚ÇÑ ‚Üí No reaction (Cu less reactive)\n\n2. Reaction with Acids:\n   ‚Ä¢ Metals above H: React with acids ‚Üí H‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Metals below H: Don't react with acids\n   ‚Ä¢ Zn + 2HCl ‚Üí ZnCl‚ÇÇ + H‚ÇÇ ‚úì\n   ‚Ä¢ Cu + 2HCl ‚Üí No reaction ‚úó\n\n3. Extraction Methods:\n   ‚Ä¢ Highly reactive (K, Na, Ca): Electrolysis\n   ‚Ä¢ Moderately reactive (Zn, Fe, Pb): Reduction with carbon\n   ‚Ä¢ Less reactive (Cu, Ag, Au): Heating or found free\n\n4. Occurrence in Nature:\n   ‚Ä¢ Highly reactive: Always in compounds\n   ‚Ä¢ Less reactive: Found free (Au, Ag, Pt)\n\n5. Reducing Power:\n   ‚Ä¢ More reactive = Better reducing agent\n   ‚Ä¢ K is strongest reducing agent\n\nMust memorize this series for problem solving!",
                    
                    "Metallurgy - Extracting Metals from Ores:\n\nMetallurgy is the process of extracting metals from their ores.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Concentration of Ore:\n   ‚Ä¢ Remove impurities (gangue)\n   ‚Ä¢ Methods: Froth floatation, magnetic separation\n   ‚Ä¢ Get pure ore\n\n2. Conversion to Oxide:\n   ‚Ä¢ Roasting: Sulfide ores + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí Oxide + SO‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Calcination: Carbonate ores ‚Üí Oxide + CO‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: ZnS + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí ZnO + SO‚ÇÇ\n\n3. Reduction to Metal:\n   ‚Ä¢ Remove oxygen from oxide\n   ‚Ä¢ Use reducing agent:\n     - Carbon (for Zn, Fe, Pb)\n     - Aluminum (for Cr, Mn)\n     - Electrolysis (for K, Na, Ca)\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Fe‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ + 3C ‚Üí 2Fe + 3CO\n\n4. Refining:\n   ‚Ä¢ Purification of metal\n   ‚Ä¢ Remove remaining impurities\n   ‚Ä¢ Methods: Electrolysis, distillation\n\nMethods by Reactivity:\n\n‚Ä¢ Highly Reactive (K, Na, Ca, Mg, Al):\n  - Electrolysis of molten compounds\n  - Cannot use carbon (forms carbides)\n\n‚Ä¢ Moderately Reactive (Zn, Fe, Pb, Sn):\n  - Reduction with carbon (coke)\n  - In blast furnace\n  - Example: Iron from hematite (Fe‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ)\n\n‚Ä¢ Less Reactive (Cu, Ag, Au):\n  - Heating (for Cu)\n  - Found free in nature (Au, Ag)\n\nExample - Iron Extraction:\nFe‚ÇÇO‚ÇÉ + 3CO ‚Üí 2Fe + 3CO‚ÇÇ (in blast furnace)",
                    
                    "Alloys - Improving Metal Properties:\n\nAlloys are homogeneous mixtures of metals or metal with non-metal.\n\nPurpose:\n‚Ä¢ Improve properties of pure metals\n‚Ä¢ Get desired characteristics\n‚Ä¢ Better than individual metals\n\nCommon Alloys:\n\n1. Steel (Fe + C):\n   ‚Ä¢ Stronger than iron\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Construction, tools\n   ‚Ä¢ Types: Mild steel, stainless steel\n\n2. Bronze (Cu + Sn):\n   ‚Ä¢ Harder than copper\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Statues, coins, tools\n   ‚Ä¢ Historical importance\n\n3. Brass (Cu + Zn):\n   ‚Ä¢ More malleable\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Musical instruments, decorative items\n   ‚Ä¢ Golden appearance\n\n4. Stainless Steel (Fe + Cr + Ni):\n   ‚Ä¢ Rust-resistant\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Utensils, medical instruments\n   ‚Ä¢ Doesn't corrode easily\n\n5. Solder (Pb + Sn):\n   ‚Ä¢ Low melting point\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Joining metals, electronics\n   ‚Ä¢ Easy to work with\n\n6. Duralumin (Al + Cu + Mg + Mn):\n   ‚Ä¢ Light and strong\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Aircraft, vehicles\n\nProperties Improved:\n‚Ä¢ Increased strength\n‚Ä¢ Corrosion resistance\n‚Ä¢ Lower melting point\n‚Ä¢ Better appearance\n‚Ä¢ Specific properties for uses\n\nAlloys are essential in modern technology.",
                    
                    "Corrosion - Metal Deterioration:\n\nCorrosion is slow deterioration of metals due to reaction with environment.\n\nRusting of Iron:\n‚Ä¢ Most common example\n‚Ä¢ Chemical reaction: 4Fe + 3O‚ÇÇ + 6H‚ÇÇO ‚Üí 4Fe(OH)‚ÇÉ\n‚Ä¢ Requires: Iron + Oxygen + Water (moisture)\n‚Ä¢ Forms: Hydrated ferric oxide (rust)\n‚Ä¢ Reddish-brown, flaky substance\n‚Ä¢ Weakens the metal\n\nFactors Affecting:\n‚Ä¢ Presence of moisture\n‚Ä¢ Presence of oxygen\n‚Ä¢ Acids/salts (accelerate)\n‚Ä¢ Temperature (higher = faster)\n‚Ä¢ Impurities in metal\n\nPrevention Methods:\n\n1. Painting:\n   ‚Ä¢ Creates barrier\n   ‚Ä¢ Prevents contact with air/water\n   ‚Ä¢ Common for iron objects\n\n2. Galvanization:\n   ‚Ä¢ Coating with zinc\n   ‚Ä¢ Zinc protects iron (sacrificial protection)\n   ‚Ä¢ Used: Pipes, buckets, car bodies\n\n3. Alloying:\n   ‚Ä¢ Making stainless steel\n   ‚Ä¢ More resistant to corrosion\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Fe + Cr + Ni\n\n4. Oiling/Greasing:\n   ‚Ä¢ Temporary protection\n   ‚Ä¢ For machinery parts\n\n5. Electroplating:\n   ‚Ä¢ Coating with another metal\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Chromium plating\n\nEconomic Impact:\n‚Ä¢ Huge losses worldwide\n‚Ä¢ Prevention is important\n‚Ä¢ Saves resources and money",
                    
                    "Uses of Metals - Applications:\n\nEach metal has specific uses based on properties:\n\n1. Iron:\n   ‚Ä¢ Construction: Buildings, bridges\n   ‚Ä¢ Machinery: Tools, equipment\n   ‚Ä¢ Vehicles: Cars, trains\n   ‚Ä¢ Most widely used metal\n\n2. Copper:\n   ‚Ä¢ Electrical wires: Best conductor after silver\n   ‚Ä¢ Coins: Currency\n   ‚Ä¢ Utensils: Cooking\n   ‚Ä¢ Plumbing: Pipes\n\n3. Aluminum:\n   ‚Ä¢ Aircraft: Lightweight\n   ‚Ä¢ Packaging: Foils, cans\n   ‚Ä¢ Construction: Windows, doors\n   ‚Ä¢ Electrical: Transmission lines\n\n4. Gold/Silver:\n   ‚Ä¢ Jewelry: Ornaments\n   ‚Ä¢ Coins: Currency\n   ‚Ä¢ Electronics: Circuits\n   ‚Ä¢ Medical: Dental fillings\n\n5. Zinc:\n   ‚Ä¢ Galvanization: Protecting iron\n   ‚Ä¢ Batteries: Dry cells\n   ‚Ä¢ Alloys: Brass\n\n6. Lead:\n   ‚Ä¢ Batteries: Car batteries\n   ‚Ä¢ Radiation shielding: X-rays\n   ‚Ä¢ Pipes: (now less common)\n\n7. Mercury:\n   ‚Ä¢ Thermometers: Liquid metal\n   ‚Ä¢ Barometers: Pressure measurement\n\nUses depend on:\n‚Ä¢ Conductivity\n‚Ä¢ Strength\n‚Ä¢ Reactivity\n‚Ä¢ Cost\n‚Ä¢ Availability",
                    
