            Chapter(
                id = "science_6",
                title = "Carbon and its Compounds",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Covalent Bonding - Sharing Electrons:\n\nCovalent bonding is chemical bonding where atoms share electrons to achieve stable electron configuration.\n\nWhy Carbon Forms Covalent Bonds:\n‚Ä¢ Carbon has 4 valence electrons\n‚Ä¢ Needs 4 more to complete octet\n‚Ä¢ Cannot easily gain or lose 4 electrons\n‚Ä¢ Sharing is most stable option\n\nTypes of Sharing:\n‚Ä¢ Single bond: 1 pair of electrons shared\n‚Ä¢ Double bond: 2 pairs of electrons shared\n‚Ä¢ Triple bond: 3 pairs of electrons shared\n\nExample - Methane (CH‚ÇÑ):\n‚Ä¢ Carbon shares 4 electrons\n‚Ä¢ 1 electron with each of 4 hydrogen atoms\n‚Ä¢ Each H shares 1 electron with C\n‚Ä¢ All atoms achieve stable configuration\n‚Ä¢ Formula: CH‚ÇÑ\n\nProperties of Covalent Compounds:\n‚Ä¢ Low melting and boiling points\n‚Ä¢ Don't conduct electricity (no ions)\n‚Ä¢ Generally insoluble in water\n‚Ä¢ Formed by non-metals\n‚Ä¢ Weak intermolecular forces\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Forms basis of organic chemistry\n‚Ä¢ All life is based on carbon compounds\n‚Ä¢ Essential for understanding chemistry\n\nCovalent bonding allows carbon to form millions of compounds, making it the basis of life.",
                    
                    "Hydrocarbons - Carbon and Hydrogen Compounds:\n\nHydrocarbons are organic compounds containing only carbon and hydrogen atoms.\n\nSimplest Hydrocarbon:\n‚Ä¢ Methane (CH‚ÇÑ)\n‚Ä¢ 1 carbon, 4 hydrogen atoms\n‚Ä¢ Natural gas component\n\nTypes:\n\n1. Alkanes:\n   ‚Ä¢ Only single bonds\n   ‚Ä¢ Saturated (maximum H)\n   ‚Ä¢ General formula: C‚ÇôH‚ÇÇ‚Çô‚Çä‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples: Methane (CH‚ÇÑ), Ethane (C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÜ), Propane (C‚ÇÉH‚Çà)\n   ‚Ä¢ Less reactive\n\n2. Alkenes:\n   ‚Ä¢ One double bond\n   ‚Ä¢ Unsaturated (can add H)\n   ‚Ä¢ General formula: C‚ÇôH‚ÇÇ‚Çô\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples: Ethene (C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÑ), Propene (C‚ÇÉH‚ÇÜ)\n   ‚Ä¢ More reactive\n\n3. Alkynes:\n   ‚Ä¢ One triple bond\n   ‚Ä¢ Unsaturated (can add H)\n   ‚Ä¢ General formula: C‚ÇôH‚ÇÇ‚Çô‚Çã‚ÇÇ\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples: Ethyne (C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÇ), Propyne (C‚ÇÉH‚ÇÑ)\n   ‚Ä¢ Most reactive\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Fuels: Petroleum, natural gas, LPG\n‚Ä¢ Manufacturing: Plastics, chemicals\n‚Ä¢ Industrial processes\n‚Ä¢ Energy source\n\nHydrocarbons are the foundation of the petrochemical industry and modern energy systems.",
                    
                    "Saturated and Unsaturated Compounds - Bond Types:\n\nClassification based on types of bonds:\n\nSaturated Hydrocarbons:\n‚Ä¢ Only single bonds (C-C)\n‚Ä¢ All carbon atoms have maximum hydrogen\n‚Ä¢ Cannot add more hydrogen\n‚Ä¢ Example: Ethane (C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÜ)\n‚Ä¢ Less reactive\n‚Ä¢ General formula: C‚ÇôH‚ÇÇ‚Çô‚Çä‚ÇÇ (alkanes)\n\nUnsaturated Hydrocarbons:\n‚Ä¢ Have double or triple bonds\n‚Ä¢ Can add more hydrogen\n‚Ä¢ Example: Ethene (C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÑ) has double bond\n‚Ä¢ More reactive\n‚Ä¢ Types:\n  - Alkenes: C‚ÇôH‚ÇÇ‚Çô (double bond)\n  - Alkynes: C‚ÇôH‚ÇÇ‚Çô‚Çã‚ÇÇ (triple bond)\n\nTest for Unsaturation:\n‚Ä¢ Add bromine water\n‚Ä¢ Unsaturated: Decolorizes (brown ‚Üí colorless)\n‚Ä¢ Saturated: No change\n\nIn Fats:\n‚Ä¢ Saturated fats: Solid at room temperature\n‚Ä¢ Unsaturated fats: Liquid at room temperature\n‚Ä¢ Health implications differ\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Food industry: Oils and fats\n‚Ä¢ Chemical synthesis: Starting materials\n‚Ä¢ Manufacturing: Plastics, polymers\n\nUnderstanding saturation is important for chemistry and health.",
                    
                    "Functional Groups - Determining Properties:\n\nFunctional groups are specific groups of atoms that determine chemical properties of organic compounds.\n\nCommon Functional Groups:\n\n1. -OH (Hydroxyl):\n   ‚Ä¢ Alcohols\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples: Methanol (CH‚ÇÉOH), Ethanol (C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÖOH)\n   ‚Ä¢ Properties: Soluble in water, can form hydrogen bonds\n\n2. -COOH (Carboxyl):\n   ‚Ä¢ Carboxylic acids\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples: Formic acid (HCOOH), Acetic acid (CH‚ÇÉCOOH)\n   ‚Ä¢ Properties: Acidic, react with bases\n\n3. -CHO (Aldehyde):\n   ‚Ä¢ Aldehydes\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Formaldehyde (HCHO)\n   ‚Ä¢ Properties: Reducing agents, reactive\n\n4. -CO- (Carbonyl):\n   ‚Ä¢ Ketones\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Acetone (CH‚ÇÉCOCH‚ÇÉ)\n   ‚Ä¢ Properties: Less reactive than aldehydes\n\n5. -NH‚ÇÇ (Amino):\n   ‚Ä¢ Amines\n   ‚Ä¢ Properties: Basic, form salts\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Determine chemical behavior\n‚Ä¢ Predict reactions\n‚Ä¢ Classify compounds\n‚Ä¢ Essential for organic chemistry\n\nFunctional groups are like 'chemical personalities' - they determine how compounds behave.",
                    
                    "Isomerism - Same Formula, Different Structure:\n\nIsomerism occurs when compounds have the same molecular formula but different structural arrangements.\n\nDefinition:\n‚Ä¢ Same number of atoms\n‚Ä¢ Different arrangement\n‚Ä¢ Different properties\n\nTypes:\n\n1. Structural Isomers:\n   ‚Ä¢ Different connectivity of atoms\n   ‚Ä¢ Different bonding patterns\n   ‚Ä¢ Example: Butane (C‚ÇÑH‚ÇÅ‚ÇÄ)\n     - n-butane: Straight chain\n     - Isobutane: Branched chain\n\n2. Geometric Isomers:\n   ‚Ä¢ Same connectivity\n   ‚Ä¢ Different spatial arrangement\n   ‚Ä¢ In compounds with double bonds\n\nExample - Butane Isomers:\n‚Ä¢ n-butane: CH‚ÇÉ-CH‚ÇÇ-CH‚ÇÇ-CH‚ÇÉ (straight)\n‚Ä¢ Isobutane: CH‚ÇÉ-CH(CH‚ÇÉ)-CH‚ÇÉ (branched)\n‚Ä¢ Same formula: C‚ÇÑH‚ÇÅ‚ÇÄ\n‚Ä¢ Different properties:\n  - Different boiling points\n  - Different reactivities\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Understanding organic chemistry\n‚Ä¢ Drug design (different isomers have different effects)\n‚Ä¢ Explains variety of compounds\n‚Ä¢ Essential for biochemistry\n\nIsomerism explains why the same atoms can form different compounds with different properties.",
                    
                    "Alcohols - Hydroxyl Group Compounds:\n\nAlcohols are organic compounds with -OH (hydroxyl) functional group.\n\nGeneral Formula:\nR-OH\n\nWhere R is an alkyl group (carbon chain).\n\nExamples:\n\n1. Methanol (CH‚ÇÉOH):\n   ‚Ä¢ Simplest alcohol\n   ‚Ä¢ Used as fuel\n   ‚Ä¢ Industrial solvent\n   ‚Ä¢ Toxic if ingested\n\n2. Ethanol (C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÖOH):\n   ‚Ä¢ Alcoholic beverages\n   ‚Ä¢ Fuel (biofuel)\n   ‚Ä¢ Solvent\n   ‚Ä¢ Antiseptic\n   ‚Ä¢ Industrial chemical\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Soluble in water (form hydrogen bonds)\n‚Ä¢ Higher boiling points than hydrocarbons\n‚Ä¢ Can form hydrogen bonds\n‚Ä¢ Polar molecules\n‚Ä¢ Volatile\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Fuels: Ethanol as biofuel\n‚Ä¢ Solvents: Industrial and laboratory\n‚Ä¢ Beverages: Alcoholic drinks\n‚Ä¢ Antiseptics: Medical use\n‚Ä¢ Industrial chemicals: Manufacturing\n‚Ä¢ Preservatives: Food industry\n\nReactions:\n‚Ä¢ Combustion: Burn to produce CO‚ÇÇ and H‚ÇÇO\n‚Ä¢ Oxidation: Form aldehydes/carboxylic acids\n‚Ä¢ Esterification: Form esters with acids\n\nAlcohols are versatile compounds with many applications in daily life and industry.",
                    
                    "Carboxylic Acids - Acidic Organic Compounds:\n\nCarboxylic acids are organic compounds with -COOH (carboxyl) functional group.\n\nGeneral Formula:\nR-COOH\n\nWhere R is an alkyl group.\n\nExamples:\n\n1. Formic Acid (HCOOH):\n   ‚Ä¢ Simplest carboxylic acid\n   ‚Ä¢ Found in ant stings\n   ‚Ä¢ Industrial chemical\n\n2. Acetic Acid (CH‚ÇÉCOOH):\n   ‚Ä¢ Vinegar (5-8% solution)\n   ‚Ä¢ Food preservative\n   ‚Ä¢ Industrial chemical\n   ‚Ä¢ Most common carboxylic acid\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Weak acids (partially ionize)\n‚Ä¢ Sour taste\n‚Ä¢ React with bases to form salts\n‚Ä¢ Higher boiling points (hydrogen bonding)\n‚Ä¢ Soluble in water\n\nReactions:\n‚Ä¢ With bases: Form salts\n  CH‚ÇÉCOOH + NaOH ‚Üí CH‚ÇÉCOONa + H‚ÇÇO\n‚Ä¢ Esterification: Form esters with alcohols\n‚Ä¢ Decarboxylation: Remove CO‚ÇÇ\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Food preservatives: Vinegar\n‚Ä¢ Manufacturing soaps: Saponification\n‚Ä¢ Pharmaceuticals: Drug synthesis\n‚Ä¢ Industrial chemicals: Many processes\n‚Ä¢ Food industry: Flavoring, preservation\n\nCarboxylic acids are important in food, medicine, and industry.",
                    
                    "Esters - Fruity Smelling Compounds:\n\nEsters are formed by reaction of carboxylic acid with alcohol.\n\nGeneral Formula:\nR-COO-R'\n\nWhere R and R' are alkyl groups.\n\nFormation:\nAcid + Alcohol ‚Üí Ester + Water\n\nExample:\nCH‚ÇÉCOOH + C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÖOH ‚Üí CH‚ÇÉCOOC‚ÇÇH‚ÇÖ + H‚ÇÇO\n‚Ä¢ Acetic acid + Ethanol\n‚Ä¢ ‚Üí Ethyl ethanoate + Water\n\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Pleasant fruity odors\n‚Ä¢ Used in perfumes\n‚Ä¢ Used in artificial flavors\n‚Ä¢ Lower boiling points than acids\n‚Ä¢ Volatile\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ Ethyl ethanoate: Fruity smell (pineapple)\n‚Ä¢ Methyl butanoate: Apple smell\n‚Ä¢ Pentyl ethanoate: Banana smell\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Perfumes: Fragrances\n‚Ä¢ Artificial flavors: Food industry\n‚Ä¢ Solvents: Industrial use\n‚Ä¢ Plastics: Manufacturing\n‚Ä¢ Cosmetics: Fragrances\n\nNatural Occurrence:\n‚Ä¢ Fruits: Natural flavors\n‚Ä¢ Flowers: Fragrances\n‚Ä¢ Many biological compounds\n\nEsters give fruits and flowers their characteristic smells and are widely used in perfumes and flavors.",
                    
                    "Soaps and Detergents - Cleaning Agents:\n\nSoaps and detergents are cleaning agents that remove dirt and oil.\n\nSoaps:\n‚Ä¢ Salts of fatty acids (long chain carboxylic acids)\n‚Ä¢ Formed by saponification:\n  Fat/Oil + NaOH ‚Üí Soap + Glycerol\n‚Ä¢ Natural cleaning agents\n\nStructure:\n‚Ä¢ Hydrophobic tail: Water-repelling (long carbon chain)\n‚Ä¢ Hydrophilic head: Water-attracting (ionic part)\n‚Ä¢ This dual nature enables cleaning\n\nCleansing Action:\n1. Soap molecules form micelles\n2. Hydrophobic tails trap dirt and oil\n3. Hydrophilic heads face water\n4. Micelles are washed away\n5. Dirt and oil removed\n\nDetergents:\n‚Ä¢ Synthetic cleaning agents\n‚Ä¢ Similar structure to soaps\n‚Ä¢ Work in hard water (soaps don't)\n‚Ä¢ More effective in some conditions\n\nDifferences:\n‚Ä¢ Soaps: Natural, don't work in hard water\n‚Ä¢ Detergents: Synthetic, work in hard water\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Cleaning: Clothes, dishes, surfaces\n‚Ä¢ Washing: Personal hygiene\n‚Ä¢ Industrial: Manufacturing\n‚Ä¢ Household: Daily cleaning\n\nSoaps and detergents are essential for hygiene and cleanliness in modern life.",
                    
                    "Important Carbon Compounds - Summary:\n\nKey carbon compounds and their uses:\n\n1. Ethanol (C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÖOH):\n   ‚Ä¢ Alcoholic beverages\n   ‚Ä¢ Fuel (biofuel)\n   ‚Ä¢ Solvent\n   ‚Ä¢ Antiseptic\n   ‚Ä¢ Industrial chemical\n\n2. Ethanoic Acid (CH‚ÇÉCOOH):\n   ‚Ä¢ Vinegar (food)\n   ‚Ä¢ Food preservative\n   ‚Ä¢ Manufacturing soaps\n   ‚Ä¢ Industrial processes\n\n3. Soap:\n   ‚Ä¢ Cleaning agent\n   ‚Ä¢ Personal hygiene\n   ‚Ä¢ Made from fats/oils\n   ‚Ä¢ Natural surfactant\n\n4. Detergents:\n   ‚Ä¢ Synthetic cleaners\n   ‚Ä¢ Work in hard water\n   ‚Ä¢ Industrial and household use\n   ‚Ä¢ More effective than soaps\n\n5. Methanol (CH‚ÇÉOH):\n   ‚Ä¢ Fuel\n   ‚Ä¢ Industrial solvent\n   ‚Ä¢ Chemical synthesis\n\n6. Formic Acid (HCOOH):\n   ‚Ä¢ Ant stings\n   ‚Ä¢ Industrial chemical\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Essential for chemistry understanding\n‚Ä¢ Basis of organic chemistry\n‚Ä¢ Important in biology\n‚Ä¢ Used in medicine\n‚Ä¢ Daily life applications\n\nUnderstanding carbon compounds is essential for:\n‚Ä¢ Chemistry education\n‚Ä¢ Biology (life is carbon-based)\n‚Ä¢ Medicine (drugs are carbon compounds)\n‚Ä¢ Daily life (food, materials, energy)\n\nCarbon compounds form the foundation of life and modern technology."
                ),
                keyPoints = listOf(
                    "Covalent Bonding: Sharing of electrons between atoms to achieve stable octet. Forms molecules. Single bond (sharing 2 electrons), double bond (4 electrons), triple bond (6 electrons). Stronger than ionic in some cases. Examples: H‚ÇÇ (H-H), O‚ÇÇ (O=O), N‚ÇÇ (N‚â°N), H‚ÇÇO, CH‚ÇÑ. Carbon forms covalent bonds due to tetravalency.",
                    "Hydrocarbons: Compounds containing only carbon and hydrogen. Saturated: Alkanes (C‚ÇôH‚ÇÇ‚Çô‚Çä‚ÇÇ, single bonds only, e.g., CH‚ÇÑ methane, C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÜ ethane). Unsaturated: Alkenes (C‚ÇôH‚ÇÇ‚Çô, one double bond, e.g., C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÑ ethene), Alkynes (C‚ÇôH‚ÇÇ‚Çô‚Çã‚ÇÇ, one triple bond, e.g., C‚ÇÇH‚ÇÇ ethyne). Basis of organic chemistry.",
