            Chapter(
                id = "science_7",
                title = "Periodic Classification of Elements",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Modern Periodic Law - Complete Understanding:\n\nThe Modern Periodic Law states that the properties of elements are a periodic function of their atomic numbers (not atomic masses).\n\nKey Points:\n‚Ä¢ Proposed by Henry Moseley (1913)\n‚Ä¢ Based on atomic number, not atomic mass\n‚Ä¢ Atomic number = Number of protons = Number of electrons (in neutral atom)\n‚Ä¢ Removed anomalies of Mendeleev's periodic table\n\nWhy Atomic Number?\n‚Ä¢ Atomic number is more fundamental than atomic mass\n‚Ä¢ Determines the element's identity\n‚Ä¢ Explains periodicity better\n‚Ä¢ No exceptions or anomalies\n\nResult:\n‚Ä¢ Modern periodic table with 18 groups (vertical columns)\n‚Ä¢ 7 periods (horizontal rows)\n‚Ä¢ Elements with similar properties recur at regular intervals\n‚Ä¢ Systematic arrangement\n\nComparison with Mendeleev's Law:\n‚Ä¢ Mendeleev: Based on atomic mass (had anomalies)\n‚Ä¢ Modern: Based on atomic number (no anomalies)\n‚Ä¢ Modern law is more accurate and fundamental\n\nExample:\n‚Ä¢ Argon (atomic number 18) comes before Potassium (atomic number 19)\n‚Ä¢ In Mendeleev's table, this was an anomaly (Ar had higher atomic mass but came first)\n‚Ä¢ Modern table: No anomaly - arranged by atomic number\n\nThe Modern Periodic Law is the foundation of the current periodic table and explains all periodic trends accurately.",
                    
                    "Periods - Horizontal Rows:\n\nPeriods are horizontal rows in the periodic table, numbered 1 to 7.\n\nKey Characteristics:\n‚Ä¢ Elements in same period have same number of electron shells\n‚Ä¢ Period number = Number of electron shells\n‚Ä¢ Properties change gradually across a period\n\nPeriod Details:\n\nPeriod 1:\n‚Ä¢ 2 elements: Hydrogen (H), Helium (He)\n‚Ä¢ Only K shell (1 shell)\n\nPeriod 2:\n‚Ä¢ 8 elements: Li, Be, B, C, N, O, F, Ne\n‚Ä¢ K and L shells (2 shells)\n\nPeriod 3:\n‚Ä¢ 8 elements: Na, Mg, Al, Si, P, S, Cl, Ar\n‚Ä¢ K, L, M shells (3 shells)\n\nPeriod 4:\n‚Ä¢ 18 elements: K, Ca, ..., Kr\n‚Ä¢ 4 shells\n\nPeriod 5:\n‚Ä¢ 18 elements: Rb, Sr, ..., Xe\n‚Ä¢ 5 shells\n\nPeriod 6:\n‚Ä¢ 32 elements: Cs, Ba, ..., Rn\n‚Ä¢ 6 shells\n\nPeriod 7:\n‚Ä¢ Incomplete (some elements are synthetic)\n‚Ä¢ 7 shells\n\nTrends Across Period (Left to Right):\n‚Ä¢ Atomic size: Decreases\n‚Ä¢ Metallic character: Decreases\n‚Ä¢ Non-metallic character: Increases\n‚Ä¢ Ionization energy: Increases\n‚Ä¢ Electronegativity: Increases\n\nUnderstanding periods helps predict element properties and understand periodic trends.",
                    
                    "Groups - Vertical Columns:\n\nGroups are vertical columns in the periodic table, numbered 1 to 18.\n\nKey Characteristics:\n‚Ä¢ Elements in same group have same number of valence electrons\n‚Ä¢ Similar chemical properties\n‚Ä¢ Group number (for 1-2, 13-18) = Number of valence electrons\n\nImportant Groups:\n\nGroup 1 - Alkali Metals:\n‚Ä¢ Li, Na, K, Rb, Cs, Fr\n‚Ä¢ 1 valence electron\n‚Ä¢ Highly reactive\n‚Ä¢ Form +1 ions\n‚Ä¢ Soft, low density\n‚Ä¢ Good conductors\n\nGroup 2 - Alkaline Earth Metals:\n‚Ä¢ Be, Mg, Ca, Sr, Ba, Ra\n‚Ä¢ 2 valence electrons\n‚Ä¢ Form +2 ions\n‚Ä¢ Less reactive than Group 1\n‚Ä¢ Harder than Group 1\n\nGroup 17 - Halogens:\n‚Ä¢ F, Cl, Br, I, At\n‚Ä¢ 7 valence electrons\n‚Ä¢ Highly reactive non-metals\n‚Ä¢ Form -1 ions\n‚Ä¢ Diatomic molecules (F‚ÇÇ, Cl‚ÇÇ, etc.)\n‚Ä¢ Used in disinfectants\n\nGroup 18 - Noble Gases:\n‚Ä¢ He, Ne, Ar, Kr, Xe, Rn\n‚Ä¢ 8 valence electrons (except He with 2)\n‚Ä¢ Inert, stable\n‚Ä¢ Don't form compounds easily\n‚Ä¢ Used in lighting\n\nTrends Down Group (Top to Bottom):\n‚Ä¢ Atomic size: Increases\n‚Ä¢ Metallic character: Increases\n‚Ä¢ Reactivity (metals): Increases\n‚Ä¢ Reactivity (non-metals): Decreases\n\nGroups help predict chemical behavior and understand element families.",
                    
                    "Atomic Size Trends - Complete Analysis:\n\nAtomic size (atomic radius) shows clear trends in the periodic table.\n\nTrend Across Period (Left to Right):\n‚Ä¢ Atomic size DECREASES\n‚Ä¢ Reason: Increasing nuclear charge pulls electrons closer\n‚Ä¢ More protons in nucleus ‚Üí stronger attraction ‚Üí smaller size\n‚Ä¢ Example: Na (left) is larger than Cl (right) in Period 3\n\nTrend Down Group (Top to Bottom):\n‚Ä¢ Atomic size INCREASES\n‚Ä¢ Reason: Addition of new electron shells\n‚Ä¢ More shells ‚Üí electrons farther from nucleus ‚Üí larger size\n‚Ä¢ Example: Li (top) is smaller than Cs (bottom) in Group 1\n\nExtremes:\n‚Ä¢ Largest atoms: Bottom left (e.g., Francium - Fr)\n‚Ä¢ Smallest atoms: Top right (e.g., Helium - He)\n\nFactors Affecting Atomic Size:\n1. Nuclear Charge: More protons ‚Üí smaller size\n2. Number of Shells: More shells ‚Üí larger size\n3. Shielding Effect: Inner electrons shield outer electrons\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Affects chemical properties\n‚Ä¢ Determines reactivity\n‚Ä¢ Influences bonding\n‚Ä¢ Explains periodic trends\n\nExample:\n‚Ä¢ Na (Group 1, Period 3): Large atom, loses electron easily\n‚Ä¢ Cl (Group 17, Period 3): Small atom, gains electron easily\n\nUnderstanding atomic size trends helps predict element behavior and chemical properties.",
                    
                    "Metallic Character - Classification:\n\nMetallic character describes how much an element behaves like a metal.\n\nTrend Across Period (Left to Right):\n‚Ä¢ Metallic character DECREASES\n‚Ä¢ Left side: Metals (Na, Mg, Al)\n‚Ä¢ Right side: Non-metals (P, S, Cl)\n‚Ä¢ Middle: Metalloids (Si)\n\nTrend Down Group (Top to Bottom):\n‚Ä¢ Metallic character INCREASES\n‚Ä¢ Top elements: Less metallic\n‚Ä¢ Bottom elements: More metallic\n\nMetals:\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Lose electrons (form positive ions)\n‚Ä¢ Good conductors of heat and electricity\n‚Ä¢ Shiny (lustrous)\n‚Ä¢ Malleable (can be hammered)\n‚Ä¢ Ductile (can be drawn into wires)\n‚Ä¢ High melting and boiling points\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ Group 1-2: Strongly metallic\n‚Ä¢ Transition metals: Metallic\n‚Ä¢ Bottom of groups: More metallic\n\nNon-Metals:\nProperties:\n‚Ä¢ Gain electrons (form negative ions)\n‚Ä¢ Poor conductors (except graphite)\n‚Ä¢ Dull appearance\n‚Ä¢ Brittle\n‚Ä¢ Lower melting and boiling points\n\nExamples:\n‚Ä¢ Group 17: Halogens (non-metals)\n‚Ä¢ Group 18: Noble gases (non-metals)\n‚Ä¢ Top right: Strongly non-metallic\n\nMetalloids:\n‚Ä¢ Have properties of both metals and non-metals\n‚Ä¢ Examples: B, Si, Ge, As, Sb, Te\n‚Ä¢ Used in semiconductors\n\nUnderstanding metallic character helps classify elements and predict their properties.",
                    
                    "Valency - Combining Capacity:\n\nValency is the number of electrons an atom can gain, lose, or share to form bonds.\n\nDetermination:\n‚Ä¢ Based on number of valence electrons\n‚Ä¢ Valence electrons = Electrons in outermost shell\n‚Ä¢ Determines how elements combine\n\nRules:\n\nGroup 1-2 (Metals):\n‚Ä¢ Valency = Group number\n‚Ä¢ Lose electrons to achieve stability\n‚Ä¢ Example: Na (Group 1) ‚Üí Valency = 1\n‚Ä¢ Example: Mg (Group 2) ‚Üí Valency = 2\n\nGroup 13-18 (Non-metals/Metalloids):\n‚Ä¢ Valency = 18 - Group number\n‚Ä¢ Gain or share electrons to achieve octet\n‚Ä¢ Example: O (Group 16) ‚Üí Valency = 18 - 16 = 2\n‚Ä¢ Example: Cl (Group 17) ‚Üí Valency = 18 - 17 = 1\n\nSpecial Cases:\n‚Ä¢ Hydrogen: Valency = 1\n‚Ä¢ Carbon: Valency = 4 (Group 14)\n‚Ä¢ Nitrogen: Valency = 3 or 5 (Group 15)\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Writing chemical formulas\n‚Ä¢ Predicting compounds\n‚Ä¢ Understanding bonding\n‚Ä¢ Balancing equations\n\nExample:\n‚Ä¢ Sodium (valency 1) + Chlorine (valency 1) ‚Üí NaCl\n‚Ä¢ Magnesium (valency 2) + Oxygen (valency 2) ‚Üí MgO\n‚Ä¢ Carbon (valency 4) + Oxygen (valency 2) ‚Üí CO‚ÇÇ\n\nValency is fundamental for understanding how elements combine to form compounds.",
                    
                    "Electronegativity - Electron Attraction:\n\nElectronegativity is the tendency of an atom to attract electrons in a chemical bond.\n\nTrend Across Period (Left to Right):\n‚Ä¢ Electronegativity INCREASES\n‚Ä¢ Reason: Smaller atoms attract electrons more strongly\n‚Ä¢ Left: Low electronegativity (metals)\n‚Ä¢ Right: High electronegativity (non-metals)\n\nTrend Down Group (Top to Bottom):\n‚Ä¢ Electronegativity DECREASES\n‚Ä¢ Reason: Larger atoms attract electrons less strongly\n‚Ä¢ Top: Higher electronegativity\n‚Ä¢ Bottom: Lower electronegativity\n\nHighest Electronegativity:\n‚Ä¢ Fluorine (F) = 4.0 (highest)\n‚Ä¢ Used as reference point\n\nBond Type Determination:\nElectronegativity difference (ŒîEN) determines bond type:\n\n‚Ä¢ ŒîEN > 1.7: Ionic bond\n  Example: Na (0.9) and Cl (3.0) ‚Üí ŒîEN = 2.1 ‚Üí Ionic\n\n‚Ä¢ 0.4 ‚â§ ŒîEN ‚â§ 1.7: Polar covalent bond\n  Example: H (2.1) and Cl (3.0) ‚Üí ŒîEN = 0.9 ‚Üí Polar covalent\n\n‚Ä¢ ŒîEN < 0.4: Non-polar covalent bond\n  Example: H (2.1) and H (2.1) ‚Üí ŒîEN = 0 ‚Üí Non-polar\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Predict bond type\n‚Ä¢ Determine molecular polarity\n‚Ä¢ Understand chemical behavior\n‚Ä¢ Explain reactivity\n\nUnderstanding electronegativity helps predict how atoms will bond and form compounds.",
                    
                    "Ionization Energy - Electron Removal:\n\nIonization energy is the energy required to remove an electron from an atom.\n\nFirst Ionization Energy:\n‚Ä¢ Energy to remove the first electron\n‚Ä¢ Most commonly discussed\n‚Ä¢ Measured in kJ/mol\n\nTrend Across Period (Left to Right):\n‚Ä¢ Ionization energy INCREASES\n‚Ä¢ Reason: Smaller atoms hold electrons more tightly\n‚Ä¢ Harder to remove electrons from smaller atoms\n‚Ä¢ Left: Low ionization energy (easy to remove)\n‚Ä¢ Right: High ionization energy (hard to remove)\n\nTrend Down Group (Top to Bottom):\n‚Ä¢ Ionization energy DECREASES\n‚Ä¢ Reason: Larger atoms hold outer electrons less tightly\n‚Ä¢ Easier to remove electrons from larger atoms\n‚Ä¢ Top: High ionization energy\n‚Ä¢ Bottom: Low ionization energy\n\nHighest Ionization Energy:\n‚Ä¢ Noble gases (Group 18)\n‚Ä¢ Have stable electron configuration\n‚Ä¢ Don't want to lose electrons\n‚Ä¢ Very unreactive\n\nLowest Ionization Energy:\n‚Ä¢ Alkali metals (Group 1)\n‚Ä¢ Have one valence electron\n‚Ä¢ Easy to remove\n‚Ä¢ Very reactive\n\nRelationship with Reactivity:\n‚Ä¢ Low ionization energy ‚Üí High reactivity (metals)\n‚Ä¢ High ionization energy ‚Üí Low reactivity (noble gases)\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Understand reactivity\n‚Ä¢ Predict chemical behavior\n‚Ä¢ Explain periodic trends\n‚Ä¢ Determine element properties\n\nIonization energy helps explain why some elements are more reactive than others.",
                    
                    "Chemical Reactivity - Element Behavior:\n\nChemical reactivity describes how readily an element undergoes chemical reactions.\n\nMetals:\n\nTrend Down Group:\n‚Ä¢ Reactivity INCREASES\n‚Ä¢ Reason: Easier to lose electrons (lower ionization energy)\n‚Ä¢ Example: Li < Na < K < Rb < Cs (increasing reactivity)\n\nTrend Across Period:\n‚Ä¢ Reactivity DECREASES (left to right)\n‚Ä¢ Reason: Harder to lose electrons (higher ionization energy)\n‚Ä¢ Example: Na > Mg > Al (decreasing reactivity)\n\nMost Reactive Metals:\n‚Ä¢ Group 1 (Alkali metals)\n‚Ä¢ Especially Cs and Fr (bottom of group)\n‚Ä¢ React violently with water\n‚Ä¢ Stored in oil to prevent reaction\n\nNon-Metals:\n\nTrend Down Group:\n‚Ä¢ Reactivity DECREASES\n‚Ä¢ Reason: Harder to gain electrons (larger atoms)\n‚Ä¢ Example: F > Cl > Br > I (decreasing reactivity)\n\nTrend Across Period:\n‚Ä¢ Reactivity INCREASES (left to right)\n‚Ä¢ Reason: Easier to gain electrons (higher electronegativity)\n‚Ä¢ Example: C < N < O < F (increasing reactivity)\n\nMost Reactive Non-Metal:\n‚Ä¢ Fluorine (F)\n‚Ä¢ Highest electronegativity\n‚Ä¢ Reacts with almost everything\n‚Ä¢ Very dangerous\n\nReactivity Series:\n‚Ä¢ Helps predict which elements react with each other\n‚Ä¢ More reactive displaces less reactive\n‚Ä¢ Used in extraction of metals\n\nUnderstanding reactivity helps predict chemical reactions and element behavior.",
                    
                    "Uses of Periodic Table - Applications:\n\nThe periodic table is one of the most important tools in chemistry with many applications:\n\n1. Predicting Properties:\n   ‚Ä¢ Can predict properties of elements\n   ‚Ä¢ Based on position in table\n   ‚Ä¢ Helps understand element behavior\n\n2. Writing Chemical Formulas:\n   ‚Ä¢ Valency from group number\n   ‚Ä¢ Predicts how elements combine\n   ‚Ä¢ Helps balance equations\n\n3. Explaining Trends:\n   ‚Ä¢ Understand periodic patterns\n   ‚Ä¢ Predict changes in properties\n   ‚Ä¢ Explain chemical behavior\n\n4. Guiding Synthesis:\n   ‚Ä¢ Helps create new compounds\n   ‚Ä¢ Predicts reaction products\n   ‚Ä¢ Guides research\n\n5. Understanding Chemistry:\n   ‚Ä¢ Foundation of chemistry\n   ‚Ä¢ Essential for learning\n   ‚Ä¢ Organizes knowledge\n\n6. Research and Industry:\n   ‚Ä¢ Used in research\n   ‚Ä¢ Industrial applications\n   ‚Ä¢ Material development\n\n7. Teaching and Learning:\n   ‚Ä¢ Systematic organization\n   ‚Ä¢ Easy to understand\n   ‚Ä¢ Visual representation\n\n8. Classification:\n   ‚Ä¢ Groups similar elements\n   ‚Ä¢ Organizes information\n   ‚Ä¢ Makes study easier\n\nThe modern periodic table is essential for understanding chemistry and is used in all areas of science and technology."
                ),
                keyPoints = listOf(
                    "Modern Periodic Table: Arranged by atomic number (not atomic mass). 7 periods (horizontal rows), 18 groups (vertical columns). Period number = number of shells. Group number = number of valence electrons (for groups 1-2, 13-18). Based on Modern Periodic Law: Properties are periodic function of atomic number. Removed anomalies of Mendeleev's table.",
                    "Periods and Groups: Periods: 7 horizontal rows. Period 1 (2 elements), Period 2-3 (8 elements each), Period 4-5 (18 elements each), Period 6-7 (32 elements each). Groups: 18 vertical columns. Groups 1-2: s-block, Groups 13-18: p-block, Groups 3-12: d-block (transition metals). Elements in same group have similar properties.",
                    "Trends in Properties: Atomic size: Decreases left to right (increasing nuclear charge), increases top to bottom (new shell). Metallic character: Decreases left to right, increases top to bottom. Ionization energy: Increases left to right, decreases top to bottom. Electronegativity: Increases left to right, decreases top to bottom. Valency: Same in group, varies in period.",
                    "Valency and Atomic Size: Valency: Number of electrons gained/lost to achieve octet. Group 1-2: Valency = group number. Group 13-18: Valency = 18 - group number. Atomic size: Distance from nucleus to outermost shell. Measured as atomic radius. Affects chemical properties. Larger atoms lose electrons easily (more metallic).",
