    private fun getSocialScienceChapters(): List<Chapter> {
        return listOf(
            Chapter(
                id = "social_1",
                title = "The Rise of Nationalism in Europe",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Nationalism - Complete Concept:\n\nNationalism is a feeling of unity, loyalty, and devotion towards one's nation.\n\nKey Characteristics:\n‚Ä¢ Sense of belonging to a nation\n‚Ä¢ Pride in national identity\n‚Ä¢ Desire for self-governance\n‚Ä¢ Unity among people sharing common culture, language, history\n\nEmergence:\n‚Ä¢ Emerged in Europe in the 19th century\n‚Ä¢ Led to formation of modern nation-states\n‚Ä¢ Replaced old multi-ethnic empires\n‚Ä¢ Based on shared culture, language, territory\n\nNation-State:\n‚Ä¢ State where majority shares common identity\n‚Ä¢ People have sense of belonging\n‚Ä¢ Government represents the nation\n‚Ä¢ Example: France, Germany, Italy\n\nFactors Promoting Nationalism:\n‚Ä¢ Common language\n‚Ä¢ Shared history and culture\n‚Ä¢ Common territory\n‚Ä¢ Economic interests\n‚Ä¢ Political aspirations\n\nImpact:\n‚Ä¢ Positive: Unity, independence, self-determination\n‚Ä¢ Negative: Conflicts, wars, exclusion of minorities\n\nNationalism transformed Europe and shaped modern world history.",
                    
                    "French Revolution (1789) - Beginning of Modern Nationalism:\n\nThe French Revolution (1789-1799) marked the beginning of modern nationalism.\n\nKey Events:\n‚Ä¢ 1789: Storming of Bastille (July 14)\n‚Ä¢ Declaration of Rights of Man and Citizen\n‚Ä¢ Overthrow of monarchy\n‚Ä¢ Establishment of republic\n\nRevolutionary Ideas:\n‚Ä¢ Liberty: Freedom from oppression\n‚Ä¢ Equality: Equal rights for all citizens\n‚Ä¢ Fraternity: Brotherhood among people\n\nSpread of Ideas:\n‚Ä¢ Ideas spread across Europe through:\n  - French armies\n  - Revolutionary literature\n  - Educated classes\n  - Newspapers and pamphlets\n\nImpact on Europe:\n‚Ä¢ Inspired other nations\n‚Ä¢ Challenged old monarchies\n‚Ä¢ Promoted democratic ideals\n‚Ä¢ Encouraged national consciousness\n\nNational Symbols:\n‚Ä¢ Tricolor flag (red, white, blue)\n‚Ä¢ La Marseillaise (national anthem)\n‚Ä¢ Marianne (national symbol)\n\nSignificance:\n‚Ä¢ First modern nation-state based on citizenship\n‚Ä¢ People, not king, became source of power\n‚Ä¢ Model for other nations\n‚Ä¢ Foundation of modern nationalism\n\nThe French Revolution showed that people could govern themselves and inspired nationalist movements across Europe.",
                    
                    "Napoleon Bonaparte - Spreading Revolutionary Ideas:\n\nNapoleon Bonaparte (1769-1821) spread French revolutionary ideas through military conquests.\n\nRise to Power:\n‚Ä¢ Military general in French Revolution\n‚Ä¢ Became First Consul (1799)\n‚Ä¢ Crowned Emperor (1804)\n‚Ä¢ Conquered much of Europe\n\nCivil Code (1804):\n‚Ä¢ Also called Napoleonic Code\n‚Ä¢ Established:\n  - Equality before law\n  - Right to property\n  - Abolished feudalism\n  - Uniform legal system\n‚Ä¢ Applied in conquered territories\n\nAdministrative Reforms:\n‚Ä¢ Efficient bureaucracy\n‚Ä¢ Standardized weights and measures\n‚Ä¢ Improved infrastructure\n‚Ä¢ Modernized administration\n\nImpact on Europe:\n‚Ä¢ Spread French ideas:\n  - Legal equality\n  - Administrative efficiency\n  - Modern governance\n‚Ä¢ Awakened national consciousness\n‚Ä¢ Created desire for independence\n‚Ä¢ Inspired nationalist movements\n\nReaction:\n‚Ä¢ Initially welcomed (reforms)\n‚Ä¢ Later resisted (foreign rule)\n‚Ä¢ Led to nationalist uprisings\n‚Ä¢ Example: Spain, Germany, Italy\n\nDefeat:\n‚Ä¢ 1815: Battle of Waterloo\n‚Ä¢ Exiled to St. Helena\n‚Ä¢ European powers restored old order\n\nNapoleon's conquests, while imposing French rule, also spread ideas of liberty and nationalism that eventually led to demands for independence.",
                    
                    "Congress of Vienna (1815) - Restoring Old Order:\n\nThe Congress of Vienna (1814-1815) was a meeting of European powers to restore order after Napoleon's defeat.\n\nParticipants:\n‚Ä¢ Austria (Metternich)\n‚Ä¢ Britain (Castlereagh)\n‚Ä¢ Prussia (Hardenberg)\n‚Ä¢ Russia (Alexander I)\n‚Ä¢ France (Talleyrand)\n\nMain Goals:\n‚Ä¢ Restore old monarchies\n‚Ä¢ Prevent future revolutions\n‚Ä¢ Maintain balance of power\n‚Ä¢ Redraw European boundaries\n\nPrinciples:\n‚Ä¢ Legitimacy: Restore legitimate rulers\n‚Ä¢ Compensation: Reward victors\n‚Ä¢ Balance of Power: Prevent dominance\n‚Ä¢ Conservatism: Oppose change\n\nTerritorial Changes:\n‚Ä¢ France: Reduced to 1790 boundaries\n‚Ä¢ Prussia: Gained territories\n‚Ä¢ Austria: Gained Italian territories\n‚Ä¢ Russia: Gained Polish territories\n‚Ä¢ German Confederation: Created (39 states)\n\nConservative Regimes:\n‚Ä¢ Absolute monarchies restored\n‚Ä¢ Suppression of liberal ideas\n‚Ä¢ Censorship and surveillance\n‚Ä¢ Secret police\n\nImpact:\n‚Ä¢ Temporary peace\n‚Ä¢ Suppressed nationalist movements\n‚Ä¢ Created resentment\n‚Ä¢ Led to revolutions (1830, 1848)\n\nLimitations:\n‚Ä¢ Could not stop ideas\n‚Ä¢ Nationalism continued to grow\n‚Ä¢ Liberal movements emerged\n‚Ä¢ Eventually led to unification movements\n\nThe Congress tried to turn back time but could not stop the forces of nationalism and liberalism.",
                    
                    "Revolutionary Movements (1830s and 1848) - Liberal Revolutions:\n\nThe 1830s and 1848 saw widespread liberal revolutions across Europe.\n\nRevolution of 1830:\n\nFrance:\n‚Ä¢ July Revolution\n‚Ä¢ Overthrew Bourbon monarchy\n‚Ä¢ Established constitutional monarchy\n‚Ä¢ Louis Philippe became king\n\nBelgium:\n‚Ä¢ Gained independence from Netherlands\n‚Ä¢ Established constitutional monarchy\n‚Ä¢ First successful nationalist revolution\n\nPoland:\n‚Ä¢ Uprising against Russian rule\n‚Ä¢ Suppressed by Russia\n‚Ä¢ Failed but inspired others\n\nRevolution of 1848 - 'Spring of Nations':\n\nFrance:\n‚Ä¢ February Revolution\n‚Ä¢ Overthrew Louis Philippe\n‚Ä¢ Established Second Republic\n‚Ä¢ Universal male suffrage\n\nGermany:\n‚Ä¢ Liberal uprisings in various states\n‚Ä¢ Frankfurt Parliament (1848-49)\n‚Ä¢ Attempted German unification\n‚Ä¢ Failed due to divisions\n\nItaly:\n‚Ä¢ Revolutions in various Italian states\n‚Ä¢ Demanded constitutionalism\n‚Ä¢ Attempted unification\n‚Ä¢ Suppressed by Austria\n\nAustrian Empire:\n‚Ä¢ Revolutions in:\n  - Vienna (Austria)\n  - Budapest (Hungary)\n  - Prague (Czech lands)\n‚Ä¢ Demanded autonomy\n‚Ä¢ Suppressed by military\n\nCommon Demands:\n‚Ä¢ Constitutionalism\n‚Ä¢ National unification\n‚Ä¢ Democratic rights\n‚Ä¢ End of absolute monarchy\n\nOutcomes:\n‚Ä¢ Most revolutions failed\n‚Ä¢ Monarchies restored\n‚Ä¢ But ideas spread\n‚Ä¢ Paved way for later success\n\nThese revolutions showed the power of nationalist and liberal ideas, even if they failed initially.",
                    
                    "Unification of Germany - Bismarck's 'Blood and Iron':\n\nGermany was unified under Prussian leadership by Otto von Bismarck (1815-1898).\n\nBackground:\n‚Ä¢ Germany was divided into 39 states\n‚Ä¢ German Confederation (loose union)\n‚Ä¢ Austria and Prussia were rivals\n‚Ä¢ Need for economic and political unity\n\nBismarck's Policy:\n‚Ä¢ 'Blood and Iron' (military force)\n‚Ä¢ Realpolitik (practical politics)\n‚Ä¢ Use of war to achieve goals\n‚Ä¢ Exclude Austria from Germany\n\nThree Wars:\n\n1. Danish War (1864):\n   ‚Ä¢ Prussia + Austria vs Denmark\n   ‚Ä¢ Gained Schleswig-Holstein\n   ‚Ä¢ Strengthened Prussia\n\n2. Austro-Prussian War (1866):\n   ‚Ä¢ Seven Weeks' War\n   ‚Ä¢ Prussia defeated Austria\n   ‚Ä¢ Excluded Austria from Germany\n   ‚Ä¢ Created North German Confederation\n\n3. Franco-Prussian War (1870-71):\n   ‚Ä¢ Prussia vs France\n   ‚Ä¢ Prussia won decisively\n   ‚Ä¢ Captured Napoleon III\n   ‚Ä¢ Gained Alsace-Lorraine\n\nUnification (1871):\n‚Ä¢ January 18, 1871\n‚Ä¢ Hall of Mirrors, Versailles\n‚Ä¢ King William I of Prussia\n‚Ä¢ Proclaimed German Emperor\n‚Ä¢ German Empire established\n\nKey Factors:\n‚Ä¢ Prussian military strength\n‚Ä¢ Economic power (Zollverein)\n‚Ä¢ Bismarck's diplomacy\n‚Ä¢ Nationalist sentiment\n‚Ä¢ Weakness of opponents\n\nResult:\n‚Ä¢ Unified German nation-state\n‚Ä¢ Powerful European nation\n‚Ä¢ Changed European balance\n‚Ä¢ Led to World War I tensions\n\nGermany's unification transformed Europe and demonstrated the power of nationalism combined with military strength.",
                    
                    "Unification of Italy - Risorgimento:\n\nThe unification of Italy (Risorgimento) was completed by 1870.\n\nBackground:\n‚Ä¢ Italy was divided into many states\n‚Ä¢ Austrian control in north\n‚Ä¢ Papal States in center\n‚Ä¢ Spanish Bourbons in south\n‚Ä¢ Need for unity\n\nKey Leaders:\n\n1. Giuseppe Mazzini (1805-1872):\n   ‚Ä¢ 'Soul' of unification\n   ‚Ä¢ Founded Young Italy\n   ‚Ä¢ Promoted republican ideals\n   ‚Ä¢ Inspired nationalist movement\n\n2. Count Camillo di Cavour (1810-1861):\n   ‚Ä¢ Prime Minister of Piedmont-Sardinia\n   ‚Ä¢ 'Brain' of unification\n   ‚Ä¢ Diplomatic and military strategy\n   ‚Ä¢ Allied with France\n\n3. Giuseppe Garibaldi (1807-1882):\n   ‚Ä¢ 'Sword' of unification\n   ‚Ä¢ Military leader\n   ‚Ä¢ Led Red Shirts\n   ‚Ä¢ Conquered Kingdom of Two Sicilies\n\nProcess:\n\n1859-60:\n‚Ä¢ Cavour allied with France\n‚Ä¢ Defeated Austria\n‚Ä¢ Gained Lombardy\n‚Ä¢ Central states joined\n\n1860:\n‚Ä¢ Garibaldi's Expedition of the Thousand\n‚Ä¢ Conquered Sicily and Naples\n‚Ä¢ Handed over to King Victor Emmanuel II\n\n1861:\n‚Ä¢ Kingdom of Italy proclaimed\n‚Ä¢ Victor Emmanuel II became king\n‚Ä¢ Capital: Turin (later Florence)\n\n1866:\n‚Ä¢ Gained Venice (Austro-Prussian War)\n\n1870:\n‚Ä¢ Captured Rome (Franco-Prussian War)\n‚Ä¢ Completed unification\n‚Ä¢ Capital moved to Rome\n\nResult:\n‚Ä¢ Unified Italian nation-state\n‚Ä¢ Modern Italy created\n‚Ä¢ Inspired other nationalist movements\n\nItaly's unification showed that different methods (diplomacy, military, popular support) could combine to achieve national unity.",
                    
                    "Balkan Nationalism - Powder Keg of Europe:\n\nThe Balkans region saw intense nationalist movements in the 19th-20th centuries.\n\nBackground:\n‚Ä¢ Balkans: Southeast Europe\n‚Ä¢ Under Ottoman Empire control\n‚Ä¢ Multiple ethnic groups:\n  - Serbs, Croats, Bulgarians\n  - Greeks, Romanians, Albanians\n  - Various religions and languages\n\nNationalist Movements:\n\nGreece (1821-1832):\n‚Ä¢ First to gain independence\n‚Ä¢ War against Ottomans\n‚Ä¢ Supported by European powers\n‚Ä¢ Established independent kingdom\n\nSerbia:\n‚Ä¢ Gained autonomy (1815)\n‚Ä¢ Full independence (1878)\n‚Ä¢ Wanted to unite all Serbs\n‚Ä¢ Pan-Slavic movement\n\nBulgaria:\n‚Ä¢ Gained autonomy (1878)\n‚Ä¢ Full independence (1908)\n‚Ä¢ Wanted to expand territory\n\nOther Groups:\n‚Ä¢ Romanians, Albanians, Croats\n‚Ä¢ All sought independence\n‚Ä¢ Created tensions\n\nConflicts:\n‚Ä¢ Competing territorial claims\n‚Ä¢ Ethnic rivalries\n‚Ä¢ Religious differences\n‚Ä¢ Great Power interference\n\nCrisis:\n‚Ä¢ 1908: Austria annexed Bosnia\n‚Ä¢ 1912-13: Balkan Wars\n‚Ä¢ Serbia became powerful\n‚Ä¢ Austria felt threatened\n\n1914:\n‚Ä¢ Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand\n‚Ä¢ Triggered World War I\n‚Ä¢ Balkans = 'Powder Keg of Europe'\n\nImpact:\n‚Ä¢ Destabilized Europe\n‚Ä¢ Led to World War I\n‚Ä¢ Created lasting conflicts\n‚Ä¢ Still affects region today\n\nThe Balkans demonstrated how intense nationalism could lead to major conflicts.",
                    
                    "Role of Culture in Nationalism - Building National Identity:\n\nCulture played a crucial role in developing nationalist sentiments.\n\nLanguage:\n‚Ä¢ Common language = national identity\n‚Ä¢ Preserved through:\n  - Literature\n  - Education\n  - Administration\n‚Ä¢ Example: German language unification\n\nArt and Literature:\n‚Ä¢ Romanticism: Emphasized emotions, nature, folk culture\n‚Ä¢ National themes: History, heroes, legends\n‚Ä¢ Examples:\n  - German: Grimm's Fairy Tales\n  - Polish: National epics\n  - Italian: Literature of Risorgimento\n\nMusic:\n‚Ä¢ National anthems\n‚Ä¢ Folk songs\n‚Ä¢ Composers: Chopin (Poland), Verdi (Italy)\n‚Ä¢ Expressed national spirit\n\nHistory and Folklore:\n‚Ä¢ Glorious past\n‚Ä¢ National heroes\n‚Ä¢ Shared memories\n‚Ä¢ Created sense of continuity\n\nVisual Arts:\n‚Ä¢ Paintings of national scenes\n‚Ä¢ Depiction of national symbols\n‚Ä¢ Romantic landscapes\n‚Ä¢ Historical paintings\n\nEducation:\n‚Ä¢ Taught national language\n‚Ä¢ National history\n‚Ä¢ Cultural values\n‚Ä¢ Created sense of belonging\n\nPrint Culture:\n‚Ä¢ Newspapers\n‚Ä¢ Books\n‚Ä¢ Pamphlets\n‚Ä¢ Spread ideas\n‚Ä¢ Created reading public\n\nImpact:\n‚Ä¢ Created shared identity\n‚Ä¢ United diverse groups\n‚Ä¢ Inspired nationalist movements\n‚Ä¢ Strengthened national consciousness\n\nCulture was the foundation on which modern nations were built, creating emotional bonds stronger than political boundaries.",
                    
                    "Impact of Nationalism - Transformation of Europe:\n\nNationalism had profound and lasting impact on Europe and the world.\n\nPositive Impacts:\n\n1. Formation of Nation-States:\n   ‚Ä¢ Unified divided regions\n   ‚Ä¢ Created modern countries\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples: Germany, Italy\n\n2. Self-Determination:\n   ‚Ä¢ People chose their government\n   ‚Ä¢ Ended foreign domination\n   ‚Ä¢ Democratic ideals\n\n3. Economic Development:\n   ‚Ä¢ Unified markets\n   ‚Ä¢ Better infrastructure\n   ‚Ä¢ Industrial growth\n\n4. Cultural Revival:\n   ‚Ä¢ Preserved languages\n   ‚Ä¢ Promoted arts\n   ‚Ä¢ Strengthened identity\n\nNegative Impacts:\n\n1. Conflicts and Wars:\n   ‚Ä¢ Territorial disputes\n   ‚Ä¢ Ethnic tensions\n   ‚Ä¢ World War I (1914-1918)\n   ‚Ä¢ World War II (1939-1945)\n\n2. Exclusion of Minorities:\n   ‚Ä¢ Discrimination\n   ‚Ä¢ Forced assimilation\n   ‚Ä¢ Persecution\n\n3. Imperialism:\n   ‚Ä¢ National pride ‚Üí expansion\n   ‚Ä¢ Colonialism\n   ‚Ä¢ Competition for colonies\n\n4. Extreme Nationalism:\n   ‚Ä¢ Fascism (Italy, Germany)\n   ‚Ä¢ Nazism\n   ‚Ä¢ Led to Holocaust\n\nLong-term Effects:\n‚Ä¢ Shaped modern world map\n‚Ä¢ Created current nation-states\n‚Ä¢ Influenced international relations\n‚Ä¢ Still affects politics today\n\nLegacy:\n‚Ä¢ Mixed results\n‚Ä¢ Unity but also division\n‚Ä¢ Progress but also destruction\n‚Ä¢ Continues to influence world\n\nNationalism transformed Europe, creating both opportunities for unity and sources of conflict that shaped the 20th century."
