                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "First World War Impact on India - Economic Hardships:\n\nThe First World War (1914-1918) had severe impact on India.\n\nEconomic Effects:\n‚Ä¢ Increased taxes to fund war\n‚Ä¢ Forced recruitment of soldiers\n‚Ä¢ Food shortages and inflation\n‚Ä¢ Prices doubled between 1913-1918\n‚Ä¢ Economic distress for common people\n\nPolitical Effects:\n‚Ä¢ War expenses burdened India\n‚Ä¢ Promises of reforms not fulfilled\n‚Ä¢ Disappointment with British rule\n‚Ä¢ Growing discontent\n\nSocial Effects:\n‚Ä¢ Food shortages led to famines\n‚Ä¢ Forced recruitment caused resentment\n‚Ä¢ Economic hardships affected all classes\n‚Ä¢ Created conditions for mass movements\n\nBritish Promises:\n‚Ä¢ Promised self-government after war\n‚Ä¢ Promised to consider Indian demands\n‚Ä¢ But failed to deliver\n‚Ä¢ Created disillusionment\n\nResult:\n‚Ä¢ Widespread anger and frustration\n‚Ä¢ Prepared ground for mass movements\n‚Ä¢ Led to Non-Cooperation Movement\n‚Ä¢ Strengthened nationalist sentiment\n\nThe war exposed British exploitation and united Indians against colonial rule.",
                    
                    "Rowlatt Act (1919) - Repressive Law:\n\nThe Rowlatt Act was a repressive law passed by British government in 1919.\n\nProvisions:\n‚Ä¢ Gave government power to arrest without trial\n‚Ä¢ Detention without warrant\n‚Ä¢ No right to appeal\n‚Ä¢ Trials without juries\n‚Ä¢ Extended emergency powers from war\n\nPurpose:\n‚Ä¢ Suppress nationalist activities\n‚Ä¢ Prevent revolutionary movements\n‚Ä¢ Maintain British control\n‚Ä¢ Crush dissent\n\nReaction:\n‚Ä¢ Widespread protests across India\n‚Ä¢ Gandhi called for Satyagraha\n‚Ä¢ Hartals (strikes) organized\n‚Ä¢ Mass demonstrations\n‚Ä¢ Unity among different groups\n\nGandhi's Response:\n‚Ä¢ Launched Rowlatt Satyagraha\n‚Ä¢ Called for non-violent resistance\n‚Ä¢ Organized protests\n‚Ä¢ First all-India mass movement\n\nImpact:\n‚Ä¢ United Indians against British\n‚Ä¢ Showed power of mass protest\n‚Ä¢ Led to Jallianwala Bagh incident\n‚Ä¢ Strengthened nationalist movement\n\nSignificance:\n‚Ä¢ Marked beginning of mass phase\n‚Ä¢ Gandhi emerged as leader\n‚Ä¢ Showed British repression\n‚Ä¢ United different communities\n\nThe Act backfired and strengthened the freedom struggle instead of suppressing it.",
                    
                    "Jallianwala Bagh Massacre (1919) - Turning Point:\n\nThe Jallianwala Bagh Massacre was a brutal incident on April 13, 1919, in Amritsar.\n\nBackground:\n‚Ä¢ People gathered for Baisakhi festival\n‚Ä¢ Also protesting Rowlatt Act\n‚Ä¢ Peaceful gathering in enclosed garden\n‚Ä¢ General Dyer arrived with troops\n\nThe Massacre:\n‚Ä¢ General Dyer blocked only exit\n‚Ä¢ Ordered firing without warning\n‚Ä¢ Fired for 10 minutes\n‚Ä¢ 379 killed (official), 1000+ (actual)\n‚Ä¢ 1200+ injured\n‚Ä¢ No medical aid allowed\n\nAftermath:\n‚Ä¢ Martial law imposed\n‚Ä¢ Public floggings\n‚Ä¢ Crawling order (Indians had to crawl)\n‚Ä¢ Severe repression\n\nReaction:\n‚Ä¢ Nationwide shock and anger\n‚Ä¢ Rabindranath Tagore returned knighthood\n‚Ä¢ Gandhi called it 'satanic'\n‚Ä¢ Turned many against British\n\nImpact:\n‚Ä¢ Turning point in freedom struggle\n‚Ä¢ Exposed British brutality\n‚Ä¢ United Indians across communities\n‚Ä¢ Strengthened nationalist movement\n‚Ä¢ Created permanent anger\n\nSignificance:\n‚Ä¢ Showed true face of British rule\n‚Ä¢ Proved need for independence\n‚Ä¢ Inspired future movements\n‚Ä¢ Never forgotten by Indians\n\nThe massacre became a symbol of British oppression and strengthened the resolve for freedom.",
                    
                    "Non-Cooperation Movement (1920-22) - Gandhi's First Mass Movement:\n\nThe Non-Cooperation Movement was launched by Gandhi in 1920.\n\nBackground:\n‚Ä¢ Disappointment with British reforms\n‚Ä¢ Rowlatt Act and Jallianwala Bagh\n‚Ä¢ Khilafat issue\n‚Ä¢ Need for mass action\n\nProgram:\n‚Ä¢ Boycott of British goods\n‚Ä¢ Boycott of British schools and colleges\n‚Ä¢ Boycott of British courts\n‚Ä¢ Boycott of councils and elections\n‚Ä¢ Surrender of titles and honors\n‚Ä¢ Non-payment of taxes (in some areas)\n\nMethods:\n‚Ä¢ Non-violent resistance (Satyagraha)\n‚Ä¢ Mass participation\n‚Ä¢ Peaceful protests\n‚Ä¢ Swadeshi (use Indian goods)\n\nParticipation:\n‚Ä¢ Students left schools\n‚Ä¢ Lawyers gave up practice\n‚Ä¢ People boycotted foreign goods\n‚Ä¢ Widespread support\n‚Ä¢ Unity of Hindus and Muslims\n\nAchievements:\n‚Ä¢ Massive participation\n‚Ä¢ Showed power of non-violence\n‚Ä¢ United different groups\n‚Ä¢ Economic impact on British\n‚Ä¢ Strengthened Congress\n\nWithdrawal (1922):\n‚Ä¢ Chauri Chaura incident (violence)\n‚Ä¢ Gandhi called off movement\n‚Ä¢ Some leaders disagreed\n‚Ä¢ But maintained non-violence principle\n\nImpact:\n‚Ä¢ First mass movement\n‚Ä¢ Established Gandhi as leader\n‚Ä¢ Showed potential of non-violence\n‚Ä¢ Prepared for future movements\n‚Ä¢ Inspired millions\n\nThe movement demonstrated the power of mass non-violent resistance and established Gandhi's leadership.",
                    
                    "Khilafat Movement - Muslim Participation:\n\nThe Khilafat Movement (1919-1924) was a movement to protect the Ottoman Caliphate.\n\nBackground:\n‚Ä¢ Ottoman Empire defeated in WWI\n‚Ä¢ Threat to Caliphate (spiritual leader)\n‚Ä¢ Muslims worldwide concerned\n‚Ä¢ Indian Muslims wanted to protect it\n\nLeaders:\n‚Ä¢ Ali Brothers (Mohammad Ali and Shaukat Ali)\n‚Ä¢ Maulana Abul Kalam Azad\n‚Ä¢ Supported by Gandhi\n\nDemands:\n‚Ä¢ Protect Ottoman Caliphate\n‚Ä¢ Restore Turkish territories\n‚Ä¢ Maintain Caliph's authority\n\nGandhi's Support:\n‚Ä¢ Saw opportunity for Hindu-Muslim unity\n‚Ä¢ Supported Khilafat cause\n‚Ä¢ Combined with Non-Cooperation\n‚Ä¢ United front against British\n\nMethods:\n‚Ä¢ Joined Non-Cooperation Movement\n‚Ä¢ Boycott of British institutions\n‚Ä¢ Mass protests\n‚Ä¢ Non-violent resistance\n\nAchievements:\n‚Ä¢ United Hindus and Muslims\n‚Ä¢ Massive Muslim participation\n‚Ä¢ Strengthened freedom struggle\n‚Ä¢ Showed religious harmony\n\nEnd:\n‚Ä¢ Turkey abolished Caliphate (1924)\n‚Ä¢ Movement lost purpose\n‚Ä¢ But unity remained\n\nSignificance:\n‚Ä¢ Demonstrated Hindu-Muslim unity\n‚Ä¢ Showed Gandhi's inclusive approach\n‚Ä¢ Brought Muslims into mainstream\n‚Ä¢ Strengthened nationalist movement\n\nThe Khilafat Movement, while ultimately unsuccessful in its goal, achieved lasting Hindu-Muslim unity in the freedom struggle.",
                    
                    "Civil Disobedience Movement (1930) - Salt March:\n\nThe Civil Disobedience Movement (1930-1934) was a major mass movement led by Gandhi.\n\nBackground:\n‚Ä¢ Disappointment with Simon Commission\n‚Ä¢ Demand for complete independence\n‚Ä¢ Need for direct action\n‚Ä¢ Salt tax as symbol of oppression\n\nSalt March (Dandi March):\n‚Ä¢ March 12 - April 6, 1930\n‚Ä¢ Gandhi and 78 followers\n‚Ä¢ From Sabarmati Ashram to Dandi\n‚Ä¢ 240 miles, 24 days\n‚Ä¢ Breaking salt law at Dandi\n\nProgram:\n‚Ä¢ Breaking salt law\n‚Ä¢ Boycott of foreign goods\n‚Ä¢ Non-payment of taxes\n‚Ä¢ Resignation from government posts\n‚Ä¢ Peaceful violation of laws\n\nMass Participation:\n‚Ä¢ Millions participated\n‚Ä¢ Across all regions\n‚Ä¢ All communities\n‚Ä¢ Women's participation\n‚Ä¢ Students, peasants, workers\n\nMethods:\n‚Ä¢ Making salt illegally\n‚Ä¢ Picketing shops\n‚Ä¢ Peaceful protests\n‚Ä¢ Non-violent resistance\n‚Ä¢ Civil disobedience\n\nGovernment Response:\n‚Ä¢ Mass arrests (60,000+)\n‚Ä¢ Repression\n‚Ä¢ Gandhi arrested\n‚Ä¢ But movement continued\n\nAchievements:\n‚Ä¢ Showed power of non-violence\n‚Ä¢ International attention\n‚Ä¢ Strengthened Congress\n‚Ä¢ Proved mass support\n‚Ä¢ Inspired future movements\n\nImpact:\n‚Ä¢ Most successful mass movement\n‚Ä¢ Established Gandhi's methods\n‚Ä¢ Showed Indian unity\n‚Ä¢ Paved way for independence\n\nThe Salt March became an iconic symbol of non-violent resistance and inspired movements worldwide.",
                    
                    "Quit India Movement (1942) - 'Do or Die':\n\nThe Quit India Movement (1942) was the final mass movement for independence.\n\nBackground:\n‚Ä¢ Failure of Cripps Mission (1942)\n‚Ä¢ British refusal to grant independence\n‚Ä¢ WWII context\n‚Ä¢ Need for immediate action\n\nGandhi's Call:\n‚Ä¢ 'Do or Die' (Karo ya Maro)\n‚Ä¢ August 8, 1942\n‚Ä¢ 'Quit India' resolution\n‚Ä¢ Complete independence demand\n\nProgram:\n‚Ä¢ Mass protests\n‚Ä¢ Non-violent resistance\n‚Ä¢ Disruption of British administration\n‚Ä¢ Workers' strikes\n‚Ä¢ Students' participation\n\nMassive Protests:\n‚Ä¢ Spontaneous uprisings\n‚Ä¢ Across India\n‚Ä¢ All sections participated\n‚Ä¢ Peasants, workers, students\n‚Ä¢ Women's active role\n\nGovernment Response:\n‚Ä¢ Immediate crackdown\n‚Ä¢ Mass arrests (100,000+)\n‚Ä¢ Gandhi and leaders arrested\n‚Ä¢ Brutal repression\n‚Ä¢ Shooting on protesters\n\nUnderground Activities:\n‚Ä¢ Secret organizations\n‚Ä¢ Underground publications\n‚Ä¢ Continued resistance\n‚Ä¢ Despite repression\n\nAchievements:\n‚Ä¢ Showed determination\n‚Ä¢ Proved mass support\n‚Ä¢ Exposed British weakness\n‚Ä¢ Strengthened resolve\n‚Ä¢ Paved way for independence\n\nImpact:\n‚Ä¢ Final push for freedom\n‚Ä¢ Proved British couldn't rule\n‚Ä¢ Showed Indian unity\n‚Ä¢ Led to independence (1947)\n\nThe movement demonstrated that Indians were ready to sacrifice everything for freedom.",
                    
                    "Role of Congress - Leading Freedom Struggle:\n\nThe Indian National Congress was the main political party leading the freedom struggle.\n\nFormation (1885):\n‚Ä¢ Founded by A.O. Hume\n‚Ä¢ Initially moderate demands\n‚Ä¢ Constitutional methods\n‚Ä¢ Later became radical\n\nEvolution:\n‚Ä¢ Early phase: Petitions and prayers\n‚Ä¢ Moderate phase: Constitutional reforms\n‚Ä¢ Extremist phase: Direct action\n‚Ä¢ Gandhi phase: Mass movements\n\nLeadership:\n‚Ä¢ Dadabhai Naoroji, Gopal Krishna Gokhale (Moderates)\n‚Ä¢ Bal Gangadhar Tilak, Bipin Chandra Pal (Extremists)\n‚Ä¢ Mahatma Gandhi, Jawaharlal Nehru (Mass leaders)\n\nOrganizational Role:\n‚Ä¢ Organized mass movements\n‚Ä¢ Coordinated protests\n‚Ä¢ Represented Indian demands\n‚Ä¢ United different groups\n\nMass Movements:\n‚Ä¢ Non-Cooperation (1920-22)\n‚Ä¢ Civil Disobedience (1930-34)\n‚Ä¢ Quit India (1942)\n‚Ä¢ Led by Congress\n\nAchievements:\n‚Ä¢ United Indians\n‚Ä¢ Represented national aspirations\n‚Ä¢ Organized effective resistance\n‚Ä¢ Negotiated with British\n‚Ä¢ Led to independence\n\nChallenges:\n‚Ä¢ Communal divisions\n‚Ä¢ Different ideologies\n‚Ä¢ British repression\n‚Ä¢ But remained united\n\nLegacy:\n‚Ä¢ Main force for independence\n‚Ä¢ Established democratic traditions\n‚Ä¢ Shaped modern India\n‚Ä¢ Continues to influence politics\n\nCongress played the central role in achieving India's independence through mass mobilization and political leadership.",
                    
                    "Revolutionary Movements - Armed Resistance:\n\nRevolutionary movements used armed resistance against British rule.\n\nBackground:\n‚Ä¢ Frustration with moderate methods\n‚Ä¢ Need for direct action\n‚Ä¢ Inspired by international revolutions\n‚Ä¢ Young, educated revolutionaries\n\nKey Revolutionaries:\n\n1. Bhagat Singh (1907-1931):\n   ‚Ä¢ Hindustan Socialist Republican Association\n   ‚Ä¢ Bomb in Assembly (1929)\n   ‚Ä¢ Hungry strike in jail\n   ‚Ä¢ Executed at 23\n   ‚Ä¢ Iconic figure\n\n2. Chandrashekhar Azad (1906-1931):\n   ‚Ä¢ Leader of HSRA\n   ‚Ä¢ Never captured alive\n   ‚Ä¢ Shot himself to avoid capture\n   ‚Ä¢ Legendary revolutionary\n\n3. Others:\n   ‚Ä¢ Sukhdev, Rajguru (executed with Bhagat Singh)\n   ‚Ä¢ Ram Prasad Bismil\n   ‚Ä¢ Ashfaqulla Khan\n   ‚Ä¢ Many others\n\nMethods:\n‚Ä¢ Armed attacks\n‚Ä¢ Bomb attacks\n‚Ä¢ Assassinations\n‚Ä¢ Robberies (for funds)\n‚Ä¢ Underground activities\n\nOrganizations:\n‚Ä¢ Hindustan Socialist Republican Association\n‚Ä¢ Anushilan Samiti (Bengal)\n‚Ä¢ Ghadar Party (Punjab)\n\nImpact:\n‚Ä¢ Inspired youth\n‚Ä¢ Showed alternative path\n‚Ä¢ Created fear among British\n‚Ä¢ Strengthened nationalist sentiment\n‚Ä¢ Sacrificed lives for freedom\n\nSignificance:\n‚Ä¢ Complemented mass movements\n‚Ä¢ Showed determination\n‚Ä¢ Inspired future generations\n‚Ä¢ Part of freedom struggle\n\nRevolutionaries, while using different methods, shared the same goal of independence and inspired millions.",
                    
                    "Partition and Independence (1947) - Price of Freedom:\n\nIndia gained independence on August 15, 1947, but was partitioned into India and Pakistan.\n\nBackground:\n‚Ä¢ Mountbatten Plan (June 1947)\n‚Ä¢ Division of British India\n‚Ä¢ Two independent nations\n‚Ä¢ Based on religious lines\n\nPartition:\n‚Ä¢ India (Hindu majority)\n‚Ä¢ Pakistan (Muslim majority - East and West)\n‚Ä¢ Mass migration\n‚Ä¢ Violence and bloodshed\n‚Ä¢ Millions displaced\n\nIndependence:\n‚Ä¢ August 15, 1947\n‚Ä¢ Jawaharlal Nehru: First Prime Minister\n‚Ä¢ 'Tryst with Destiny' speech\n‚Ä¢ End of 200 years of British rule\n‚Ä¢ Beginning of new era\n\nChallenges:\n‚Ä¢ Communal violence\n‚Ä¢ Refugee crisis\n‚Ä¢ Integration of princely states\n‚Ä¢ Economic problems\n‚Ä¢ Building new nation\n\nAchievements:\n‚Ä¢ Freedom achieved\n‚Ä¢ Democratic system\n‚Ä¢ Constitution adopted (1950)\n‚Ä¢ Secular, democratic republic\n\nCost:\n‚Ä¢ Partition violence\n‚Ä¢ Millions displaced\n‚Ä¢ Lives lost\n‚Ä¢ Permanent division\n‚Ä¢ Ongoing tensions\n\nSignificance:\n‚Ä¢ End of colonial rule\n‚Ä¢ Beginning of independence\n‚Ä¢ Democratic India\n‚Ä¢ Despite challenges, success\n‚Ä¢ Inspiration for world\n\nLegacy:\n‚Ä¢ Largest democracy\n‚Ä¢ Secular nation\n‚Ä¢ Economic progress\n‚Ä¢ Global power\n‚Ä¢ Despite partition, India succeeded\n\nIndependence came at a high price, but India emerged as a strong, democratic nation committed to freedom and equality."
