                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Types of Farming - Complete Classification:\n\nDifferent types of farming based on scale, technology, and purpose.\n\n1. Primitive Subsistence Farming:\n   ‚Ä¢ Characteristics:\n     - Small plots of land\n     - Traditional tools (hoe, dao)\n     - Family labor\n     - Low productivity\n     - Mainly for family consumption\n   ‚Ä¢ Methods:\n     - Shifting cultivation (Jhumming)\n     - Slash and burn\n   ‚Ä¢ Regions: Hilly and forest areas\n\n2. Intensive Subsistence Farming:\n   ‚Ä¢ Characteristics:\n     - High labor input\n     - Small landholdings\n     - High yield per unit area\n     - Multiple crops\n     - Intensive use of land\n   ‚Ä¢ Methods:\n     - Multiple cropping\n     - Use of organic manure\n   ‚Ä¢ Regions: Densely populated areas\n\n3. Commercial Farming:\n   ‚Ä¢ Characteristics:\n     - Large scale\n     - Use of modern technology\n     - High capital investment\n     - Market-oriented\n     - High productivity\n   ‚Ä¢ Crops: Wheat, rice, cotton, sugarcane\n   ‚Ä¢ Regions: Punjab, Haryana, Western Uttar Pradesh\n\n4. Plantation Farming:\n   ‚Ä¢ Characteristics:\n     - Single crop on large area\n     - Capital intensive\n     - Scientific methods\n     - Export-oriented\n     - Processing facilities\n   ‚Ä¢ Crops: Tea, coffee, rubber, spices\n   ‚Ä¢ Regions: Assam, Kerala, Karnataka\n\nEach type serves different purposes and suits different conditions.",
                    
                    "Cropping Pattern - Three Seasons:\n\nIndia has three distinct cropping seasons based on monsoon pattern.\n\n1. Rabi Season (Winter):\n   ‚Ä¢ Sowing: October-December\n   ‚Ä¢ Harvesting: April-June\n   ‚Ä¢ Water source: Irrigation\n   ‚Ä¢ Major crops:\n     - Wheat (most important)\n     - Barley\n     - Mustard\n     - Peas\n     - Gram\n   ‚Ä¢ Regions: Punjab, Haryana, Western Uttar Pradesh\n   ‚Ä¢ Characteristics:\n     - Cool weather crops\n     - Require less water\n     - High quality grains\n\n2. Kharif Season (Monsoon):\n   ‚Ä¢ Sowing: June-July (with monsoon)\n   ‚Ä¢ Harvesting: September-October\n   ‚Ä¢ Water source: Monsoon rains\n   ‚Ä¢ Major crops:\n     - Rice (most important)\n     - Cotton\n     - Jute\n     - Maize\n     - Groundnut\n     - Soybean\n   ‚Ä¢ Regions: Eastern and Southern India\n   ‚Ä¢ Characteristics:\n     - Warm weather crops\n     - Require high rainfall\n     - Main food crops\n\n3. Zaid Season (Summer):\n   ‚Ä¢ Sowing: March-April\n   ‚Ä¢ Harvesting: May-June\n   ‚Ä¢ Water source: Irrigation\n   ‚Ä¢ Major crops:\n     - Vegetables\n     - Fruits\n     - Watermelon\n     - Cucumber\n   ‚Ä¢ Characteristics:\n     - Short duration crops\n     - High value crops\n     - Bridge between Rabi and Kharif\n\nUnderstanding cropping patterns helps in agricultural planning and food security.",
                    
                    "Major Crops - Classification:\n\nCrops are classified based on their use and economic importance.\n\n1. Food Crops:\n   ‚Ä¢ Rice:\n     - Staple food for majority\n     - Requires high rainfall\n     - Grown in: West Bengal, Punjab, Uttar Pradesh\n     - Kharif crop\n   ‚Ä¢ Wheat:\n     - Second most important food crop\n     - Rabi crop\n     - Grown in: Punjab, Haryana, Uttar Pradesh\n     - High protein content\n   ‚Ä¢ Maize:\n     - Used as food and fodder\n     - Kharif crop\n     - Grown in: Madhya Pradesh, Karnataka\n\n2. Cash Crops:\n   ‚Ä¢ Sugarcane:\n     - Source of sugar and jaggery\n     - Requires high temperature and water\n     - Grown in: Uttar Pradesh, Maharashtra\n   ‚Ä¢ Cotton:\n     - Fiber crop\n     - Kharif crop\n     - Grown in: Gujarat, Maharashtra\n     - Important for textile industry\n   ‚Ä¢ Jute:\n     - Golden fiber\n     - Grown in: West Bengal, Assam\n     - Used for sacks and bags\n\n3. Plantation Crops:\n   ‚Ä¢ Tea:\n     - Grown in: Assam, West Bengal\n     - Hill slopes\n     - Export crop\n   ‚Ä¢ Coffee:\n     - Grown in: Karnataka, Kerala\n     - Hill regions\n     - High value crop\n   ‚Ä¢ Rubber:\n     - Grown in: Kerala, Tamil Nadu\n     - Industrial use\n\nEach crop has specific requirements and economic importance.",
                    
                    "Agricultural Development - Green Revolution:\n\nThe Green Revolution significantly increased agricultural production.\n\nKey Features:\n\n1. High Yielding Variety (HYV) Seeds:\n   ‚Ä¢ Improved crop varieties\n   ‚Ä¢ Higher yield per hectare\n   ‚Ä¢ Disease resistant\n   ‚Ä¢ Shorter duration\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples: IR-8 (rice), Kalyan Sona (wheat)\n\n2. Chemical Fertilizers:\n   ‚Ä¢ NPK fertilizers\n   ‚Ä¢ Increased soil fertility\n   ‚Ä¢ Higher yields\n   ‚Ä¢ Essential nutrients\n\n3. Irrigation:\n   ‚Ä¢ Expansion of irrigation facilities\n   ‚Ä¢ Dams and canals\n   ‚Ä¢ Tube wells\n   ‚Ä¢ Reduced dependence on monsoon\n\n4. Pesticides:\n   ‚Ä¢ Control of pests and diseases\n   ‚Ä¢ Protection of crops\n   ‚Ä¢ Higher production\n\nBenefits:\n‚Ä¢ Increased food production\n‚Ä¢ Self-sufficiency in food grains\n‚Ä¢ Reduced hunger\n‚Ä¢ Economic growth\n‚Ä¢ Rural development\n\nProblems Caused:\n‚Ä¢ Environmental degradation\n‚Ä¢ Soil fertility decline\n‚Ä¢ Water pollution\n‚Ä¢ Health issues\n‚Ä¢ Loss of biodiversity\n‚Ä¢ High cost of inputs\n\nImpact:\n‚Ä¢ Transformed Indian agriculture\n‚Ä¢ Made India food secure\n‚Ä¢ But created sustainability concerns\n\nThe Green Revolution was a major milestone but needs sustainable approaches now.",
                    
                    "Problems in Agriculture - Challenges:\n\nIndian agriculture faces several challenges.\n\n1. Small Landholdings:\n   ‚Ä¢ Fragmented farms\n   ‚Ä¢ Uneconomical size\n   ‚Ä¢ Difficult to use modern technology\n   ‚Ä¢ Low productivity\n   ‚Ä¢ Inheritance division\n\n2. Lack of Irrigation:\n   ‚Ä¢ Dependence on monsoon\n   ‚Ä¢ Inadequate irrigation facilities\n   ‚Ä¢ Drought vulnerability\n   ‚Ä¢ Crop failure risk\n   ‚Ä¢ Only 40% area irrigated\n\n3. Debt:\n   ‚Ä¢ High input costs\n   ‚Ä¢ Low returns\n   ‚Ä¢ Borrowing from moneylenders\n   ‚Ä¢ High interest rates\n   ‚Ä¢ Debt trap\n   ‚Ä¢ Farmer suicides\n\n4. Low Productivity:\n   ‚Ä¢ Compared to world standards\n   ‚Ä¢ Traditional methods\n   ‚Ä¢ Lack of technology\n   ‚Ä¢ Poor infrastructure\n   ‚Ä¢ Low yield per hectare\n\n5. Market Access Issues:\n   ‚Ä¢ Middlemen exploitation\n   ‚Ä¢ Low prices to farmers\n   ‚Ä¢ Lack of storage\n   ‚Ä¢ Poor transportation\n   ‚Ä¢ No direct market access\n\n6. Other Problems:\n   ‚Ä¢ Climate change\n   ‚Ä¢ Pests and diseases\n   ‚Ä¢ Soil degradation\n   ‚Ä¢ Water scarcity\n   ‚Ä¢ Lack of credit\n\nAddressing these problems is crucial for agricultural development and farmer welfare.",
                    
                    "Reforms Needed - Solutions:\n\nVarious reforms are needed to improve agriculture.\n\n1. Land Reforms:\n   ‚Ä¢ Consolidation of holdings\n   ‚Ä¢ Tenancy reforms\n   ‚Ä¢ Land ceiling\n   ‚Ä¢ Distribution to landless\n   ‚Ä¢ Better land use\n\n2. Credit Facilities:\n   ‚Ä¢ Easy loans\n   ‚Ä¢ Low interest rates\n   ‚Ä¢ Timely credit\n   ‚Ä¢ Reduce dependence on moneylenders\n   ‚Ä¢ Kisan Credit Cards\n\n3. Technology:\n   ‚Ä¢ Modern farming methods\n   ‚Ä¢ Precision agriculture\n   ‚Ä¢ Biotechnology\n   ‚Ä¢ Information technology\n   ‚Ä¢ Better seeds and tools\n\n4. Infrastructure:\n   ‚Ä¢ Irrigation facilities\n   ‚Ä¢ Storage facilities\n   ‚Ä¢ Cold chains\n   ‚Ä¢ Transportation\n   ‚Ä¢ Market infrastructure\n\n5. Market Linkages:\n   ‚Ä¢ Direct market access\n   ‚Ä¢ Fair prices\n   ‚Ä¢ Reduce middlemen\n   ‚Ä¢ E-marketing\n   ‚Ä¢ Contract farming\n\n6. Extension Services:\n   ‚Ä¢ Agricultural education\n   ‚Ä¢ Training programs\n   ‚Ä¢ Research and development\n   ‚Ä¢ Knowledge transfer\n\n7. Insurance:\n   ‚Ä¢ Crop insurance\n   ‚Ä¢ Risk coverage\n   ‚Ä¢ Protection from losses\n\nThese reforms can transform Indian agriculture and improve farmer livelihoods.",
                    
                    "Organic Farming - Sustainable Method:\n\nOrganic farming is chemical-free farming using natural methods.\n\nPrinciples:\n‚Ä¢ No chemical fertilizers\n‚Ä¢ No pesticides\n‚Ä¢ Natural inputs only\n‚Ä¢ Sustainable practices\n‚Ä¢ Environmental protection\n\nMethods:\n\n1. Natural Fertilizers:\n   ‚Ä¢ Compost\n   ‚Ä¢ Farmyard manure\n   ‚Ä¢ Green manure\n   ‚Ä¢ Biofertilizers\n\n2. Natural Pest Control:\n   ‚Ä¢ Biological control\n   ‚Ä¢ Crop rotation\n   ‚Ä¢ Companion planting\n   ‚Ä¢ Neem and other natural pesticides\n\n3. Soil Management:\n   ‚Ä¢ Maintain soil health\n   ‚Ä¢ Organic matter\n   ‚Ä¢ Crop rotation\n   ‚Ä¢ Cover crops\n\nBenefits:\n‚Ä¢ Better for environment\n‚Ä¢ Healthier food\n‚Ä¢ Soil fertility maintained\n‚Ä¢ Biodiversity protection\n‚Ä¢ Sustainable\n‚Ä¢ Higher prices\n\nChallenges:\n‚Ä¢ Lower yields initially\n‚Ä¢ More labor intensive\n‚Ä¢ Higher costs\n‚Ä¢ Certification needed\n‚Ä¢ Market access\n\nFuture:\n‚Ä¢ Growing demand\n‚Ä¢ Health consciousness\n‚Ä¢ Environmental awareness\n‚Ä¢ Export opportunities\n‚Ä¢ Government support\n\nOrganic farming offers a sustainable alternative to chemical-intensive agriculture.",
                    
                    "Food Security - Ensuring Food for All:\n\nFood security means ensuring availability, accessibility, and affordability of food.\n\nComponents:\n\n1. Availability:\n   ‚Ä¢ Sufficient food production\n   ‚Ä¢ Adequate stocks\n   ‚Ä¢ Distribution systems\n\n2. Accessibility:\n   ‚Ä¢ Physical access\n   ‚Ä¢ Economic access\n   ‚Ä¢ Social access\n\n3. Affordability:\n   ‚Ä¢ Reasonable prices\n   ‚Ä¢ Purchasing power\n   ‚Ä¢ Subsidies if needed\n\nPublic Distribution System (PDS):\n‚Ä¢ Government program\n‚Ä¢ Provides food grains at subsidized rates\n‚Ä¢ Ration cards\n‚Ä¢ Fair price shops\n‚Ä¢ Reaches poor and needy\n‚Ä¢ Buffer stocks maintained\n\nOther Measures:\n‚Ä¢ Minimum Support Price (MSP)\n‚Ä¢ Buffer stocks\n‚Ä¢ Food for work programs\n‚Ä¢ Mid-day meal scheme\n‚Ä¢ Nutrition programs\n\nChallenges:\n‚Ä¢ Population growth\n‚Ä¢ Climate change\n‚Ä¢ Distribution issues\n‚Ä¢ Storage problems\n‚Ä¢ Corruption\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Right to food\n‚Ä¢ Reduces hunger\n‚Ä¢ Improves nutrition\n‚Ä¢ Social stability\n‚Ä¢ Human development\n\nFood security is essential for human dignity and development.",
                    
                    "Agricultural Marketing - Challenges and Solutions:\n\nAgricultural marketing involves selling farm produce.\n\nProblems:\n\n1. Storage:\n   ‚Ä¢ Inadequate storage facilities\n   ‚Ä¢ Post-harvest losses\n   ‚Ä¢ Wastage of produce\n   ‚Ä¢ Need for cold storage\n\n2. Transportation:\n   ‚Ä¢ Poor road connectivity\n   ‚Ä¢ High transport costs\n   ‚Ä¢ Damage during transport\n   ‚Ä¢ Delays\n\n3. Fair Prices:\n   ‚Ä¢ Middlemen exploitation\n   ‚Ä¢ Low prices to farmers\n   ‚Ä¢ High prices to consumers\n   ‚Ä¢ Price fluctuations\n\n4. Market Access:\n   ‚Ä¢ Limited markets\n   ‚Ä¢ No direct access\n   ‚Ä¢ Dependence on middlemen\n   ‚Ä¢ Information asymmetry\n\nSolutions:\n\n1. Storage Infrastructure:\n   ‚Ä¢ Warehouses\n   ‚Ä¢ Cold storage\n   ‚Ä¢ Silos\n   ‚Ä¢ Government support\n\n2. Transportation:\n   ‚Ä¢ Better roads\n   ‚Ä¢ Rail connectivity\n   ‚Ä¢ Refrigerated transport\n   ‚Ä¢ Reduced costs\n\n3. Market Reforms:\n   ‚Ä¢ Direct marketing\n   ‚Ä¢ E-marketing\n   ‚Ä¢ Contract farming\n   ‚Ä¢ Farmer Producer Organizations (FPOs)\n\n4. Price Support:\n   ‚Ä¢ Minimum Support Price\n   ‚Ä¢ Market intervention\n   ‚Ä¢ Price stabilization\n\nBetter marketing ensures fair returns to farmers and availability to consumers.",
                    
                    "Future of Agriculture - Sustainable Development:\n\nThe future of agriculture requires sustainable and innovative approaches.\n\n1. Sustainable Agriculture:\n   ‚Ä¢ Environmentally friendly\n   ‚Ä¢ Economically viable\n   ‚Ä¢ Socially acceptable\n   ‚Ä¢ Long-term sustainability\n   ‚Ä¢ Resource conservation\n\n2. Technology Adoption:\n   ‚Ä¢ Precision agriculture\n   ‚Ä¢ Drones and sensors\n   ‚Ä¢ Artificial intelligence\n   ‚Ä¢ Biotechnology\n   ‚Ä¢ Digital farming\n\n3. Diversification:\n   ‚Ä¢ Multiple crops\n   ‚Ä¢ Mixed farming\n   ‚Ä¢ Horticulture\n   ‚Ä¢ Animal husbandry\n   ‚Ä¢ Reduce risk\n\n4. Value Addition:\n   ‚Ä¢ Processing\n   ‚Ä¢ Packaging\n   ‚Ä¢ Branding\n   ‚Ä¢ Higher returns\n   ‚Ä¢ Employment generation\n\n5. Climate Resilience:\n   ‚Ä¢ Adapt to climate change\n   ‚Ä¢ Drought-resistant crops\n   ‚Ä¢ Water management\n   ‚Ä¢ Sustainable practices\n\n6. Organic and Natural:\n   ‚Ä¢ Growing demand\n   ‚Ä¢ Health consciousness\n   ‚Ä¢ Premium prices\n   ‚Ä¢ Export opportunities\n\n7. Digitalization:\n   ‚Ä¢ E-marketing\n   ‚Ä¢ Online platforms\n   ‚Ä¢ Information access\n   ‚Ä¢ Financial services\n\n8. Farmer Empowerment:\n   ‚Ä¢ Education and training\n   ‚Ä¢ Access to resources\n   ‚Ä¢ Collective action\n   ‚Ä¢ Policy participation\n\nThe future of agriculture lies in sustainable, technology-driven, and farmer-centric development."
