            Chapter(
                id = "social_6",
                title = "Minerals and Energy Resources",
                revisionNotes = listOf(
                    "Minerals - Natural Resources:\n\nMinerals are naturally occurring substances with definite chemical composition.\n\nCharacteristics:\n‚Ä¢ Found in rocks\n‚Ä¢ Definite chemical composition\n‚Ä¢ Inorganic origin\n‚Ä¢ Crystalline structure\n‚Ä¢ Formed over millions of years\n\nFormation:\n‚Ä¢ Igneous rocks: Formed from cooling magma\n‚Ä¢ Sedimentary rocks: Formed from sediments\n‚Ä¢ Metamorphic rocks: Formed from transformation\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Essential for industrial development\n‚Ä¢ Raw materials for industries\n‚Ä¢ Construction materials\n‚Ä¢ Economic value\n‚Ä¢ National wealth\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Manufacturing\n‚Ä¢ Construction\n‚Ä¢ Technology\n‚Ä¢ Energy production\n‚Ä¢ Daily life products\n\nMinerals are the foundation of industrial development and economic growth.",
                    
                    "Classification of Minerals:\n\nMinerals are classified based on their composition.\n\n1. Metallic Minerals:\n   ‚Ä¢ Contain metals\n   ‚Ä¢ Can be extracted\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples:\n     - Iron ore (steel production)\n     - Copper (electrical wires)\n     - Gold (jewelry, electronics)\n     - Bauxite (aluminum)\n     - Manganese (steel making)\n   ‚Ä¢ Used in industries\n   ‚Ä¢ High economic value\n\n2. Non-Metallic Minerals:\n   ‚Ä¢ Do not contain metals\n   ‚Ä¢ Various uses\n   ‚Ä¢ Examples:\n     - Limestone (cement, construction)\n     - Mica (electrical insulation)\n     - Salt (food, chemicals)\n     - Gypsum (plaster)\n     - Phosphate (fertilizers)\n   ‚Ä¢ Construction and industrial use\n\nClassification helps in:\n‚Ä¢ Understanding uses\n‚Ä¢ Extraction methods\n‚Ä¢ Economic planning\n‚Ä¢ Resource management\n\nProper classification is essential for mineral resource management.",
                    
                    "Distribution of Minerals:\n\nMinerals are unevenly distributed across the Earth.\n\nCharacteristics:\n‚Ä¢ Not found everywhere\n‚Ä¢ Concentrated in specific regions\n‚Ä¢ Geological factors determine location\n‚Ä¢ Uneven global distribution\n\nIndia's Mineral Wealth:\n‚Ä¢ Rich deposits of various minerals\n‚Ä¢ Major minerals:\n   - Iron ore\n   - Coal\n   - Bauxite\n   - Manganese\n   - Mica\n   - Limestone\n\nRegional Distribution:\n‚Ä¢ Odisha: Iron ore, coal\n‚Ä¢ Jharkhand: Coal, iron ore\n‚Ä¢ Chhattisgarh: Iron ore, coal\n‚Ä¢ Karnataka: Iron ore, gold\n‚Ä¢ Rajasthan: Zinc, lead\n\nFactors Affecting Distribution:\n‚Ä¢ Geological processes\n‚Ä¢ Rock types\n‚Ä¢ Age of rocks\n‚Ä¢ Tectonic activity\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Economic development\n‚Ä¢ Industrial location\n‚Ä¢ Regional development\n‚Ä¢ Trade\n\nUnderstanding distribution helps in planning and development.",
                    
                    "Iron Ore - Steel Industry Backbone:\n\nIron ore is the primary raw material for steel production.\n\nMajor Deposits in India:\n‚Ä¢ Odisha: Largest producer\n‚Ä¢ Jharkhand: Rich deposits\n‚Ä¢ Chhattisgarh: Significant reserves\n‚Ä¢ Karnataka: Good quality ore\n‚Ä¢ Goa: Export oriented\n\nTypes:\n\n1. Hematite:\n   ‚Ä¢ Best quality\n   ‚Ä¢ High iron content (60-70%)\n   ‚Ä¢ Reddish color\n   ‚Ä¢ Most important type\n\n2. Magnetite:\n   ‚Ä¢ Magnetic properties\n   ‚Ä¢ High iron content\n   ‚Ä¢ Black color\n   ‚Ä¢ Good quality\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Steel production (main use)\n‚Ä¢ Construction\n‚Ä¢ Manufacturing\n‚Ä¢ Infrastructure\n‚Ä¢ Export\n\nSteel Industry:\n‚Ä¢ Major consumer\n‚Ä¢ Economic importance\n‚Ä¢ Employment generation\n‚Ä¢ Industrial development\n\nProduction:\n‚Ä¢ India is major producer\n‚Ä¢ Exported to other countries\n‚Ä¢ Domestic consumption high\n‚Ä¢ Growing demand\n\nIron ore is essential for steel industry and industrial development.",
                    
                    "Coal - Main Energy Source:\n\nCoal is the main energy source and most important mineral fuel.\n\nMajor Deposits:\n‚Ä¢ Jharkhand: Largest reserves\n‚Ä¢ West Bengal: Significant deposits\n‚Ä¢ Odisha: Good reserves\n‚Ä¢ Chhattisgarh: Major producer\n‚Ä¢ Madhya Pradesh: Coal fields\n\nTypes:\n\n1. Lignite:\n   ‚Ä¢ Brown coal\n   ‚Ä¢ Low carbon content\n   ‚Ä¢ Low heat value\n   ‚Ä¢ Used in power generation\n\n2. Bituminous:\n   ‚Ä¢ Most common type\n   ‚Ä¢ Medium carbon content\n   ‚Ä¢ Good heat value\n   ‚Ä¢ Used in industries\n\n3. Anthracite:\n   ‚Ä¢ Best quality\n   ‚Ä¢ High carbon content\n   ‚Ä¢ Highest heat value\n   ‚Ä¢ Limited availability\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Power generation (main use)\n‚Ä¢ Steel production\n‚Ä¢ Cement industry\n‚Ä¢ Railway (steam engines)\n‚Ä¢ Domestic fuel\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Primary energy source\n‚Ä¢ Industrial fuel\n‚Ä¢ Economic importance\n‚Ä¢ Employment\n\nChallenges:\n‚Ä¢ Environmental pollution\n‚Ä¢ Limited reserves\n‚Ä¢ Need for alternatives\n\nCoal remains the backbone of India's energy sector.",
                    
                    "Petroleum - Liquid Gold:\n\nPetroleum is a crucial energy resource found in limited reserves.\n\nMajor Fields in India:\n‚Ä¢ Assam: Digboi, Naharkatiya\n‚Ä¢ Gujarat: Ankleshwar, Kalol\n‚Ä¢ Mumbai High: Offshore field (largest)\n‚Ä¢ Rajasthan: New discoveries\n\nRefining:\n‚Ä¢ Crude oil is refined\n‚Ä¢ Products obtained:\n   - Petrol (gasoline)\n   - Diesel\n   - Kerosene\n   - LPG (Liquefied Petroleum Gas)\n   - Lubricants\n   - Bitumen\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Transportation fuel\n‚Ä¢ Industrial fuel\n‚Ä¢ Petrochemicals\n‚Ä¢ Plastics\n‚Ä¢ Fertilizers\n\nLimitations:\n‚Ä¢ Limited reserves\n‚Ä¢ Import dependence\n‚Ä¢ Price fluctuations\n‚Ä¢ Environmental concerns\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Critical for economy\n‚Ä¢ Transportation needs\n‚Ä¢ Industrial development\n‚Ä¢ Strategic resource\n\nConservation:\n‚Ä¢ Efficient use\n‚Ä¢ Alternative fuels\n‚Ä¢ Public transport\n‚Ä¢ Energy efficiency\n\nPetroleum is essential but limited, requiring careful management and alternatives.",
                    
                    "Natural Gas - Clean Fuel:\n\nNatural gas is a clean and efficient fuel source.\n\nCharacteristics:\n‚Ä¢ Cleaner than coal and oil\n‚Ä¢ Less pollution\n‚Ä¢ Efficient burning\n‚Ä¢ Easy to transport (piped)\n\nOccurrence:\n‚Ä¢ Found with petroleum\n‚Ä¢ Associated gas\n‚Ä¢ Non-associated gas\n‚Ä¢ Offshore fields\n\nMajor Fields:\n‚Ä¢ Mumbai High\n‚Ä¢ Krishna-Godavari basin\n‚Ä¢ Assam\n‚Ä¢ Gujarat\n\nUses:\n‚Ä¢ Power generation\n‚Ä¢ Cooking (CNG, PNG)\n‚Ä¢ Industrial fuel\n‚Ä¢ Fertilizer production\n‚Ä¢ Transportation (CNG vehicles)\n\nAdvantages:\n‚Ä¢ Cleaner burning\n‚Ä¢ Less pollution\n‚Ä¢ Efficient\n‚Ä¢ Convenient\n‚Ä¢ Cost-effective\n\nCNG (Compressed Natural Gas):\n‚Ä¢ Used in vehicles\n‚Ä¢ Reduces pollution\n‚Ä¢ Cleaner alternative\n‚Ä¢ Growing use\n\nFuture:\n‚Ä¢ Growing importance\n‚Ä¢ Clean energy transition\n‚Ä¢ Infrastructure development\n‚Ä¢ Increased production\n\nNatural gas is an important clean fuel for energy transition.",
                    
                    "Electricity - Power Generation:\n\nElectricity is generated from various sources.\n\nTypes:\n\n1. Thermal Power:\n   ‚Ä¢ Coal-based\n   ‚Ä¢ Gas-based\n   ‚Ä¢ Most common\n   ‚Ä¢ Environmental concerns\n\n2. Hydroelectric:\n   ‚Ä¢ Water power\n   ‚Ä¢ Renewable\n   ‚Ä¢ Clean energy\n   ‚Ä¢ Dams required\n\n3. Nuclear:\n   ‚Ä¢ Uranium fuel\n   ‚Ä¢ High energy\n   ‚Ä¢ Limited reserves\n   ‚Ä¢ Safety concerns\n\n4. Solar:\n   ‚Ä¢ Sunlight\n   ‚Ä¢ Renewable\n   ‚Ä¢ Clean\n   ‚Ä¢ Growing rapidly\n\n5. Wind:\n   ‚Ä¢ Wind energy\n   ‚Ä¢ Renewable\n   ‚Ä¢ Clean\n   ‚Ä¢ Growing sector\n\nNeed for Renewable Energy:\n‚Ä¢ Environmental protection\n‚Ä¢ Sustainability\n‚Ä¢ Energy security\n‚Ä¢ Climate change\n‚Ä¢ Future needs\n\nChallenges:\n‚Ä¢ Growing demand\n‚Ä¢ Infrastructure\n‚Ä¢ Storage\n‚Ä¢ Cost\n\nFuture:\n‚Ä¢ Shift to renewables\n‚Ä¢ Solar and wind growth\n‚Ä¢ Energy efficiency\n‚Ä¢ Smart grids\n\nTransition to renewable energy is essential for sustainable development.",
                    
                    "Conservation of Minerals:\n\nMinerals are non-renewable resources requiring conservation.\n\nWhy Conserve:\n‚Ä¢ Non-renewable (take millions of years to form)\n‚Ä¢ Limited reserves\n‚Ä¢ Growing demand\n‚Ä¢ Future generations\n‚Ä¢ Economic value\n\nMethods:\n\n1. Efficient Use:\n   ‚Ä¢ Reduce wastage\n   ‚Ä¢ Better technology\n   ‚Ä¢ Optimize processes\n   ‚Ä¢ Maximum utilization\n\n2. Recycling:\n   ‚Ä¢ Reuse materials\n   ‚Ä¢ Metal recycling\n   ‚Ä¢ Reduce extraction\n   ‚Ä¢ Save resources\n\n3. Alternatives:\n   ‚Ä¢ Substitute materials\n   ‚Ä¢ Renewable resources\n   ‚Ä¢ New technologies\n   ‚Ä¢ Innovation\n\n4. Technology:\n   ‚Ä¢ Better extraction\n   ‚Ä¢ Efficient processing\n   ‚Ä¢ Waste reduction\n   ‚Ä¢ Modern methods\n\n5. Planning:\n   ‚Ä¢ Sustainable mining\n   ‚Ä¢ Environmental protection\n   ‚Ä¢ Long-term planning\n   ‚Ä¢ Resource management\n\nImportance:\n‚Ä¢ Ensure availability\n‚Ä¢ Protect environment\n‚Ä¢ Economic sustainability\n‚Ä¢ Future security\n\nConservation is essential for sustainable mineral resource management.",
                    
